{"title_page": "2011 Li\u00e8ge attack", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox civilian attack\n| title        = 2011 Li\u00e8ge attack\n| image        = 20100722 liege13.JPG\n| image_size   = 300px\n| alt          =\n| caption      = The bus shelter on [[Place Saint-Lambert|Saint-Lambert Square]], Li\u00e8ge; the killer was standing and killed himself on the platform on the right.<!-- needs a location marker -->\n| location     = [[Li\u00e8ge]], Belgium\n| target       = Civilians\n| coordinates  = {{coord|50|38|42|N|05|34|22|E|region:BE||display=inline}}\n| date         = Tuesday, 13 December 2011\n| time         = 12:33 ([[Central European Time|CET]])\n| timezone     = [[UTC+01:00]]\n| type         = [[Mass shooting]], [[murder\u2013suicide]]\n| fatalities   = 7 (including the perpetrator)<ref>Five deaths of the attack itself; one victim of the murder preceding the attack, plus the suicide of the attacker.</ref>\n| injuries     = 125\n| victim       =\n| perps        =\n| perp         = Nordine Amrani<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rtbf.be/info/regions/detail_liege-explosion-de-grenades-place-saint-lambert?id=7236523 |title=Fusillade \u00e0 Li\u00e8ge: quatre morts, dont l'auteur \u2013 RTBF Regions |publisher=[[RTBF]] |accessdate=13 December 2011}}</ref>\n| perpetrator  = Nordine Amrani\n| susperps     =\n| susperp      =\n| weapons      =\n* [[FN FAL]] [[battle rifle]]\n* [[Smith & Wesson Model 57]] [[revolver]]\n* Four [[M84 stun grenade]]s\n| numparts     =\n| numpart      =\n| dfens        =\n| dfen         =\n| footage      =\n}}\n\n<!--Per MOS:BOLDTITLE and WP:SBE, please do not reword this to include the article's title.-->On 13 December 2011, a [[murder\u2013suicide]] attack took place in the city of [[Li\u00e8ge]] in the [[Wallonia]] region of [[Belgium]].<ref name=tele>{{cite news|title=Belgium grenade attack kills two|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/8953449/Belgium-grenade-attack-kills-two.html|accessdate=13 December 2011|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=13 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe attacker, 33-year-old Nordine Amrani,<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite news|url=http://www.rtbf.be/info/regions/detail_liege-explosion-de-grenades-place-saint-lambert?id=7236523 |title=L'info sur RTBF \u2013 R\u00e9gions |publisher=[[RTBF]] |date=13 December 2011 |accessdate=13 December 2011}}</ref><ref name=soir>{{cite web|url=http://www.lesoir.be/regions/liege/2011-12-13/attaque-meurtriere-sur-la-place-saint-lambert-a-liege-live-883451.php |title=Li\u00e8ge : 4 morts et des dizaines de bless\u00e9s (live) |publisher=lesoir.be |accessdate=13 December 2011|language=French}}</ref> threw [[Hand grenade|grenade]]s and fired an [[FN FAL]]<ref>{{cite web |author=e-TF1 |url=http://videos.tf1.fr/jt-20h/quatre-morts-et-75-blesses-dans-une-fusillade-a-liege-6874549.html |title=Quatre morts et 75 bless\u00e9s dans une fusillade \u00e0 Li\u00e8ge \u2013 Vid\u00e9o replay du journal televise : Le journal de 20h \u2013 TF1 |publisher=Videos.tf1.fr |date=13 December 2011 |accessdate=14 December 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120108133156/http://videos.tf1.fr/jt-20h/quatre-morts-et-75-blesses-dans-une-fusillade-a-liege-6874549.html |archive-date=8 January 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> rifle at civilians on [[Place Saint-Lambert|Saint-Lambert Square]]. The attack killed six and left 125 others injured, seven of them seriously. Amrani then committed suicide by shooting himself with a revolver. Earlier that day, he had also murdered a woman in his house.\n\nThe attack occurred on the same day and at the same hour as the [[2011 Florence shootings]].\n\n== Attack ==\nThe attack took place on 13 December 2011, at 12:33 local time (11:33 [[Coordinated Universal Time|UTC]]) in [[Place Saint-Lambert|Saint-Lambert Square]], home to the [[Prince-Bishops' Palace (Li\u00e8ge)|town's courthouse]]. It was a busy day with many shoppers in the nearby [[Christmas market]].\n\nWitnesses reported four explosions and gunfire. At first, it was believed that there were two or more assailants, who threw [[stun grenades]] into the courthouse while another hurled them at a bus shelter. The gunman then fired shots with a [[7.62\u00d751mm NATO]] [[FN FAL]] from the rooftop of a bakery shop, located across the square.<ref name=tele/> Police were on the scene quickly and sealed off the square.<ref name=guardian>{{cite news|title=Belgium attack: grenades thrown at bus-stop in Li\u00e8ge \u2013 live updates|url=https://www.theguardian.com/global/blog/2011/dec/13/belgium-attack-grenades-thrown-at-bus-stop-in-liege-live-updates|accessdate=13 December 2011|newspaper=[[Guardian.co.uk]]|date=13 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nAmrani killed five people in the attack and wounded 125 others, seven seriously. After that, Amrani committed suicide by shooting himself with a [[Smith & Wesson Model 19|Smith & Wesson M57]] [[.41 Magnum]] [[revolver]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ad.nl/ad/nl/1013/Buitenland/article/detail/3074983/2011/12/13/Vier-doden-en-64-gewonden-bij-bloedige-aanslag-Luik.dhtml|title =Vier doden en 64 gewonden bij bloedige aanslag Luik|newspaper=[[Algemeen Dagblad]]|accessdate=13 December 2011|date=13 December 2011}}</ref> Two of the dead were teenage boys aged 15 and 17. A 17-month-old boy died later in a hospital.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-16161746 | title=Li\u00e8ge attack: Gunman kills three in Belgium | work=Matt Cole | date=13 December 2011 | agency=BBC News, Li\u00e8ge | accessdate=14 December 2011}}</ref> A 75-year-old woman died from her injuries two days after the attack.<ref name=soir /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.deredactie.be/permalink/1.1177092|title =Vijfde slachtoffer van schietpartij is overleden |newspaper=deredactie.be|accessdate=15 December 2011|date=15 December 2011}}</ref> A fifth victim, who had been in an induced coma since the attack, died of head injuries on 23 December.<ref>[http://www.standaard.be/artikel/detail.aspx?artikelid=DMF20111223_050 Zesde slachtoffer van Nordine Amrani overleden], ''[[De Standaard]]'' (23 December 2011)</ref>\n\n===Victims===\n*Antonietta Racano, 45, died at Amrani's apartment on 13 December\n*Mehdi Belhadj, 15, died at Saint-Lambert Square on 13 December\n*Pierre G\u00e9rouville, 17, died at Saint-Lambert Square on 13 December\n*Gabri\u00ebl Leblond, 1, died at a hospital on 13 December\n*Claudette Putzeys, 75, died at a hospital on 15 December\n*Laurent Kremer, 20, died at a hospital on 23 December\n\n== Perpetrator ==\n[[File:Nordine Amrani.jpg|thumb|Nordine Amrani]]\n\n'''Nordine Amrani''' (15 November 1978 \u2013 13 December 2011) was born in [[Ixelles|Ixelles/Elsene]] in Brussels, [[Belgium]]. He was a [[French-speaking Community of Belgium|French-speaking Belgian]] of [[Moroccan diaspora|Moroccan]] origin and a welder by trade.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-16175795 |title=Profile: Liege mass killer Nordine Amrani  |date=14 December 2011 |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=14 December 2011}}</ref> According to Amrani's lawyer, he could not speak [[Arabic language|Arabic]] nor was he [[Muslim]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Waterfield |first=Bruno |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/belgium/8956132/Liege-attacks-Belgian-gunman-Nordine-Amrani-had-grudge-against-society.html |title=Liege attacks: Belgian gunman Nordine Amrani had 'grudge against society' |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=14 December 2011 |accessdate=15 December 2011}}</ref> Amrani was known to have an interest in guns, with a history of convictions for possession of weapons.<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-16175795 | title=BBC News \u2013 Profile: Liege mass killer Nordine Amrani | date=14 December 2011 | agency=BBC News | accessdate=18 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nHe grew up near [[Brussels]], and was living with his fianc\u00e9e, a home care nurse.<ref name=\"Express girl\">{{cite web|url=http://www.express.co.uk/posts/view/289983/Liege-maniac-left-I-love-you-note-for-his-girl-before-grenade-rampage |title=Liege maniac left 'I love you' note for his girl |publisher=Express.co.uk |accessdate=2011-12-18}}</ref> Orphaned early, he was raised in foster homes.<ref name=\"nytimes1\">[https://www.nytimes.com/2011/12/15/world/europe/death-toll-rises-after-liege-belgium-attack.html Belgian Gunman, Long in Trouble With Law, Killed Before Rampage]</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Waterfield |first=Bruno |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/belgium/8956132/Liege-attacks-Belgian-gunman-Nordine-Amrani-had-grudge-against-society.html |title=Liege attacks: Belgian gunman Nordine Amrani had 'grudge against society' |work=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|accessdate=2011-12-18}}</ref>\n\nAmrani had been released from prison in October 2010. He had been convicted to a 58-month (4 years, 10 months) sentence he received from a Li\u00e8ge court in 2008. The conviction was for possession of thousands of weapons parts, almost 10,000 rounds of ammunition, dozens of weapons, including a [[rocket launcher]], [[assault rifle|assault]] and [[sniper rifle]]s, as well as 2,800 [[cannabis (drug)|cannabis]] plants, in the context of a criminal [[Conspiracy (crime)|conspiracy]] (''association de malfaiteurs''). He also had convictions for [[handling stolen goods]] and sex offences but had no known links to terror groups.<ref name=\"Express girl\"/> On the day of the attack, Amrani had been summoned for an interview with the police to answer questions about a [[sexual abuse]] case.<ref name=\"nytimes1\"/>\n\nBefore the attack, Amrani transferred money from his account to that of his girlfriend. On the morning of the attack, Amrani killed a 45-year-old woman in his apartment. The victim was working as a cleaner for Amrani's neighbour. He possibly lured her into his flat under the pretext of offering her work. After the murder, he hid her body in his shed, then left his flat for the city centre, equipped with a backpack containing the weapons.<ref>{{cite news|title=Liege attacks: body found at home of Belgium gunman|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/belgium/8955077/Liege-attacks-body-found-at-home-of-Belgium-gunman.html|accessdate=14 December 2011|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=14 December 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Reaction ==\n\n===Domestic===\nRecently appointed [[Prime Minister of Belgium]] [[Elio Di Rupo]] visited the location of the attack later in the day and described the attack as \"horrible\". He added, \"The whole country shares the pain of the families affected. We share the shock of the population.\"<ref name=bbc1/><ref>{{cite news|title=Vier doden na aanslag met granaten in centrum van Luik, 75 mensen gewond|url=http://www.demorgen.be/dm/nl/989/Binnenland/article/detail/1362239/2011/12/13/Vier-doden-na-aanslag-met-granaten-in-centrum-van-Luik-60-tal-mensen-gewond.dhtml|accessdate=13 December 2011|newspaper=De Morgen|date=13 December 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"lesoir1\">{{cite news|url=http://www.lesoir.be/regions/Li\u00e8ge/2011-12-13/attaque-meurtriere-sur-la-place-saint-lambert-a-Li\u00e8ge-live-883451.php |title=Li\u00e8ge : 4 morts et des dizaines de bless\u00e9s (live) |publisher=lesoir.be |date=13 December 2011 |accessdate=13 December 2011}}</ref> [[Albert II of Belgium|Albert II]], King of the Belgians, was shocked and visited Li\u00e8ge on the same day, along with [[Queen Paola]]. They were received by the Governor, the Prime Minister and the Lord Mayor of Li\u00e8ge. Prince Philippe, the Duke of Brabant, honoured the victims in a public ceremony later.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.clint.be/actua/binnenland/koning-en-premier-di-rupo-bezoeken-plaats-van-aanslag-luik |title=Koning en premier Di Rupo bezoeken plaats van aanslag Luik |language=Dutch |publisher=clint.be }}</ref> In the [[List of members of the Chamber of Representatives of Belgium|Chamber of Representatives of Belgium]] a minute of silence was held in honour of the victims.\n\nWilly Demeyer, the mayor of Li\u00e8ge, condemned the attack and said the attack had \"sown sorrow in the heart of the city\".<ref name=bbc1>{{cite news|title=Li\u00e8ge attack: Belgian police search for gunman motive|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-16172662|accessdate=14 December 2011|newspaper=[[BBC]]|date=14 December 2011}}</ref>\n\n=== International ===\nCondolences were expressed by the governments of Australia,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.ninemsn.com.au/national/8389695/gillard-offers-condolences-over-shooting |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120711193019/http://news.ninemsn.com.au/national/8389695/gillard-offers-condolences-over-shooting |url-status=dead |archive-date=11 July 2012 |title=Gillard offers condolences over shooting |publisher=[[ninemsn]] |date=15 December 2011 |accessdate=15 December 2011 }}</ref> [[Estonia]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.err.ee/aa8f35e0-c642-48a2-8e93-10aa8901fe13 |title=President Offers Condolences to Wounded Belgium &#124; News &#124; ERR |publisher=News |date=14 December 2011 |accessdate=15 December 2011}}</ref> [[Latvia]],<ref>{{cite web|author=Developed by mendo |url=http://www.saeima.lv/en/news/saeima-news/19155-speaker-solvita-aboltina-conveys-condolences-to-belgium |title=Latvijas Republikas Saeima \u2013 Speaker Solvita \u0100bolti\u0146a conveys condolences to Belgium |publisher=Saeima.lv |accessdate=2011-12-18}}</ref> [[Lithuania]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.topix.com/be/liege/2011/12/lithuanian-foreign-minister-sends-condolences-over-the-armed-attack-in-the-belgian-city-of-liege |title=Lithuanian Foreign Minister Sends Condolences Over the Armed Attack in the Belgian City of Li\u00e8ge |publisher=Topix |accessdate=2011-12-18}}</ref> [[Luxembourg]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/world/gunman-leaves-no-clues-to-what-sparked-killings-20111214-1ouxc.html |title=Gunman leaves no clues to what sparked killings |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=15 December 2011 |accessdate=15 December 2011}}</ref> Singapore<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/singaporelocalnews/view/1171492/1/.html |title=PM Lee sends condolences to Belgium |publisher=[[Channel NewsAsia]] |date=15 December 2011 |accessdate=16 December 2011}}</ref> and the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite web|author=Location Settings |url=http://www.news24.com/World/News/Belgian-gunman-offered-no-explanation-20111214 |title=Belgian gunman offered no explanation |publisher=[[News24]] |date=15 December 2011 |accessdate=15 December 2011}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Belgium}}\n* [[January 2015 anti-terrorism operations in Belgium]]\n* [[2018 Li\u00e8ge attack]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Liege Attack}}\n[[Category:2011 crimes in Belgium]]\n[[Category:2011 murders in Europe]]\n[[Category:Attacks in 2011]]\n[[Category:December 2011 crimes]]\n[[Category:December 2011 events in Europe]]\n[[Category:History of Li\u00e8ge|2011 Liege attack]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in 2011]]\n[[Category:Murder in Belgium]]\n[[Category:Murder\u2013suicides in Europe]]\n[[Category:Spree shootings in Belgium]]\n[[Category:Terrorist incidents in Belgium]]\n[[Category:2010s murders in Belgium]]\n[[Category:2010s mass shootings in Europe]]\n[[Category:2011 mass shootings]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox civilian attack\n| title        = 2011 Li\u00e8ge attack\n| image        = 20100722 liege13.JPG\n| image_size   = 300px\n| alt          =\n| caption      = The bus shelter on [[Place Saint-Lambert|Saint-Lambert Square]], Li\u00e8ge; the killer was standing and killed himself on the platform on the right.<!-- needs a location marker -->\n| location     = [[Li\u00e8ge]], Belgium\n| target       = Civilians\n| coordinates  = {{coord|50|38|42|N|05|34|22|E|region:BE||display=inline}}\n| date         = Tuesday, 13 December 2011\n| time         = 12:33 ([[Central European Time|CET]])\n| timezone     = [[UTC+01:00]]\n| type         = [[Mass shooting]], [[murder\u2013suicide]]\n| fatalities   = 7 (including the perpetrator)<ref>Five deaths of the attack itself; one victim of the murder preceding the attack, plus the suicide of the attacker.</ref>\n| injuries     = 125\n| victim       =\n| perps        =\n| perp         = Nordine Amrani<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rtbf.be/info/regions/detail_liege-explosion-de-grenades-place-saint-lambert?id=7236523 |title=Fusillade \u00e0 Li\u00e8ge: quatre morts, dont l'auteur \u2013 RTBF Regions |publisher=[[RTBF]] |accessdate=13 December 2011}}</ref>\n| perpetrator  = Nordine Amrani\n| susperps     =\n| susperp      =\n| weapons      =\n* [[FN FAL]] [[battle rifle]]\n* [[Smith & Wesson Model 57]] [[revolver]]\n* Four [[M84 stun grenade]]s\n| numparts     =\n| numpart      =\n| dfens        =\n| dfen         =\n| footage      =\n}}\n\n<!--Per MOS:BOLDTITLE and WP:SBE, please do not reword this to include the article's title.-->On 13 December 2011, a [[murder\u2013suicide]] attack took place in the city of [[Li\u00e8ge]] in the [[Wallonia]] region of [[Belgium]].<ref name=tele>{{cite news|title=Belgium grenade attack kills two|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/8953449/Belgium-grenade-attack-kills-two.html|accessdate=13 December 2011|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=13 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nThe attacker, 33-year-old Nordine Amrani,<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite news|url=http://www.rtbf.be/info/regions/detail_liege-explosion-de-grenades-place-saint-lambert?id=7236523 |title=L'info sur RTBF \u2013 R\u00e9gions |publisher=[[RTBF]] |date=13 December 2011 |accessdate=13 December 2011}}</ref><ref name=soir>{{cite web|url=http://www.lesoir.be/regions/liege/2011-12-13/attaque-meurtriere-sur-la-place-saint-lambert-a-liege-live-883451.php |title=Li\u00e8ge : 4 morts et des dizaines de bless\u00e9s (live) |publisher=lesoir.be |accessdate=13 December 2011|language=French}}</ref> threw [[Hand grenade|grenade]]s and fired an [[FN FAL]]<ref>{{cite web |author=e-TF1 |url=http://videos.tf1.fr/jt-20h/quatre-morts-et-75-blesses-dans-une-fusillade-a-liege-6874549.html |title=Quatre morts et 75 bless\u00e9s dans une fusillade \u00e0 Li\u00e8ge \u2013 Vid\u00e9o replay du journal televise : Le journal de 20h \u2013 TF1 |publisher=Videos.tf1.fr |date=13 December 2011 |accessdate=14 December 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120108133156/http://videos.tf1.fr/jt-20h/quatre-morts-et-75-blesses-dans-une-fusillade-a-liege-6874549.html |archive-date=8 January 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> rifle at civilians on [[Place Saint-Lambert|Saint-Lambert Square]]. The attack killed six and left 125 others injured, seven of them seriously. Amrani then committed suicide by shooting himself with a revolver. Earlier that day, he had also murdered a woman in his house.\n\nThe attack occurred on the same day and at the same hour as the [[2011 Florence shootings]].\n\n== Attack ==\nThe attack took place on 13 December 2011, at 12:33 local time (11:33 [[Coordinated Universal Time|UTC]]) in [[Place Saint-Lambert|Saint-Lambert Square]], home to the [[Prince-Bishops' Palace (Li\u00e8ge)|town's courthouse]]. It was a busy day with many shoppers in the nearby [[Christmas market]].\n\nWitnesses reported four explosions and gunfire. At first, it was believed that there were two or more assailants, who threw [[stun grenades]] into the courthouse while another hurled them at a bus shelter. The gunman then fired shots with a [[7.62\u00d751mm NATO]] [[FN FAL]] from the rooftop of a bakery shop, located across the square.<ref name=tele/> Police were on the scene quickly and sealed off the square.<ref name=guardian>{{cite news|title=Belgium attack: grenades thrown at bus-stop in Li\u00e8ge \u2013 live updates|url=https://www.theguardian.com/global/blog/2011/dec/13/belgium-attack-grenades-thrown-at-bus-stop-in-liege-live-updates|accessdate=13 December 2011|newspaper=[[Guardian.co.uk]]|date=13 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nAmrani killed five people in the attack and wounded 125 others, seven seriously. After that, Amrani committed suicide by shooting himself with a [[Smith & Wesson Model 19|Smith & Wesson M57]] [[.41 Magnum]] [[revolver]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ad.nl/ad/nl/1013/Buitenland/article/detail/3074983/2011/12/13/Vier-doden-en-64-gewonden-bij-bloedige-aanslag-Luik.dhtml|title =Vier doden en 64 gewonden bij bloedige aanslag Luik|newspaper=[[Algemeen Dagblad]]|accessdate=13 December 2011|date=13 December 2011}}</ref> Two of the dead were teenage boys aged 15 and 17. A 17-month-old boy died later in a hospital.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-16161746 | title=Li\u00e8ge attack: Gunman kills three in Belgium | work=Matt Cole | date=13 December 2011 | agency=BBC News, Li\u00e8ge | accessdate=14 December 2011}}</ref> A 75-year-old woman died from her injuries two days after the attack.<ref name=soir /><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.deredactie.be/permalink/1.1177092|title =Vijfde slachtoffer van schietpartij is overleden |newspaper=deredactie.be|accessdate=15 December 2011|date=15 December 2011}}</ref> A fifth victim, who had been in an induced coma since the attack, died of head injuries on 23 December.<ref>[http://www.standaard.be/artikel/detail.aspx?artikelid=DMF20111223_050 Zesde slachtoffer van Nordine Amrani overleden], ''[[De Standaard]]'' (23 December 2011)</ref>\n\n===Victims===\n*Antonietta Racano, 45, died at Amrani's apartment on 13 December\n*Mehdi Belhadj, 15, died at Saint-Lambert Square on 13 December\n*Pierre G\u00e9rouville, 17, died at Saint-Lambert Square on 13 December\n*Gabri\u00ebl Leblond, 1, died at a hospital on 13 December\n*Claudette Putzeys, 75, died at a hospital on 15 December\n*Laurent Kremer, 20, died at a hospital on 23 December\n\n== Perpetrator ==\n[[File:Nordine Amrani.jpg|thumb|Nordine Amrani]]\n\n'''Nordine Amrani''' (15 November 1978 \u2013 13 December 2011) was born in [[Ixelles|Ixelles/Elsene]] in Brussels, [[Belgium]]. He was a [[French-speaking Community of Belgium|French-speaking Belgian]] of [[Moroccan diaspora|Moroccan]] origin and a welder by trade.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-16175795 |title=Profile: Liege mass killer Nordine Amrani  |date=14 December 2011 |publisher=BBC News |accessdate=14 December 2011}}</ref> According to Amrani's lawyer, he could not speak [[Arabic language|Arabic]] nor was he [[Muslim]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Waterfield |first=Bruno |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/belgium/8956132/Liege-attacks-Belgian-gunman-Nordine-Amrani-had-grudge-against-society.html |title=Liege attacks: Belgian gunman Nordine Amrani had 'grudge against society' |work[[The Daily Telegraph]] |date=14 December 2011 |accessdate=15 December 2011}}</ref> Amrani was known to have an interest in guns, with a history of convictions for possession of weapons.<ref name=\"BBC\">{{cite news | url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-16175795 | title=BBC News \u2013 Profile: Liege mass killer Nordine Amrani | date=14 December 2011 | agency=BBC News | accessdate=18 December 2011}}</ref>\n\nHe grew up near [[Brussels]], and was living with his fianc\u00e9e, a home care nurse.<ref name=\"Express girl\">{{cite web|url=http://www.express.co.uk/posts/view/289983/Liege-maniac-left-I-love-you-note-for-his-girl-before-grenade-rampage |title=Liege maniac left 'I love you' note for his girl |publisher=Express.co.uk |accessdate=2011-12-18}}</ref> Orphaned early, he was raised in foster homes.<ref name=\"nytimes1\">[https://www.nytimes.com/2011/12/15/world/europe/death-toll-rises-after-liege-belgium-attack.html Belgian Gunman, Long in Trouble With Law, Killed Before Rampage]</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Waterfield |first=Bruno |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/belgium/8956132/Liege-attacks-Belgian-gunman-Nordine-Amrani-had-grudge-against-society.html |title=Liege attacks: Belgian gunman Nordine Amrani had 'grudge against society' |work[[The Daily Telegraph]]|accessdate=2011-12-18}}</ref>\n\nAmrani had been released from prison in October 2010. He had been convicted to a 58-month (4 years, 10 months) sentence he received from a Li\u00e8ge court in 2008. The conviction was for possession of thousands of weapons parts, almost 10,000 rounds of ammunition, dozens of weapons, including a [[rocket launcher]], [[assault rifle|assault]] and [[sniper rifle]]s, as well as 2,800 [[cannabis (drug)|cannabis]] plants, in the context of a criminal [[Conspiracy (crime)|conspiracy]] (''association de malfaiteurs''). He also had convictions for [[handling stolen goods]] and sex offences but had no known links to terror groups.<ref name=\"Express girl\"/> On the day of the attack, Amrani had been summoned for an interview with the police to answer questions about a [[sexual abuse]] case.<ref name=\"nytimes1\"/>\n\nBefore the attack, Amrani transferred money from his account to that of his girlfriend. On the morning of the attack, Amrani killed a 45-year-old woman in his apartment. The victim was working as a cleaner for Amrani's neighbour. He possibly lured her into his flat under the pretext of offering her work. After the murder, he hid her body in his shed, then left his flat for the city centre, equipped with a backpack containing the weapons.<ref>{{cite news|title=Liege attacks: body found at home of Belgium gunman|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/europe/belgium/8955077/Liege-attacks-body-found-at-home-of-Belgium-gunman.html|accessdate=14 December 2011|newspaper=[[The Daily Telegraph]]|date=14 December 2011}}</ref>\n\n== Reaction ==\n\n===Domestic===\nRecently appointed [[Prime Minister of Belgium]] [[Elio Di Rupo]] visited the location of the attack later in the day and described the attack as \"horrible\". He added, \"The whole country shares the pain of the families affected. We share the shock of the population.\"<ref name=bbc1/><ref>{{cite news|title=Vier doden na aanslag met granaten in centrum van Luik, 75 mensen gewond|url=http://www.demorgen.be/dm/nl/989/Binnenland/article/detail/1362239/2011/12/13/Vier-doden-na-aanslag-met-granaten-in-centrum-van-Luik-60-tal-mensen-gewond.dhtml|accessdate=13 December 2011|newspaper=De Morgen|date=13 December 2011}}</ref><ref name=\"lesoir1\">{{cite news|url=http://www.lesoir.be/regions/Li\u00e8ge/2011-12-13/attaque-meurtriere-sur-la-place-saint-lambert-a-Li\u00e8ge-live-883451.php |title=Li\u00e8ge : 4 morts et des dizaines de bless\u00e9s (live) |publisher=lesoir.be |date=13 December 2011 |accessdate=13 December 2011}}</ref> [[Albert II of Belgium|Albert II]], King of the Belgians, was shocked and visited Li\u00e8ge on the same day, along with [[Queen Paola]]. They were received by the Governor, the Prime Minister and the Lord Mayor of Li\u00e8ge. Prince Philippe, the Duke of Brabant, honoured the victims in a public ceremony later.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.clint.be/actua/binnenland/koning-en-premier-di-rupo-bezoeken-plaats-van-aanslag-luik |title=Koning en premier Di Rupo bezoeken plaats van aanslag Luik |language=Dutch |publisher=clint.be }}</ref> In the [[List of members of the Chamber of Representatives of Belgium|Chamber of Representatives of Belgium]] a minute of silence was held in honour of the victims.\n\nWilly Demeyer, the mayor of Li\u00e8ge, condemned the attack and said the attack had \"sown sorrow in the heart of the city\".<ref name=bbc1>{{cite news|title=Li\u00e8ge attack: Belgian police search for gunman motive|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-16172662|accessdate=14 December 2011|newspaper=[[BBC]]|date=14 December 2011}}</ref>\n\n=== International ===\nCondolences were expressed by the governments of Australia,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.ninemsn.com.au/national/8389695/gillard-offers-condolences-over-shooting |archive-url=https://archive.is/20120711193019/http://news.ninemsn.com.au/national/8389695/gillard-offers-condolences-over-shooting |url-status=dead |archive-date=11 July 2012 |title=Gillard offers condolences over shooting |publisher=[[ninemsn]] |date=15 December 2011 |accessdate=15 December 2011 }}</ref> [[Estonia]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.err.ee/aa8f35e0-c642-48a2-8e93-10aa8901fe13 |title=President Offers Condolences to Wounded Belgium &#124; News &#124; ERR |publisher=News |date=14 December 2011 |accessdate=15 December 2011}}</ref> [[Latvia]],<ref>{{cite web|author=Developed by mendo |url=http://www.saeima.lv/en/news/saeima-news/19155-speaker-solvita-aboltina-conveys-condolences-to-belgium |title=Latvijas Republikas Saeima \u2013 Speaker Solvita \u0100bolti\u0146a conveys condolences to Belgium |publisher=Saeima.lv |accessdate=2011-12-18}}</ref> [[Lithuania]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.topix.com/be/liege/2011/12/lithuanian-foreign-minister-sends-condolences-over-the-armed-attack-in-the-belgian-city-of-liege |title=Lithuanian Foreign Minister Sends Condolences Over the Armed Attack in the Belgian City of Li\u00e8ge |publisher=Topix |accessdate=2011-12-18}}</ref> [[Luxembourg]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.smh.com.au/world/gunman-leaves-no-clues-to-what-sparked-killings-20111214-1ouxc.html |title=Gunman leaves no clues to what sparked killings |work=[[The Sydney Morning Herald]] |date=15 December 2011 |accessdate=15 December 2011}}</ref> Singapore<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.channelnewsasia.com/stories/singaporelocalnews/view/1171492/1/.html |title=PM Lee sends condolences to Belgium |publisher=[[Channel NewsAsia]] |date=15 December 2011 |accessdate=16 December 2011}}</ref> and the United Kingdom.<ref>{{cite web|author=Location Settings |url=http://www.news24.com/World/News/Belgian-gunman-offered-no-explanation-20111214 |title=Belgian gunman offered no explanation |publisher=[[News24]] |date=15 December 2011 |accessdate=15 December 2011}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Belgium}}\n* [[2015 anti-terrorism operations in Belgium]]\n* [[2018 Li\u00e8ge attack]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Liege Attack}}\n[[Category:2011 crimes in Belgium]]\n[[Category:2011 murders in Europe]]\n[[Category:Attacks in 2011]]\n[[Category:December 2011 crimes]]\n[[Category:December 2011 events in Europe]]\n[[Category:History of Li\u00e8ge|2011 Liege attack]]\n[[Category:Mass murder in 2011]]\n[[Category:Murder in Belgium]]\n[[Category:Murder\u2013suicides in Europe]]\n[[Category:Spree shootings in Belgium]]\n[[Category:Terrorist incidents in Belgium]]\n[[Category:2010s murders in Belgium]]\n[[Category:2010s mass shootings in Europe]]\n[[Category:2011 mass shootings]]\n", "name_user": "Dawnseeker2000", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up after myself", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2011_Li%C3%A8ge_attack"}
{"title_page": "Dale Jones (American football)", "text_new": "{{short description|American football coach and former player}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n|name = Dale Jones\n|image =\n|caption =\n|current_team = Appalachian State Mountaineers\n|height_ft = 6\n|height_in = 1\n|weight_lbs = 234\n|position=[[Defensive coordinator]] <br> Inside Linebackers coach\n|number=\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1963|03|08}}\n|birth_place=[[Lee County, Virginia]]\n|death_date=\n|draftyear= 1987\n|draftround= 10\n|draftpick= 262\n|high_school = [[Bradley Central High School|Bradley Central (TN)]]\n|college= [[Tennessee Volunteers football|Tennessee]]\n|pastteams=\n* [[Dallas Cowboys]] ({{NFL Year|1987}})*\n* [[Houston Oilers]] ({{NFL Year|1987}})*\n* [[Dallas Cowboys]] ({{NFL Year|1987}})\n|pastteamsnote = yes\n|pastcoaching=\n* [[Tennessee Volunteers football|Tennessee]] (1989)<br /> ([[Graduate assistant|GA]])\n* [[Parma Panthers]] (1990)<br /> ([[Defensive coordinator|DC]])\n* [[Florida Gators football|Florida]] (1991)<br /> (Asst.)\n* [[Georgia Military College]] (1991)<br /> ([[Linebacker|LB]]/[[Defensive back|DB]])\n* [[Georgia Military College]] (1992\u20131995)<br /> ([[Defensive coordinator|DC]]/[[Linebacker|LB]]/[[Defensive back|DB]])\n* [[Appalachian State Mountaineers football|Appalachian State]] (1996\u20132004)<br /> ([[Defensive line|DL]]/[[Special teams|ST]])\n* [[Appalachian State Mountaineers football|Appalachian State]] (2005\u20132009)<br /> ([[Linebacker|LB]])\n* [[Appalachian State Mountaineers football|Appalachian State]] (2010\u20132012)<br /> ([[Defensive coordinator|DC]]/[[Linebacker|LB]])\n* [[Appalachian State Mountaineers football|Appalachian State]] (2013)<br /> ([[Defensive line|DL]])\n* [[Appalachian State Mountaineers football|Appalachian State]] (2014\u20132018)<br /> ([[Linebacker|ILB]])\n* [[Louisville Cardinals football|Louisville Cardinals]] (2019)<br /> ([[Linebacker|ILB]])\n* [[Appalachian State football|Appalachian State]] (2020\u2013present)<br/> ([[Defensive Coordinator|DC]])\n|statlabel1=Games played\n|statvalue1=3\n|statlabel2=\n|statvalue2=\n|nflnew=dalejones/2517930\n|pfr=JoneDa20\n|highlights=\n* [[Southeastern Conference|All-SEC]] ([[1985 All-SEC football team|1985]])\n* Second-team [[Southeastern Conference|All-SEC]] ([[1986 All-SEC football team|1986]])\n}}\n\n'''Marvin Dale Jones''' (born March 8, 1963) is an [[American football]] coach and former player. He is currently the [[Defensive Coordinator]] for [[Appalachian State football|Appalachian State]]. He served in various capacities for [[Appalachian State Mountaineers football|Appalachian State]] (1996-2018), including three years as [[defensive coordinator]] (2010\u20132012).  Jones previously worked as a defensive coordinator for [[Georgia Military College]] (1992\u20131996) and the [[Parma Panthers]] (1990) of the Italian American Football League.\n\nJones played [[linebacker]] at the [[University of Tennessee]], where he was a member of the  [[1985 Tennessee Volunteers football team|1985 \"Sugar Vols\" squad]], and was a [[captain (sports)|captain]] of the [[1986 Tennessee Volunteers football team|1986 team]].  He was drafted by the [[Dallas Cowboys]] in the 10th round of the [[1987 NFL Draft]], and played during the 1987 NFL strike as a replacement player.\n\n==Early years==\nJones was born in [[Lee County, VA]], the second from the youngest of 13 children.  After his family moved to [[Cleveland, Tennessee]] he attended [[Bradley Central High School]], where he was twice named All-State at [[defensive end]]. However, college recruiters had questions over his size (he weighed less than 180 pounds his senior year). For a whole summer, he would work all day on a farm in his hometown and then run six miles home at night.\n\nHe turned down a scholarship from [[Tennessee State University]] and instead chose to spend a year at the [[Tennessee Military Institute]]\u2014 a prep school\u2014 while gaining extra weight and muscle mass. Working with long-time coach Bill Dupes, Jones led the TMI squad in tackles in 1981, and was a team captain. He also gained nearly 30 pounds.<ref>\"[https://digital.lib.utk.edu/collections/footballprograms?bid=742&pg=51 1982 Squad],\" ''1982 Tennessee Volunteers Football Guide'' (University of Tennessee, 1982), p. 48.</ref><ref name=alger>\"[https://digital.lib.utk.edu/collections/footballprograms?bid=748&pg=12&s=dale%20jones Horatio Alger, Meet Tennessee's Dale Jones],\" ''1986 Tennessee Volunteers Football Guide'' (University of Tennessee, 1986), p. 10.</ref>\n\n==College career==\nJones's performance at TMI caught the attention of [[University of Tennessee]] coaches, and he was finally offered a scholarship.  He was injured prior to the 1982 season, however, and [[redshirt (college sports)|redshirted]].<ref>\"[https://digital.lib.utk.edu/collections/footballprograms?bid=198&pg=47 1983 Squad],\" ''1983 Tennessee Volunteers Football Guide'' (University of Tennessee, 1983), p. 49.</ref>\n\n===1983 season===\nHe began the [[1983 Tennessee Volunteers football team|1983 season]] as the third-string right outside linebacker, but still received playing time due to injuries to the Vols' starting linebackers. He had 6 tackles in the opener against [[Pittsburgh Panthers football|Pittsburgh]], and had two tackles-for-loss in the team's 41-34 victory over [[Alabama Crimson Tide football|Alabama]].<ref name=84bio>\"[http://diglib.lib.utk.edu/fbpro/main.php?bid=747&pg=54 1984 Squad],\" ''1984 Tennessee Volunteers Football Guide'' (University of Tennessee, 1984), pp. 52-53.</ref>\n\nHe led all players with 14 tackles in Tennessee's 30-23 victory over [[Maryland Terrapins football|Maryland]] in the 1983 [[Florida Citrus Bowl]].<ref>\"[http://www.utsports.com/sports/m-footbl/guides/2012/records.pdf Bowl Bests] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304113625/http://www.utsports.com/sports/m-footbl/guides/2012/records.pdf |date=2016-03-04 }},\" UTSports.com, p. 358.</ref>  He finished the season with 77 tackles (43 solo), 2 sacks and 7 tackles-for-loss.<ref name=83stats>\"[https://digital.lib.utk.edu/collections/footballprograms?bid=747&pg=94 1983 Defensive Statistics],\" ''1984 Tennessee Volunteers Football Guide'' (University of Tennessee, 1984), p. 92.</ref> He registered 11 \"big plays,\" second only to teammate [[Reggie White]]'s phenomenal 29.<ref name=83stats /> He was named to the Freshman All-American team by ''The Football News''.<ref name=bio />\n\n===1984 season===\nAs part of a linebacker corps that included future NFL players [[Reggie McKenzie (linebacker)|Reggie McKenzie]], [[Alvin Toles]] and [[Carl Zander]], Jones opened the [[1984 Tennessee Volunteers football team|1984 season]] with 12 tackles in Tennessee's 34-27 win over [[Washington State Cougars football|Washington State]].  In the Vols' loss to Auburn, Jones stuffed running back [[Brent Fullwood]] at the one-yard line, causing a fumble and preventing a touchdown.\n\nHe had 13 tackles in Tennessee's 28-27 win over Alabama.  He finished the season as the team's leader in \"big plays,\" with 4 sacks, 4 forced fumbles (led the team), and 7 tackles-for-loss.<ref name=85bio>\"[https://digital.lib.utk.edu/collections/footballprograms?bid=738&pg=68 1985 Squad],\" ''1985 Tennessee Volunteers Football Guide'' (University of Tennessee, 1985), p. 66.</ref>  His 109 total tackles was second only to Zander's 167.<ref>\"[https://digital.lib.utk.edu/collections/footballprograms?bid=738&pg=104 1984 Defensive Statistics],\" ''1985 Tennessee Volunteers Football Guide'' (University of Tennessee, 1985), p. 102.</ref>  He was named to the Sophomore All-American team by ''The Football News''.<ref name=85bio />\n\n===1985 season===\nJones is frequently recalled as the \"emotional leader\" of the [[1985 Tennessee Volunteers football team|1985 \"Sugar Vols\" squad]].<ref>Mike Strange, \"[http://www.govolsxtra.com/news/2005/aug/28/sweet-memories-uts-sugar-bowl-win-over-miami-was/?print=1 Sweet Memories: UT's Sugar Bowl Win Over Miami Was One for Ages],\" ''Knoxnews.com'', August 28, 2005. Retrieved: July 29, 2013.</ref><ref>\"[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1842&dat=19860824&id=eiMrAAAAIBAJ&sjid=UZ4FAAAAIBAJ&pg=2934,5308087 Veteran Defense May Allow Vols to Repeat in SEC],\" ''Florence TimesDaily'', August 24, 1986, p. 12F.</ref>  In Tennessee's 38-20 upset of #1 Auburn on September 28, Jones led a swarming defense that held eventual [[Heisman Trophy]] winner [[Bo Jackson]] to 80 yards on 17 carries (Jackson entered the game averaging over 200 yards per game for the season).<ref>\"[https://digital.lib.utk.edu/collections/footballprograms?bid=748&pg=103 Strong Finish By Top-Rated Auburn Falls Short As Vols Snap Loss Skein],\" ''1986 Tennessee Volunteers Football Guide'' (University of Tennessee, 1986), p. 100.</ref> Following the team's 17-10 loss to [[Florida Gators football|Florida]] on October 12, Jones rallied the team with a locker room speech in which he declared, \"This is the only game we're going to lose all year.\"<ref>Ron Bliss, \"[http://tricitiessports.com/kingsport-has-its-own-sugarvol-in-mark-hovanic-p6276.htm Kingsport Has Its Own SugarVol in Mark Hovanic],\" TricitiesSports.com, October 5, 2005. Retrieved: July 29, 2013.</ref>\n\nThe biggest play of Jones's career came in Tennessee's win over Alabama, which took place at [[Legion Field]] on October 19.  After Tennessee's star quarterback [[Tony Robinson (American football)|Tony Robinson]] left the game with an injury, Alabama seized the momentum and scored a touchdown to cut the lead to 16-14, and had driven into Tennessee territory for what would have been the go-ahead score, when Jones tipped a pass from quarterback [[Mike Shula]] and caught it as he fell to the ground for a drive-killing interception.<ref>\"[https://digital.lib.utk.edu/collections/footballprograms?bid=748&pg=103 Survival in Tense Fourth Quarter Allows Vols to Card Fourth in Row Over Tide],\" ''1986 Tennessee Volunteers Football Guide'' (University of Tennessee, 1986), p. 101.</ref>  Jones also recovered a fumble late in the 3rd quarter that set up Tennessee's third field goal.<ref>Broadcast of Tennessee vs. Alabama, College Football on TBS, October 19, 1985.</ref>\n\nIn Tennessee's 6-6 tie against [[Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets football|Georgia Tech]] on October 26, Jones batted away a 3rd-down pass by [[John Dewberry]] to force the Yellow Jackets to settle for a field goal early in the first quarter,<ref>Steve Baker, \"[https://apnews.com/966e09a4100f715526cdd635c639fccd Georgia Tech 6, Tennessee 6],\" AP News Archive, October 26, 1985. Retrieved: July 29, 2013.</ref> and was named \"SEC Lineman of the Week\" for his overall performance.<ref name=86bio />  In the Vols' 34-14 win over [[Ole Miss Rebels football|Ole Miss]], Jones had two third-quarter sacks, both of which forced Ole Miss to punt from their own end zone.<ref>Broadcast of Tennessee vs. Ole Miss, College Football on TBS, November 16, 1985.</ref>\n\nIn Tennessee's upset of [[Miami Hurricanes football|Miami]] in the [[1986 Sugar Bowl]], Jones had 7 tackles as a part of a defensive effort that held the Hurricanes' high-scoring offense to just 7 points.  Jones sacked Miami quarterback [[Vinny Testaverde]] twice for -38 yards, including a crucial sack late in the second quarter that forced Miami to settle for a long, unsuccessful field goal attempt.<ref name=86bio>\"[https://digital.lib.utk.edu/collections/footballprograms?bid=748&pg=70 1986 Squad],\" ''1986 Tennessee Volunteers Football Guide'' (University of Tennessee, 1986), p. 69.</ref>\n\nJones finished the 1985 season with 82 tackles (59 solo), 5 sacks, 9 tackles-for-loss, 5 forced fumbles, and 4 pass deflections. He was named All-SEC, 3rd-team All-American and SEC defensive lineman of the year honors from the Atlanta Touchdown Club.<ref name=86bio />\n\n===1986 season===\nJones was a tri-captain of Tennessee's 1986 squad, and was named to ''[[Playboy]]'''s preseason All-American team.<ref name=alger />  The Vols struggled to a 2-5 start before winning their final four games to secure a winning season.  Jones had 11 tackles (2 for minus yardage) and a fumble recovery in Tennessee's 21-14 victory over [[Minnesota Golden Gophers football|Minnesota]] in the 1986 [[Liberty Bowl]], and was named the game's \"Outstanding Defensive Player.\"<ref>\"[https://digital.lib.utk.edu/collections/footballprograms?bid=749&pg=106 1986 Comeback Capped by Stirring Liberty Bowl Win],\" ''1987 Tennessee Volunteers Football Guide'' (University of Tennessee, 1987), p. 104.</ref>\n\nJones finished the 1986 season with 88 tackles (53 solo), 4.5 sacks, and 2 tackles-for-loss.<ref>\"[https://digital.lib.utk.edu/collections/footballprograms?bid=749&pg=109 1986 Defensive Statistics],\" ''1987 Tennessee Volunteers Football Guide'' (University of Tennessee, 1987), p. 106.</ref>  He was again named All-SEC, and received All-American honorable mention by the Associated Press.<ref>\"[https://digital.lib.utk.edu/collections/footballprograms?bid=749&pg=110 1986 Honorees],\" ''1987 Tennessee Volunteers Football Guide'' (University of Tennessee, 1987), p. 108.</ref>\n\n===Records and legacy===\nDuring his four years at Tennessee, Jones amassed 349 total tackles (233 solo), 14.5 sacks, 24 tackles-for-loss, and 11 forced fumbles.<ref>[http://www.utsports.com/sports/m-footbl/fball-stats/j.htm Football Career Statistics], UTSports.com.  Retrieved: July 29, 2013.</ref>  As of the 2012 season, he was tied with [[Rico McCoy]] for 9th place on the school's career tackles list.  He is tied with [[Keith DeLong]] for seventh place in career solo tackles, and is fourth in tackles-for-loss behind [[Leonard Little]], [[Reggie White]] and [[Eric Westmoreland]].  He is second in forced fumbles behind Andy Spiva, who had 14 from 1973 to 1976.<ref>[http://www.utsports.com/sports/m-footbl/guides/2012/records.pdf Individual Football Records] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304113625/http://www.utsports.com/sports/m-footbl/guides/2012/records.pdf |date=March 4, 2016 }}, UTSports.com, 2012.  Retrieved: July 29, 2013.</ref>\n\nTennessee coach [[Johnny Majors]] described Jones as \"one of the greatest leaders I ever had.\"<ref>Mark Wiedmer, \"[http://www.timesfreepress.com/news/2011/nov/22/ex-vols-coach-majors-still-a-historic-presence/?print Ex-Vols Coach Johnny Majors Still a Historic Presence],\" ''Chattanooga Times Free Press'', November 22, 2011. Retrieved: July 29, 2013.</ref>  He stated that Jones \"personifies what college football is all about to the highest degree,\"<ref>\"[http://diglib.lib.utk.edu/fbpro/main.php?bid=748&pg=15&s=dale%20jones Majors Meets the Press],\" ''1986 Tennessee Volunteers Football Guide'' (University of Tennessee, 1986), p. 13.</ref> and noted, \"I have never seen a young man in my life that it meant more to play for one particular school than it does for Dale Jones to play at Tennessee.\"<ref name=alger />\n\nJones remains one of the best-known former Tennessee defenders, achieving what ''[[Knoxville News Sentinel]]'' reporter Mike Strange describes as \"folk-hero status\" among Vol fans.<ref>Mike Strange, \"[http://www.knoxnews.com/news/2012/sep/30/vols-were-sugar-sweet/?partner=RSS Vols Were Sugar Sweet],\" ''Knoxville News Sentinel'', September 30, 2012. Retrieved: July 29, 2013.</ref>  In a 2005 article, reporter John Painter wrote, \"Mention Dale Jones is making an appearance in Knoxville and chances are it would resemble 'Jimmy Buffett Night' in [[Key West, Florida|Key West]].  Gonna draw a crowd.\"<ref name=painter>John Painter, \"[http://www.utsports.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/102111aab.html Former Vols Linebacker Making His Mark as Coach],\" UTSports.com, October 21, 2011. Retrieved: July 29, 2013.</ref>\n\nHe was honored as a Vol \"Legend of the Game\" during Tennessee's game against Alabama on October 25, 2014.<ref>\"[https://utsports.com/news/2014/10/22/Saturday_s_VFL_Legend_Of_Game_Dale_Jones.aspx Saturday's VFL Legend of Game: Dale Jones],\" UTSports.com, October 22, 2014.</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\nJones was selected by the [[Dallas Cowboys]] in the 10th round (262nd overall) of the [[1987 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1987/04/29/NFL-Draft-List/6040546667200/ | title=NFL Draft List | accessdate=January 12, 2019}}</ref> He was waived on September 1.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/09/02/sports/transactions-906687.html?src=pm&pagewanted=1 | title=Transactions | newspaper=New York Times | date=September 2, 1987 | accessdate=January 12, 2019}}</ref> On September 2, he was claimed off waivers by the [[Houston Oilers]]. He was released on September 6.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/430985972/ | title=Transactions | newspaper=El Paso Times | date=September 7, 1987 | accessdate=January 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAfter the players went on a strike on the third week of the season, those games were canceled (reducing the 16 game season to 15) and the [[NFL]] decided that the games would be played with replacement players. Jones was re-signed to be a part of the Cowboys replacement team, that was given the mock name \"Rhinestone Cowboys\" by the media and started in three games at [[outside linebacker|left outside linebacker]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.nfl.com/player/dalejones/2517930/gamelogs | title=Dale Jones profile | publisher=NFL.com | accessdate=January 12, 2019}}</ref> Against the [[New York Jets]] on October 4, he posted 6 tackles and one fumble recovery. In the win over the [[Philadelphia Eagles]] on October 11, he recovered a fumble and returned it 26 yards to the 1 yard line.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://newspaperarchive.com/european-stars-and-stripes/1987-10-12/page-25 | title=Cowboys Roll Past Eagles 41-22 | publisher=European Stars and Stripes | page= 26 | date=October 12, 1987 | accessdate=January 12, 2019}}</ref> In the game against the [[Washington Redskins]] on October 19, a hit by Jones knocked Redskins [[quarterback]] [[Ed Rubbert]] out of the game in the second quarter, ironically, this allowed Jones's former teammate, backup quarterback [[Tony Robinson (American football)|Tony Robinson]], to enter the game and lead the Redskins to a 13-7 upset victory.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/sports/redskins/longterm/1997/history/allart/dw1987a.htm | title=Replacement Redskins Enjoy Happy Ending, 13-7 | author=Christine Brennan | newspaper=Washington Post | date=October 20, 1987 | accessdate=January 12, 2019}}</ref> He was again released after the strike ended on October 26.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/10/27/sports/transactions-111087.html | title=Transactions | newspaper=New York Times | date=October 27, 1987 | accessdate=January 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Coaching career==\nJones returned to Tennessee as a graduate assistant in 1989.  The following year, he was hired as defensive coordinator of the Italian League [[Parma Panthers]], joining former high school and college teammate Chris White.<ref name=painter />  After a year with the Panthers, he joined the [[Florida Gators football|Florida Gators]] staff as an assistant in 1991.  Later that year, he was hired as the linebackers and defensive backs coach at [[Georgia Military College]], and was promoted to defensive coordinator in 1992.<ref name=bio>Appalachian State Sports Information, \"[http://www.appstatesports.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=21500&ATCLID=1548736 Dale Jones] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150722235635/http://www.appstatesports.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=21500&ATCLID=1548736 |date=July 22, 2015 }}, July 8, 2013. Retrieved: July 29, 2013.</ref>\n\nIn 1996, Jones was hired by [[Appalachian State University|Appalachian State]] head coach [[Jerry Moore (American football, born 1939)|Jerry Moore]] as the Mountaineers' defensive line and [[special teams]] coach.  In 2005, he switched to linebackers coach.  He was elevated to defensive coordinator for the 2010 season, helping to engineer the Mountaineers' transition to a [[3-4 defense]].<ref>\"[https://www.dailypress.com/sports/virginia-tech/dp-xpm-20110902-2011-09-02-dp-spt-appalachian-state-tech-football-advance-090-20110902-story.html Virginia Tech Has Prepared for Potential Headaches from Appalachian State],\" ''Hampton Roads Daily Press'', September 2, 2011. Retrieved: July 29, 2013.</ref>  Following Moore's retirement in 2012, long-time [[Wofford Terriers football|Wofford]] assistant Nate Woody was hired as defensive coordinator as part of the new staff assembled by Moore's successor, [[Scott Satterfield]].  Jones returned to his earlier position of defensive line coach.<ref>Appalachian State Sports Information, \"[https://appstatesports.com/news/2013/1/14/205968461.aspx Nate Woody Named Defensive Coordinator],\" January 14, 2013. Retrieved: July 29, 2013.</ref>  Prior to the 2014 season, he switched to inside linebackers coach.\n\nDuring Jones's initial tenure as defensive line coach, eight of his lineman moved on to play in the NFL, six received FCS All-American honors, and 15 were All-[[Southern Conference]].  Two, Josh Jeffries (2002) and K.T. Stovall (2003), received the Southern Conference Defensive Player of the Year award.  Jones was named \"Special Teams Coordinator of the Year\" by ''American Football Monthly'' in 2002.  Players Jones has worked with at Appalachian State who would go on to play in the NFL include [[Marques Murrell]], [[D. J. Smith (American football)|D.J. Smith]], [[Demetrius McCray]], Jeremy Kimbrough and [[Jason Hunter (American football)|Jason Hunter]].<ref name=bio /><ref>Stan Crawley, \"[https://www.chattanoogan.com/2005/12/10/77107/Former-Vol-Dale-Jones-Coming-To-I-AA.aspx Former Vol Dale Jones Coming to I-AA Title Game As ASU Linebacker Coach],\" ''The Chattanoogan'', December 10, 2005. Retrieved: July 29, 2013.</ref> He also recruited punter [[Sam Martin (American football)|Sam Martin]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.espn.com/blog/nfcnorth/post/_/id/61913/sam-martin-goes-from-pizza-hut-to-the-pros | title=Sam Martin Goes from Pizza to the Pros | author=Michael Rothstein | publisher=ESPN | date=October 4, 2013 | accessdate=January 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn January 4, 2019, he followed head coach [[Scott Satterfield]] to the [[University of Louisville]] and was named the new [[linebacker|inside linebackers]] coach.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://gocards.com/news/2019/1/4/football-jones-named-inside-linebackers-coach-at-louisville.aspx | title=Jones Named Inside Linebackers Coach at Louisville | author=Rocco Gasparro | publisher=University of Louisville | date=January 4, 2019 | accessdate=January 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn January 15, 2020, Appalachian State announced that Jones had agreed to return as defensive coordinator under new head coach [[Shawn Clark]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Robinson |first1=Cameron |title=Inside linebackers coach Dale Jones leaving U of L, named App State defensive coordinator |url=https://www.courier-journal.com/story/sports/college/louisville/2020/01/15/louisville-football-linebackers-coach-dale-jones-moving-app-state/2657264001/ |accessdate=16 January 2020 |work=Louisville Courier Journal |date=15 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Cowboys1987DraftPicks}}\n{{2005 Appalachian State Mountaineers football navbox}}\n{{2006 Appalachian State Mountaineers football navbox}}\n{{2007 Appalachian State Mountaineers football navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jones, Dale}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Cleveland, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:American football linebackers]]\n[[Category:Tennessee Volunteers football players]]\n[[Category:Dallas Cowboys players]]\n[[Category:Tennessee Volunteers football coaches]]\n[[Category:Florida Gators football coaches]]\n[[Category:Appalachian State Mountaineers football coaches]]\n[[Category:Louisville Cardinals football coaches]]\n[[Category:National Football League replacement players]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American football coach and former player}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n|name = Dale Jones\n|image =\n|caption =\n|current_team = Appalachian State Mountaineers\n|height_ft = 6\n|height_in = 1\n|weight_lbs = 234\n|position=[[Defensive coordinator]] <br> Inside Linebackers coach\n|number=\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1963|03|08}}\n|birth_place=[[Lee County, Virginia]]\n|death_date=\n|draftyear= 1987\n|draftround= 10\n|draftpick= 262\n|high_school = [[Bradley Central High School|Bradley Central (TN)]]\n|college= [[Tennessee Volunteers football|Tennessee]]\n|pastteams=\n* [[Dallas Cowboys]] ({{NFL Year|1987}})*\n* [[Houston Oilers]] ({{NFL Year|1987}})*\n* [[Dallas Cowboys]] ({{NFL Year|1987}})\n|pastteamsnote = yes\n|pastcoaching=\n* [[Tennessee Volunteers football|Tennessee]] (1989)<br /> ([[Graduate assistant|GA]])\n* [[Parma Panthers]] (1990)<br /> ([[Defensive coordinator|DC]])\n* [[Florida Gators football|Florida]] (1991)<br /> (Asst.)\n* [[Georgia Military College]] (1991)<br /> ([[Linebacker|LB]]/[[Defensive back|DB]])\n* [[Georgia Military College]] (1992\u20131995)<br /> ([[Defensive coordinator|DC]]/[[Linebacker|LB]]/[[Defensive back|DB]])\n* [[Appalachian State Mountaineers football|Appalachian State]] (1996\u20132004)<br /> ([[Defensive line|DL]]/[[Special teams|ST]])\n* [[Appalachian State Mountaineers football|Appalachian State]] (2005\u20132009)<br /> ([[Linebacker|LB]])\n* [[Appalachian State Mountaineers football|Appalachian State]] (2010\u20132012)<br /> ([[Defensive coordinator|DC]]/[[Linebacker|LB]])\n* [[Appalachian State Mountaineers football|Appalachian State]] (2013)<br /> ([[Defensive line|DL]])\n* [[Appalachian State Mountaineers football|Appalachian State]] (2014\u20132018)<br /> ([[Linebacker|ILB]])\n* [[Louisville Cardinals football|Louisville Cardinals]] (2019\u20132020)<br /> ([[Linebacker|ILB]])\n* [[Appalachian State football|Appalachian State]] (2020-present)<br/> ([[Defensive Coordinator|DC]])\n|statlabel1=Games played\n|statvalue1=3\n|statlabel2=\n|statvalue2=\n|nflnew=dalejones/2517930\n|pfr=JoneDa20\n|highlights=\n* [[Southeastern Conference|All-SEC]] ([[1985 All-SEC football team|1985]])\n* Second-team [[Southeastern Conference|All-SEC]] ([[1986 All-SEC football team|1986]])\n}}\n\n'''Marvin Dale Jones''' (born March 8, 1963) is an [[American football]] coach and former player. He is currently the [[Defensive Coordinator]] for [[Appalachian State football|Appalachian State]]. He served in various capacities for [[Appalachian State Mountaineers football|Appalachian State]] (1996-2018), including three years as [[defensive coordinator]] (2010\u20132012).  Jones previously worked as a defensive coordinator for [[Georgia Military College]] (1992\u20131996) and the [[Parma Panthers]] (1990) of the Italian American Football League.\n\nJones played [[linebacker]] at the [[University of Tennessee]], where he was a member of the  [[1985 Tennessee Volunteers football team|1985 \"Sugar Vols\" squad]], and was a [[captain (sports)|captain]] of the [[1986 Tennessee Volunteers football team|1986 team]].  He was drafted by the [[Dallas Cowboys]] in the 10th round of the [[1987 NFL Draft]], and played during the 1987 NFL strike as a replacement player.\n\n==Early years==\nJones was born in [[Lee County, VA]], the second from the youngest of 13 children.  After his family moved to [[Cleveland, Tennessee]] he attended [[Bradley Central High School]], where he was twice named All-State at [[defensive end]]. However, college recruiters had questions over his size (he weighed less than 180 pounds his senior year). For a whole summer, he would work all day on a farm in his hometown and then run six miles home at night.\n\nHe turned down a scholarship from [[Tennessee State University]] and instead chose to spend a year at the [[Tennessee Military Institute]]\u2014 a prep school\u2014 while gaining extra weight and muscle mass. Working with long-time coach Bill Dupes, Jones led the TMI squad in tackles in 1981, and was a team captain. He also gained nearly 30 pounds.<ref>\"[https://digital.lib.utk.edu/collections/footballprograms?bid=742&pg=51 1982 Squad],\" ''1982 Tennessee Volunteers Football Guide'' (University of Tennessee, 1982), p. 48.</ref><ref name=alger>\"[https://digital.lib.utk.edu/collections/footballprograms?bid=748&pg=12&s=dale%20jones Horatio Alger, Meet Tennessee's Dale Jones],\" ''1986 Tennessee Volunteers Football Guide'' (University of Tennessee, 1986), p. 10.</ref>\n\n==College career==\nJones's performance at TMI caught the attention of [[University of Tennessee]] coaches, and he was finally offered a scholarship.  He was injured prior to the 1982 season, however, and [[redshirt (college sports)|redshirted]].<ref>\"[https://digital.lib.utk.edu/collections/footballprograms?bid=198&pg=47 1983 Squad],\" ''1983 Tennessee Volunteers Football Guide'' (University of Tennessee, 1983), p. 49.</ref>\n\n===1983 season===\nHe began the [[1983 Tennessee Volunteers football team|1983 season]] as the third-string right outside linebacker, but still received playing time due to injuries to the Vols' starting linebackers. He had 6 tackles in the opener against [[Pittsburgh Panthers football|Pittsburgh]], and had two tackles-for-loss in the team's 41-34 victory over [[Alabama Crimson Tide football|Alabama]].<ref name=84bio>\"[http://diglib.lib.utk.edu/fbpro/main.php?bid=747&pg=54 1984 Squad],\" ''1984 Tennessee Volunteers Football Guide'' (University of Tennessee, 1984), pp. 52-53.</ref>\n\nHe led all players with 14 tackles in Tennessee's 30-23 victory over [[Maryland Terrapins football|Maryland]] in the 1983 [[Florida Citrus Bowl]].<ref>\"[http://www.utsports.com/sports/m-footbl/guides/2012/records.pdf Bowl Bests] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304113625/http://www.utsports.com/sports/m-footbl/guides/2012/records.pdf |date=2016-03-04 }},\" UTSports.com, p. 358.</ref>  He finished the season with 77 tackles (43 solo), 2 sacks and 7 tackles-for-loss.<ref name=83stats>\"[https://digital.lib.utk.edu/collections/footballprograms?bid=747&pg=94 1983 Defensive Statistics],\" ''1984 Tennessee Volunteers Football Guide'' (University of Tennessee, 1984), p. 92.</ref> He registered 11 \"big plays,\" second only to teammate [[Reggie White]]'s phenomenal 29.<ref name=83stats /> He was named to the Freshman All-American team by ''The Football News''.<ref name=bio />\n\n===1984 season===\nAs part of a linebacker corps that included future NFL players [[Reggie McKenzie (linebacker)|Reggie McKenzie]], [[Alvin Toles]] and [[Carl Zander]], Jones opened the [[1984 Tennessee Volunteers football team|1984 season]] with 12 tackles in Tennessee's 34-27 win over [[Washington State Cougars football|Washington State]].  In the Vols' loss to Auburn, Jones stuffed running back [[Brent Fullwood]] at the one-yard line, causing a fumble and preventing a touchdown.\n\nHe had 13 tackles in Tennessee's 28-27 win over Alabama.  He finished the season as the team's leader in \"big plays,\" with 4 sacks, 4 forced fumbles (led the team), and 7 tackles-for-loss.<ref name=85bio>\"[https://digital.lib.utk.edu/collections/footballprograms?bid=738&pg=68 1985 Squad],\" ''1985 Tennessee Volunteers Football Guide'' (University of Tennessee, 1985), p. 66.</ref>  His 109 total tackles was second only to Zander's 167.<ref>\"[https://digital.lib.utk.edu/collections/footballprograms?bid=738&pg=104 1984 Defensive Statistics],\" ''1985 Tennessee Volunteers Football Guide'' (University of Tennessee, 1985), p. 102.</ref>  He was named to the Sophomore All-American team by ''The Football News''.<ref name=85bio />\n\n===1985 season===\nJones is frequently recalled as the \"emotional leader\" of the [[1985 Tennessee Volunteers football team|1985 \"Sugar Vols\" squad]].<ref>Mike Strange, \"[http://www.govolsxtra.com/news/2005/aug/28/sweet-memories-uts-sugar-bowl-win-over-miami-was/?print=1 Sweet Memories: UT's Sugar Bowl Win Over Miami Was One for Ages],\" ''Knoxnews.com'', August 28, 2005. Retrieved: July 29, 2013.</ref><ref>\"[https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1842&dat=19860824&id=eiMrAAAAIBAJ&sjid=UZ4FAAAAIBAJ&pg=2934,5308087 Veteran Defense May Allow Vols to Repeat in SEC],\" ''Florence TimesDaily'', August 24, 1986, p. 12F.</ref>  In Tennessee's 38-20 upset of #1 Auburn on September 28, Jones led a swarming defense that held eventual [[Heisman Trophy]] winner [[Bo Jackson]] to 80 yards on 17 carries (Jackson entered the game averaging over 200 yards per game for the season).<ref>\"[https://digital.lib.utk.edu/collections/footballprograms?bid=748&pg=103 Strong Finish By Top-Rated Auburn Falls Short As Vols Snap Loss Skein],\" ''1986 Tennessee Volunteers Football Guide'' (University of Tennessee, 1986), p. 100.</ref> Following the team's 17-10 loss to [[Florida Gators football|Florida]] on October 12, Jones rallied the team with a locker room speech in which he declared, \"This is the only game we're going to lose all year.\"<ref>Ron Bliss, \"[http://tricitiessports.com/kingsport-has-its-own-sugarvol-in-mark-hovanic-p6276.htm Kingsport Has Its Own SugarVol in Mark Hovanic],\" TricitiesSports.com, October 5, 2005. Retrieved: July 29, 2013.</ref>\n\nThe biggest play of Jones's career came in Tennessee's win over Alabama, which took place at [[Legion Field]] on October 19.  After Tennessee's star quarterback [[Tony Robinson (American football)|Tony Robinson]] left the game with an injury, Alabama seized the momentum and scored a touchdown to cut the lead to 16-14, and had driven into Tennessee territory for what would have been the go-ahead score, when Jones tipped a pass from quarterback [[Mike Shula]] and caught it as he fell to the ground for a drive-killing interception.<ref>\"[https://digital.lib.utk.edu/collections/footballprograms?bid=748&pg=103 Survival in Tense Fourth Quarter Allows Vols to Card Fourth in Row Over Tide],\" ''1986 Tennessee Volunteers Football Guide'' (University of Tennessee, 1986), p. 101.</ref>  Jones also recovered a fumble late in the 3rd quarter that set up Tennessee's third field goal.<ref>Broadcast of Tennessee vs. Alabama, College Football on TBS, October 19, 1985.</ref>\n\nIn Tennessee's 6-6 tie against [[Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets football|Georgia Tech]] on October 26, Jones batted away a 3rd-down pass by [[John Dewberry]] to force the Yellow Jackets to settle for a field goal early in the first quarter,<ref>Steve Baker, \"[https://apnews.com/966e09a4100f715526cdd635c639fccd Georgia Tech 6, Tennessee 6],\" AP News Archive, October 26, 1985. Retrieved: July 29, 2013.</ref> and was named \"SEC Lineman of the Week\" for his overall performance.<ref name=86bio />  In the Vols' 34-14 win over [[Ole Miss Rebels football|Ole Miss]], Jones had two third-quarter sacks, both of which forced Ole Miss to punt from their own end zone.<ref>Broadcast of Tennessee vs. Ole Miss, College Football on TBS, November 16, 1985.</ref>\n\nIn Tennessee's upset of [[Miami Hurricanes football|Miami]] in the [[1986 Sugar Bowl]], Jones had 7 tackles as a part of a defensive effort that held the Hurricanes' high-scoring offense to just 7 points.  Jones sacked Miami quarterback [[Vinny Testaverde]] twice for -38 yards, including a crucial sack late in the second quarter that forced Miami to settle for a long, unsuccessful field goal attempt.<ref name=86bio>\"[https://digital.lib.utk.edu/collections/footballprograms?bid=748&pg=70 1986 Squad],\" ''1986 Tennessee Volunteers Football Guide'' (University of Tennessee, 1986), p. 69.</ref>\n\nJones finished the 1985 season with 82 tackles (59 solo), 5 sacks, 9 tackles-for-loss, 5 forced fumbles, and 4 pass deflections. He was named All-SEC, 3rd-team All-American and SEC defensive lineman of the year honors from the Atlanta Touchdown Club.<ref name=86bio />\n\n===1986 season===\nJones was a tri-captain of Tennessee's 1986 squad, and was named to ''[[Playboy]]'''s preseason All-American team.<ref name=alger />  The Vols struggled to a 2-5 start before winning their final four games to secure a winning season.  Jones had 11 tackles (2 for minus yardage) and a fumble recovery in Tennessee's 21-14 victory over [[Minnesota Golden Gophers football|Minnesota]] in the 1986 [[Liberty Bowl]], and was named the game's \"Outstanding Defensive Player.\"<ref>\"[https://digital.lib.utk.edu/collections/footballprograms?bid=749&pg=106 1986 Comeback Capped by Stirring Liberty Bowl Win],\" ''1987 Tennessee Volunteers Football Guide'' (University of Tennessee, 1987), p. 104.</ref>\n\nJones finished the 1986 season with 88 tackles (53 solo), 4.5 sacks, and 2 tackles-for-loss.<ref>\"[https://digital.lib.utk.edu/collections/footballprograms?bid=749&pg=109 1986 Defensive Statistics],\" ''1987 Tennessee Volunteers Football Guide'' (University of Tennessee, 1987), p. 106.</ref>  He was again named All-SEC, and received All-American honorable mention by the Associated Press.<ref>\"[https://digital.lib.utk.edu/collections/footballprograms?bid=749&pg=110 1986 Honorees],\" ''1987 Tennessee Volunteers Football Guide'' (University of Tennessee, 1987), p. 108.</ref>\n\n===Records and legacy===\nDuring his four years at Tennessee, Jones amassed 349 total tackles (233 solo), 14.5 sacks, 24 tackles-for-loss, and 11 forced fumbles.<ref>[http://www.utsports.com/sports/m-footbl/fball-stats/j.htm Football Career Statistics], UTSports.com.  Retrieved: July 29, 2013.</ref>  As of the 2012 season, he was tied with [[Rico McCoy]] for 9th place on the school's career tackles list.  He is tied with [[Keith DeLong]] for seventh place in career solo tackles, and is fourth in tackles-for-loss behind [[Leonard Little]], [[Reggie White]] and [[Eric Westmoreland]].  He is second in forced fumbles behind Andy Spiva, who had 14 from 1973 to 1976.<ref>[http://www.utsports.com/sports/m-footbl/guides/2012/records.pdf Individual Football Records] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304113625/http://www.utsports.com/sports/m-footbl/guides/2012/records.pdf |date=March 4, 2016 }}, UTSports.com, 2012.  Retrieved: July 29, 2013.</ref>\n\nTennessee coach [[Johnny Majors]] described Jones as \"one of the greatest leaders I ever had.\"<ref>Mark Wiedmer, \"[http://www.timesfreepress.com/news/2011/nov/22/ex-vols-coach-majors-still-a-historic-presence/?print Ex-Vols Coach Johnny Majors Still a Historic Presence],\" ''Chattanooga Times Free Press'', November 22, 2011. Retrieved: July 29, 2013.</ref>  He stated that Jones \"personifies what college football is all about to the highest degree,\"<ref>\"[http://diglib.lib.utk.edu/fbpro/main.php?bid=748&pg=15&s=dale%20jones Majors Meets the Press],\" ''1986 Tennessee Volunteers Football Guide'' (University of Tennessee, 1986), p. 13.</ref> and noted, \"I have never seen a young man in my life that it meant more to play for one particular school than it does for Dale Jones to play at Tennessee.\"<ref name=alger />\n\nJones remains one of the best-known former Tennessee defenders, achieving what ''[[Knoxville News Sentinel]]'' reporter Mike Strange describes as \"folk-hero status\" among Vol fans.<ref>Mike Strange, \"[http://www.knoxnews.com/news/2012/sep/30/vols-were-sugar-sweet/?partner=RSS Vols Were Sugar Sweet],\" ''Knoxville News Sentinel'', September 30, 2012. Retrieved: July 29, 2013.</ref>  In a 2005 article, reporter John Painter wrote, \"Mention Dale Jones is making an appearance in Knoxville and chances are it would resemble 'Jimmy Buffett Night' in [[Key West, Florida|Key West]].  Gonna draw a crowd.\"<ref name=painter>John Painter, \"[http://www.utsports.com/sports/m-footbl/spec-rel/102111aab.html Former Vols Linebacker Making His Mark as Coach],\" UTSports.com, October 21, 2011. Retrieved: July 29, 2013.</ref>\n\nHe was honored as a Vol \"Legend of the Game\" during Tennessee's game against Alabama on October 25, 2014.<ref>\"[https://utsports.com/news/2014/10/22/Saturday_s_VFL_Legend_Of_Game_Dale_Jones.aspx Saturday's VFL Legend of Game: Dale Jones],\" UTSports.com, October 22, 2014.</ref>\n\n==Professional career==\nJones was selected by the [[Dallas Cowboys]] in the 10th round (262nd overall) of the [[1987 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.upi.com/Archives/1987/04/29/NFL-Draft-List/6040546667200/ | title=NFL Draft List | accessdate=January 12, 2019}}</ref> He was waived on September 1.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/09/02/sports/transactions-906687.html?src=pm&pagewanted=1 | title=Transactions | newspaper=New York Times | date=September 2, 1987 | accessdate=January 12, 2019}}</ref> On September 2, he was claimed off waivers by the [[Houston Oilers]]. He was released on September 6.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/430985972/ | title=Transactions | newspaper=El Paso Times | date=September 7, 1987 | accessdate=January 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAfter the players went on a strike on the third week of the season, those games were canceled (reducing the 16 game season to 15) and the [[NFL]] decided that the games would be played with replacement players. Jones was re-signed to be a part of the Cowboys replacement team, that was given the mock name \"Rhinestone Cowboys\" by the media and started in three games at [[outside linebacker|left outside linebacker]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.nfl.com/player/dalejones/2517930/gamelogs | title=Dale Jones profile | publisher=NFL.com | accessdate=January 12, 2019}}</ref> Against the [[New York Jets]] on October 4, he posted 6 tackles and one fumble recovery. In the win over the [[Philadelphia Eagles]] on October 11, he recovered a fumble and returned it 26 yards to the 1 yard line.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://newspaperarchive.com/european-stars-and-stripes/1987-10-12/page-25 | title=Cowboys Roll Past Eagles 41-22 | publisher=European Stars and Stripes | page= 26 | date=October 12, 1987 | accessdate=January 12, 2019}}</ref> In the game against the [[Washington Redskins]] on October 19, a hit by Jones knocked Redskins [[quarterback]] [[Ed Rubbert]] out of the game in the second quarter, ironically, this allowed Jones's former teammate, backup quarterback [[Tony Robinson (American football)|Tony Robinson]], to enter the game and lead the Redskins to a 13-7 upset victory.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/sports/redskins/longterm/1997/history/allart/dw1987a.htm | title=Replacement Redskins Enjoy Happy Ending, 13-7 | author=Christine Brennan | newspaper=Washington Post | date=October 20, 1987 | accessdate=January 12, 2019}}</ref> He was again released after the strike ended on October 26.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/1987/10/27/sports/transactions-111087.html | title=Transactions | newspaper=New York Times | date=October 27, 1987 | accessdate=January 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Coaching career==\nJones returned to Tennessee as a graduate assistant in 1989.  The following year, he was hired as defensive coordinator of the Italian League [[Parma Panthers]], joining former high school and college teammate Chris White.<ref name=painter />  After a year with the Panthers, he joined the [[Florida Gators football|Florida Gators]] staff as an assistant in 1991.  Later that year, he was hired as the linebackers and defensive backs coach at [[Georgia Military College]], and was promoted to defensive coordinator in 1992.<ref name=bio>Appalachian State Sports Information, \"[http://www.appstatesports.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=21500&ATCLID=1548736 Dale Jones] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150722235635/http://www.appstatesports.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=21500&ATCLID=1548736 |date=July 22, 2015 }}, July 8, 2013. Retrieved: July 29, 2013.</ref>\n\nIn 1996, Jones was hired by [[Appalachian State University|Appalachian State]] head coach [[Jerry Moore (American football, born 1939)|Jerry Moore]] as the Mountaineers' defensive line and [[special teams]] coach.  In 2005, he switched to linebackers coach.  He was elevated to defensive coordinator for the 2010 season, helping to engineer the Mountaineers' transition to a [[3-4 defense]].<ref>\"[https://www.dailypress.com/sports/virginia-tech/dp-xpm-20110902-2011-09-02-dp-spt-appalachian-state-tech-football-advance-090-20110902-story.html Virginia Tech Has Prepared for Potential Headaches from Appalachian State],\" ''Hampton Roads Daily Press'', September 2, 2011. Retrieved: July 29, 2013.</ref>  Following Moore's retirement in 2012, long-time [[Wofford Terriers football|Wofford]] assistant Nate Woody was hired as defensive coordinator as part of the new staff assembled by Moore's successor, [[Scott Satterfield]].  Jones returned to his earlier position of defensive line coach.<ref>Appalachian State Sports Information, \"[https://appstatesports.com/news/2013/1/14/205968461.aspx Nate Woody Named Defensive Coordinator],\" January 14, 2013. Retrieved: July 29, 2013.</ref>  Prior to the 2014 season, he switched to inside linebackers coach.\n\nDuring Jones's initial tenure as defensive line coach, eight of his lineman moved on to play in the NFL, six received FCS All-American honors, and 15 were All-[[Southern Conference]].  Two, Josh Jeffries (2002) and K.T. Stovall (2003), received the Southern Conference Defensive Player of the Year award.  Jones was named \"Special Teams Coordinator of the Year\" by ''American Football Monthly'' in 2002.  Players Jones has worked with at Appalachian State who would go on to play in the NFL include [[Marques Murrell]], [[D. J. Smith (American football)|D.J. Smith]], [[Demetrius McCray]], Jeremy Kimbrough and [[Jason Hunter (American football)|Jason Hunter]].<ref name=bio /><ref>Stan Crawley, \"[https://www.chattanoogan.com/2005/12/10/77107/Former-Vol-Dale-Jones-Coming-To-I-AA.aspx Former Vol Dale Jones Coming to I-AA Title Game As ASU Linebacker Coach],\" ''The Chattanoogan'', December 10, 2005. Retrieved: July 29, 2013.</ref> He also recruited punter [[Sam Martin (American football)|Sam Martin]].<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.espn.com/blog/nfcnorth/post/_/id/61913/sam-martin-goes-from-pizza-hut-to-the-pros | title=Sam Martin Goes from Pizza to the Pros | author=Michael Rothstein | publisher=ESPN | date=October 4, 2013 | accessdate=January 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn January 4, 2019, he followed head coach [[Scott Satterfield]] to the [[University of Louisville]] and was named the new [[linebacker|inside linebackers]] coach.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://gocards.com/news/2019/1/4/football-jones-named-inside-linebackers-coach-at-louisville.aspx | title=Jones Named Inside Linebackers Coach at Louisville | author=Rocco Gasparro | publisher=University of Louisville | date=January 4, 2019 | accessdate=January 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn January 15, 2020, Appalachian State announced that Jones had agreed to return as defensive coordinator under new head coach [[Shawn Clark]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Robinson |first1=Cameron |title=Inside linebackers coach Dale Jones leaving U of L, named App State defensive coordinator |url=https://www.courier-journal.com/story/sports/college/louisville/2020/01/15/louisville-football-linebackers-coach-dale-jones-moving-app-state/2657264001/ |accessdate=16 January 2020 |work=Louisville Courier Journal |date=15 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{Cowboys1987DraftPicks}}\n{{2005 Appalachian State Mountaineers football navbox}}\n{{2006 Appalachian State Mountaineers football navbox}}\n{{2007 Appalachian State Mountaineers football navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jones, Dale}}\n[[Category:1963 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People from Cleveland, Tennessee]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Tennessee]]\n[[Category:American football linebackers]]\n[[Category:Tennessee Volunteers football players]]\n[[Category:Dallas Cowboys players]]\n[[Category:Tennessee Volunteers football coaches]]\n[[Category:Florida Gators football coaches]]\n[[Category:Appalachian State Mountaineers football coaches]]\n[[Category:Louisville Cardinals football coaches]]\n[[Category:National Football League replacement players]]\n", "name_user": "FeverishAxe0", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eInfobox NFL biography", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dale_Jones_(American_football)"}
{"title_page": "Dannel Malloy", "text_new": "{{distinguish|Daniel Molloy}}\n{{short description|88th Governor of Connecticut}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Dan Malloy\n|image        = Dannel Malloy 2016.jpg\n|office1      = 13th Chancellor of the<br>[[University of Maine System]]<br>\n|term_start1  = July 1, 2019\n|term_end1    =\n|predecessor1  = [[James H. Page]]\n|successor1    =\n|order2        = 88th [[List of governors of Connecticut|Governor of Connecticut]]\n|lieutenant2   = [[Nancy Wyman]]\n|term_start2   = January 5, 2011\n|term_end2     = January 9, 2019\n|predecessor2  = [[Jodi Rell]]\n|successor2    = [[Ned Lamont]]\n|office3      = 29th [[Mayor of Stamford, Connecticut|Mayor of Stamford]]\n|term_start3  = December 1, 1995\n|term_end3    = December 1, 2009\n|predecessor3 = Stanley Esposito\n|successor3   = [[Michael Pavia]]\n|birth_name   = Dannel Patrick Malloy\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1955|7|21}}\n|birth_place  = [[Stamford, Connecticut]], U.S.\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|spouse       = Cathy Malloy\n|education    = [[Boston College]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]], [[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n|signature    = DannelPMalloySignture.jpg\n}}\n'''Dannel Patrick Malloy''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|d|\u00e6|n|\u0259l|_|m|\u0259|\u02c8|l|\u0254\u026a}}; born July 21, 1955) is an American politician, who served as the [[List of Governors of Connecticut|88th governor of Connecticut]] from 2011 to 2019. A member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]], he chaired the [[Democratic Governors Association]] from 2016 to 2017. On July 1, 2019, he began his tenure as the Chancellor of the [[University of Maine System]].\n\nBorn in [[Stamford, Connecticut]], Malloy is a graduate of [[Boston College Law School]]. Malloy began his career as an assistant district attorney in New York in 1980 before moving back to Stamford and entering private practice. He served on the Stamford board of finance from 1984 to 1994 before being elected Mayor of [[Stamford, Connecticut|Stamford]]. He served four terms as mayor from December 1995 to December 2009.\n\nMalloy ran unsuccessfully for Governor of Connecticut in [[Connecticut gubernatorial election, 2006|2006]], losing the Democratic primary to [[John DeStefano, Jr.]], the [[List of mayors of New Haven, Connecticut|Mayor]] of [[New Haven, Connecticut|New Haven]], who was defeated in the general election by incumbent Republican Governor [[Jodi Rell]]. He ran again in [[Connecticut gubernatorial election, 2010|2010]] and comfortably won the primary, defeating [[Ned Lamont]], the [[United States Senate election in Connecticut, 2006|2006 U.S. Senate nominee]], by 57% of the vote to 43%.<ref name=\"courant.com\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.courant.com/2010-05-23/news/hc-malloy-governor-endorsement-0521_1_greenwich-cable-television-entrepreneur-stamford-mayor-dannel-malloy-clean-elections|title=Dannel Malloy Wins Democratic Endorsement For Governor|work=courant.com|accessdate=21 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/11/nyregion/11conn.html|title=Lamont Loses Connecticut Primary for Governor|date=11 August 2010|work=The New York Times|accessdate=21 September 2016}}</ref> Rell did not run for reelection and Malloy faced former [[United States Ambassador to Ireland]] [[Thomas C. Foley]] in the general election, defeating him by fewer than 6,500 votes. Malloy was sworn in on January 5, 2011. He was reelected in a rematch with Foley in [[Connecticut gubernatorial election, 2014|2014]], increasing his margin of victory to over 28,000 votes. As of July 2018, he had a 21% job approval rating and a 71% disapproval rating, making him the second least popular and third most disliked governor in the United States, after [[Mary Fallin]] of [[Oklahoma]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://morningconsult.com/2018/07/25/americas-most-and-least-popular-governors-2/|title=America's Most and Least Popular Governors -- July 2018|date=25 July 2018|publisher=}}</ref> On April 13, 2017, Malloy announced he would not seek reelection in [[Connecticut gubernatorial election, 2018|2018]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.courant.com/politics/hc-gov-malloy-will-not-seek-a-third-term-20170413-story.html|title=In Emotional Remarks, Gov. Malloy Says He Will Not Seek Third Term - Hartford Courant|first=Daniela|last=Altimari|website=courant.com}}</ref> He was succeeded in office by Democrat [[Ned Lamont]] on January 9, 2019.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theday.com/article/20181107/NWS12/181109564|title=Stefanowski concedes race to Lamont: 'He won fair and square'|first1=Mark|last1=Pazniokas|first2=Keith M.|last2=Phaneuf|work=The Day|date=November 7, 2018|accessdate=November 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Early life, education and early career==\nDannel Patrick Malloy was born and raised in [[Stamford, Connecticut]], the seventh of seven sons and youngest of the eight children of Agnes Veronica (n\u00e9e Egan), a nurse, and William Francis Malloy.<ref>{{cite web|last=Siedzik|first=Jason|url=http://www.registercitizen.com/articles/2010/08/03/news/doc4c57388607a1d754613517.txt|title=Dan Malloy stands behind the striking employees of Laurel Hill Health Care|publisher=The Register Citizen|accessdate=2012-12-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://familytreemaker.genealogy.com/users/m/a/l/William-F-Malloy/FILE/0001text.txt |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-11-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141015065815/http://familytreemaker.genealogy.com/users/m/a/l/William-F-Malloy/FILE/0001text.txt |archivedate=2014-10-15 }}</ref> He is of Irish descent and was raised as a [[Catholic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stamfordplus.com/stm/information/nws1/publish/politics/Irish-eyes-were-smiling-at-Governor-Elect-Malloy-in-Stamford-reception10764.shtml|title=Irish eyes were smiling at Governor-elect Malloy in Stamford reception|publisher=Stamfordplus.com|accessdate=2012-12-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Lisa Miller|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/on-faith/catholic-activists-pushing-politicians-to-turn-tide-against-the-death-penalty/2012/04/19/gIQAU2EpTT_story.html|title=Catholic activists pushing politicians to turn tide against the death penalty|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=2012-04-19|accessdate=2012-12-16}}</ref>\n\nAs a child and as Governor, Malloy suffered from [[learning disabilities]] and difficulties with [[motor coordination]]. He did not learn to tie his shoes until the fifth grade. Malloy eventually was diagnosed with [[dyslexia]]<ref>{{cite news|title=AP Interview: Malloy overcame dyslexia, physical struggles|date=May 30, 2006|accessdate=November 14, 2010|url = http://www.ctpost.com/default/article/AP-Interview-Malloy-overcame-dyslexia-physical-112920.php|last=Haigh|first=Susan|agency=Associated Press|newspaper=The Connecticut Post}}</ref><ref name=\"Hernandez\">{{cite news|title=Odds Defied? Malloy Knows the Territory|last=Hernandez|first=Raymond|accessdate=November 14, 2010|date=August 11, 2010|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/12/nyregion/12malloy.html|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref> and learned the skills necessary to succeed academically. He does not write or type, and rarely reads from notes in public, but developed an extraordinarily useful memory.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Connecticut Governor, Tackling Budget, Criticizes Christie's Approach|date=February 15, 2011|accessdate=February 16, 2011|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/02/16/nyregion/16malloy.html?_r=1&adxnnl=1&adxnnlx=1297839652-SRcFblaLbQenLjEJtrZZbg|last=Halbfinger|first=David M.|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> He graduated ''[[magna cum laude]]'' from [[Boston College]], where he met his wife Cathy, and later earned his [[Juris Doctor|J.D.]] degree from [[Boston College Law School]].<ref>{{cite news|title=AP Interview: Malloy overcame dyslexia, physical struggles|date=May 30, 2006|accessdate=November 14, 2010|url=http://www.ctpost.com/default/article/AP-Interview-Malloy-overcame-dyslexia-physical-112920.php|last=Haigh|first=Susan|agency=Associated Press|newspaper=The Connecticut Post}}</ref><ref name=\"Hernandez\"/>\n\nAfter passing the [[bar exam]], Malloy served as an [[Assistant District Attorney]] in [[Brooklyn, New York]] from 1980-84. During his tenure as a prosecutor, Malloy tried 23 felony cases, four of them homicides, and won 22 convictions. He was subsequently a partner in the Stamford law firm of Abate and Fox from 1984-95. He served on the Stamford Board of Finance from 1983-94.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.governor.ct.gov/malloy/cwp/view.asp?a=4011&q=471134|title=Governor Dannel P. Malloy profile at Connecticut's Official State Website|first=Department of Information|last=Technology|work=ct.gov|accessdate=September 21, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Mayor of Stamford (1995\u20132009)==\nIn 1995, he ran successfully for Mayor of Stamford, defeating two-term Republican incumbent Stanley Esposito. At the same time, voters approved a measure to extend the Mayor's term of office from two years to four, effective at the next election. He was re-elected in 1997, 2001 and 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stamfordplus.com/stm/information/nws1/publish/magazine/And-they-re-off5194.shtml|title=And they're off!|author=Bill Squier|publisher=Stamford Plus|date=June 1, 2009|accessdate=October 28, 2013}}</ref>\n\nMalloy made crime reduction a priority during his tenure as mayor; Stamford saw a dramatic decrease in homicides under his administration. Stamford is currently ranked as the 9th safest city in the United States and 3rd safest in the Northeast region<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stamfordplus.com/stm/information/nws1/publish/Local_2/Mayor-releases-crime-statistics-for-first-six-months-of-20095884.shtml|title=StamfordPlus.com News - Mayor releases crime statistics for first six months of 2009|work=stamfordplus.com|accessdate=21 September 2016}}</ref> and for the past six years has ranked in the top 11 safest cities with populations of 100,000 or more, according to the [[FBI]].<ref>Lowe, Zach. [http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-31324427_ITM \"Stamford named ninth safest city in U.S.\"] ''The Advocate'' (Stamford), 2007-06-20. Retrieved on 2009-02-19</ref> Malloy wrote a blog known as \"The Blog That Works\", since deleted, until mid-January 2010.\n\nBudgeting and districting of the various fire departments throughout the city has been unstable since 2007, due to an extended legal conflict between the volunteer departments and the Malloy administration, which sought to consolidate the fire departments against the advice and wishes of the volunteer fire departments.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stamfordadvocate.com/default/article/Stamford-fire-service-consolidation-part-of-272317.php|last=Morganteen|first=Jeff|date=December 2, 2009|title=Stamford fire service consolidation part of Malloy's legacy|publisher=stamfordadvocate.com|accessdate=August 29, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Governor of Connecticut (2011\u20132019)==\n\n===Elections===\n\n====2006====\n{{Main|2006 Connecticut gubernatorial election}}\nIn 2004, Malloy was the first candidate to announce his bid for the Democratic Party nomination for Governor of Connecticut. In a major upset in Malloy's favor, he received the convention endorsement of the Democratic Party on May 20, 2006 by one vote. Malloy lost in the primary election however against [[Mayor of New Haven|New Haven Mayor]] [[John DeStefano, Jr.]] on August 8, 2006.\n\n====2010====\n{{Main|2010 Connecticut gubernatorial election}}\nOn February 3, 2009, Malloy officially filed paperwork with Connecticut's State Elections Enforcement Commission to form a gubernatorial exploratory committee,<ref>Pazniokas, Mark. [http://www.courant.com/news/politics/hcu-govmalloy-0203,0,785420.story \"Stamford Mayor Explores Run For Governor\"]{{Dead link|date=November 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} ''[[The Hartford Courant]]'', 2009-02-03. Retrieved on 2009-02-19</ref> and subsequently announced that he did not intend to seek re-election as Mayor of Stamford.<ref name=\"mayorrun\">Wright, Chase. [http://thestamfordtimes.com/story/464494 \"Malloy focuses on governor's seat\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717033928/http://thestamfordtimes.com/story/464494 |date=2011-07-17 }}, ''The Stamford Times'', 2009-02-04.</ref> On March 9, 2010, Malloy filed the required paperwork to officially [[Connecticut gubernatorial election, 2010|run for governor]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stamfordadvocate.com/local/article/Malloy-makes-it-official-he-s-running-for-400115.php|title=Malloy makes it official: he's running for governor|publisher=StamfordAdvocate|date=2010-03-10|accessdate=2010-08-29}}</ref>\n\nMalloy received the Democratic Party's endorsement for governor on May 22, 2010, in a 68-32 vote over 2006 Democratic senatorial candidate [[Ned Lamont]].<ref name=\"courant.com\"/> Connecticut's Democratic Party rules allow any candidate who received more than 15% of the vote at its nominating convention to challenge the endorsed candidate for the nomination in a primary, and Lamont announced that he would challenge Malloy in the gubernatorial primary. The primary was held on August 10, 2010. Malloy won with 58% of the vote, according to [[Associated Press|AP]]-reported unofficial results.<ref name=AP>AP, \"Connecticut \u2013 Summary Vote Results\" ''Daily Coruant'', August 11, 2010. Found at [http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/files/elections/2010/by_state/CT_Page_0810.html?SITE=CTHARELN&SECTION=POLITICS AP website]; retrieved August 11, 2010.</ref><ref name=Dem>DemFromCT, \"CT primary: Malloy beats Lamont, GOP Gov. leans Foley, McMahon wins but under 50%\", [[DailyKos]], August 10, 2010; see [http://www.dailykos.com/story/2010/8/10/891992/-CT-primary:-Malloy-beats-Lamont,-GOP-Gov.-leans-Foley,-McMahon-wins-but-under-50 DailyKos website]; retrieved August 11, 2010.</ref><ref name=Post>Ken Dixon, \"Foley joins Malloy as primary winner,\" August 10, 2010. Found at [http://www.ctpost.com/news/article/Malloy-stretches-lead-Foley-still-on-top-in-610659.php Connecticut Post website]; retrieved August 11, 2010</ref> According to preliminary numbers, he beat Lamont 101,354 to 73,875.<ref name=AP /><ref name=Dem />\n\nAs a Democratic candidate for governor prior to the Democratic state convention and subsequent primary, Malloy chose [[Nancy Wyman]] to be his running mate. Wyman is the only woman elected [[Connecticut Comptroller|State Comptroller]] since the office was created in 1786. Malloy's choice was confirmed by the Democratic nominating convention on May 22, and Wyman became the official 2010 Democratic candidate for lieutenant governor when she defeated primary opponent Mary Glassman on August 10. After the primaries, candidates for governor and lieutenant governor run together as a team on a single ticket. Thus, Malloy and Wyman were both elected on November 2, 2010.\n\nMalloy faced [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] [[Thomas C. Foley]], the former [[United States Ambassador to Ireland]] under President [[George W. Bush]], in the race for governor. Tom Foley had never been elected to public office. In the last [[Quinnipiac University Polling Institute]] poll released on the morning before [[Election Day]], Malloy trailed Foley 48% to 45%.<ref>Q Poll: Blumenthal Up 9 Points; Governor Too Close To Call.[http://www.courant.com/news/politics/hc-qu-poll-story-1101,0,4009370.story \"Q Poll: Blumenthal Up 9 Points; Governor Too Close To Call\"] \"[[The Hartford Courant]]\", 2010-11-01. Retrieved on 2010-11-01.</ref>\n\nAccording to ''[[The New York Times]]'' on November 3, Malloy was elected governor; they later placed Foley in the lead with no declared winner.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://elections.nytimes.com/2010/results/connecticut?ref=nyregion|title=Connecticut - Election Results 2010 - The New York Times|work=nytimes.com|accessdate=21 September 2016}}</ref> The [[Associated Press]] had at one point also placed Foley ahead by 8,424 votes because they hadn't added the votes from [[New Haven]] or [[Bridgeport]] at that time.<ref name=SAdvocate>{{cite news|url=http://www.stamfordadvocate.com/local/article/Malloy-declared-winner-but-Foley-fights-on-797028.php|title=Malloy declared winner, but Foley fights on |author=Ken Dixon and Bill Cummings|newspaper=[[Stamford Advocate]]|date=November 3, 2010|accessdate=November 4, 2010}}</ref> In the days following the election, there was controversy over [[Connecticut gubernatorial election, 2010#Bridgeport ballot shortage|several polling locations in Bridgeport]] remaining open until 10 p.m. on Election Day due to ballot shortages.<ref name=SAdvocate/> Foley's team looked into the events that took place in [[Bridgeport]] and determined there was insufficient evidence of enough fraud to overcome the vote deficit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcconnecticut.com/news/politics/Foley-to-Make-Announcement-on-Plans-Today-106883273.html|title=Foley Concedes to Malloy|work=nbcconnecticut.com|accessdate=21 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n====2014====\n{{Main|2014 Connecticut gubernatorial election}}\nOn March 28, 2014, Malloy announced his intention to seek a second term.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.courant.com/2014-03-28/news/hc-malloy-seeking-reelection-20140328_1_re-election-plans-press-conference-capitol-complex|title=Gov. Dannel P. Malloy: Gov. Dannel P. Malloy Announces Re-Election Bid|work=courant.com|accessdate=21 September 2016}}</ref> With full support, he was unopposed in the Democratic primary. On August 12, [[Thomas C. Foley|Tom Foley]], Malloy's Republican opponent in 2010, won his party's nomination,<ref name=2014primaryresults>{{cite web |url=http://www.sots.ct.gov/sots/lib/sots/electionservices/ElectionResults/2014_Town_Primary_Returns/August_12_2014_Primary_Unofficial_Results.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140903064952/http://www.sots.ct.gov/sots/lib/sots/electionservices/ElectionResults/2014_Town_Primary_Returns/August_12_2014_Primary_Unofficial_Results.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 3, 2014 |title=Unofficial primary results |publisher=Connecticut Secretary of State |date=August 12, 2014 |accessdate=August 28, 2014 }}</ref> making the 2014 election a rematch of the bitter 2010 contest. As expected, the race was very close. On November 4, Malloy won reelection with 51.1 percent of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.statementofvote-sots.ct.gov/StatementOfVote/WebModules/ReportsLink/OfficeTitle.aspx|title=OfficeTitle|work=ct.gov|accessdate=21 September 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141013005918/http://www.statementofvote-sots.ct.gov/StatementOfVote/WebModules/ReportsLink/OfficeTitle.aspx|archivedate=13 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2014-11-05/connecticut-governor-race-deadlocked-in-rematch-of-2010-contest.html | work=Bloomberg | first=Brian | last=Chappatta | title=Connecticut's Malloy Wins Re-Election as Foley Concedes | date=November 5, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/11/06/nyregion/dannel-malloy-thomas-foley-connecticut-governors-race.html?_r=0 | work=The New York Times | first=Benjamin | last=Mueller | title=Dannel Malloy, in Repeat, Wins a Close Election for Connecticut Governor | date=November 5, 2014}}</ref> Foley conceded the election on November 5 without direct communication with Malloy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcconnecticut.com/news/local/governors-race-election-decision-2014-results-malloy-foley-281536171.html|title=Foley Concedes Governor's Race to Malloy|work=nbcconnecticut.com|accessdate=21 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\n[[File:Inauguration of Governor Dannel P. Malloy (5344187708).jpg|thumb|Dan Malloy taking the oath of office, January 2011]]\nMalloy was sworn in as the 88th Governor of Connecticut on January 5, 2011, succeeding Republican Governor [[Jodi Rell]].\n\nIn the state's legislative elections of November 2012, Republicans tried to tie Democratic legislators to Malloy, who had consistently faced negative job approval ratings.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/itsallpolitics/2013/08/25/214133469/a-guide-to-the-nations-most-vulnerable-governors |title=A Guide To The Nation's Most Vulnerable Governors |author=Alan Greenblatt |publisher=[[NPR]] |date=August 25, 2013 |accessdate=October 27, 2013}}</ref> The strategy did not work and the Democrats recorded no losses in either house. Malloy called the results a \"vindication\" and said that \"Tough times require tough decisions that are not immediately popular... you should not be afraid to make tough decisions, particularly if you are transparent about those decisions, if you explain why those decisions were necessary. In our case, the tough decisions we had to make were in fact caused by Republican governors.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ctmirror.org/story/2012/11/08/malloy-sees-vindication-2012-election-results |title=Malloy sees vindication in 2012 election results |author=Mark Pazniokas |publisher=The CT Mirror |date=November 8, 2012 |accessdate=October 27, 2013}}</ref>\n\nAccording to a July 2016 ''[[The New York Times|New York Times]]'' survey, Malloy was the most unpopular Democratic governor in the country, with a 64% disapproval and 29% approval rating, and the second-most unpopular overall, after [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] [[Sam Brownback]] of [[Governor of Kansas|Kansas]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Parlapiano|first=Alicia|title=Pence Ranks Low in Approval, but Not as Low as Trump and Clinton|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2016/07/14/us/politics/mike-pence-approval-rating-governors.html?_r=0|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=July 15, 2016|accessdate=August 21, 2016}}</ref>\n\n====Economy====\nThe first task facing Malloy upon taking office was addressing a multibillion-dollar deficit as a result of the prior state budget enacted by the Democratic super-majority-controlled legislature which Rell chose to accept without signing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtnh.com/dpp/news/hartford_cty/Hartford-rell-looks-to-fix-2011%27s-budget-deficit |title=Hartford Rell looks to fix 2011's budget deficit &#124; WTNH.com Connecticut |publisher=Wtnh.com |date= |accessdate=2012-08-17}}</ref> Malloy adopted what he called an agenda of \"shared sacrifice\" which was dependent on increases in various taxes, including the income tax, the gas tax, the sales tax, and the estate tax, as well as $1 billion each year in union concessions.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://articles.courant.com/2011-02-17/news/hc-ed-malloy-budget-sacrifice-0217-20110217_1_spending-cuts-cuts-in-state-programs-state-workers |title=Malloy's Budget Pitch: 'Shared Sacrifice' \u2013 Hartford Courant |publisher=Articles.courant.com |date=2011-02-17 |accessdate=2012-08-17}}</ref> Malloy chose not to reduce aid to municipalities as part of his budget agenda,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.courant.com/2011-02-16/news/hc-malloy-cities-towns-0217-20110216_1_town-aid-road-municipal-aid-mayors-and-first-selectmen |title=City And Town Aid Escape Malloy's Budget-Cutting \u2013 Hartford Courant |publisher=Articles.courant.com |date=2011-02-16 |accessdate=2012-08-17}}</ref> although such aid would have been jeopardized if labor concessions were not reached.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehour.com/story/502842 |title=Malloy may cut municipal aid if unions don't concede \u2013 The Hour Publishing Company: Norwalk |publisher=Thehour.com |date=2011-04-13 |accessdate=2012-08-17}}</ref> After two months of negotiations, in May 2011, Malloy won $1.6 billion in union [[givebacks]]. The budget deal meant that, in contrast to many other states, there were no layoffs.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/05/14/nyregion/connecticut-reaches-deal-with-unions-to-close-budget-shortfall.html |title=Connecticut Unions Agree to $1.6 Billion in Givebacks |author=Peter Applebome |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=May 13, 2011 |accessdate=October 27, 2013}}</ref> Many of Malloy's proposed tax increases were unpopular,<ref>{{cite web|author=LeAnne Gendreau |url=http://www.nbcconnecticut.com/news/politics/Most-Disapprove-of-Malloy-Poll--117639723.html |title=Most Disapprove of Malloy: Poll |publisher=NBC Connecticut |date=2011-03-09 |accessdate=2012-08-17}}</ref> despite a statewide \"listening tour\" to promote the budget.<ref>{{cite web|author=Colin McEnroe|url=http://www.courant.com/news/opinion/hc-op-mcenroe-budget-malloy-republica20110424,0,3090603.column?track=rss |title=Looking For Sequel To Malloy's Budget Show \u2013 Hartford Courant |publisher=Courant.com |date=2011-04-24 |accessdate=2012-08-17}}</ref>\n\n====Marijuana====\nIn June 2011, Malloy signed a bill that [[Places that have decriminalized non-medical cannabis in the United States|decriminalized possession of small amounts of marijuana]]. Offenders pay a $150 fine for a first offense and a fine ranging from $200 to $500 for subsequent offenses. Those younger than 21 face a 60-day driver's license suspension. Paraphernalia has also been decriminalized as long as the person possesses under 1/2 an ounce of marijuana. Offenders may still be arrested for under 1/2 an ounce or a pipe if they are in a school zone and there is a [[Mandatory sentencing|mandatory minimum sentence]] (MMS) of 3 years. There is also an MMS of 3 years for sale to a minor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcconnecticut.com/news/politics/Marijuana-Decriminalization-Bill-Passes-123381848.html |title=Marijuana Decriminalization Bill Passes |publisher=NBC Connecticut |date= |accessdate=2013-07-06}}</ref>\n\nConnecticut became the 17th state to [[Medical cannabis in the United States|legalize medical marijuana]] on June 1, 2012 after Malloy signed a bill into law. Some portions of the law were effective immediately while the remaining portions became effective on October 1, 2012.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/06/01/us-usa-marijuana-connecticut-idUSBRE85018X20120601?feedType=RSS&feedName=domesticNews | work=Reuters | title=Medical marijuana legalized in Connecticut | date=2012-06-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cga.ct.gov/2012/BA/2012HB-05389-R010597-BA.htm | work=State of Connecticut | title=OLR Bill Analysis \u2013 AN ACT CONCERNING THE PALLIATIVE USE OF MARIJUANA. | date=2012-10-20}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2016, Malloy publicly stated that he opposed the legalization of recreational marijuana in [[Connecticut]] and that he would not support legislative efforts at legalization.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.courant.com/politics/capitol-watch/hc-malloy-blasts-legalizing-recreational-marijuana-20161215-story.html |title=Malloy Blasts Legalizing Recreational Marijuana |newspaper=Hartford Courant |accessdate=2016-12-15}}</ref>\n\n====LGBT equality====\nMalloy supports progressive social measures, including protections for transgender identity. Malloy praised the Transgender Rights Bill HB 6599<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cga.ct.gov/asp/cgabillstatus/cgabillstatus.asp?selBillType=Bill&bill_num=HB-6599 |title=Bill Status |publisher=Cga.ct.gov |date= |accessdate=2012-08-17}}</ref> and promised he would sign it into law. It passed the legislature and he signed it on July 5, 2011.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/07/06/connecticut-gender-identity-discrimination-dan-malloy_n_891739.html |title=Connecticut Gender Identity Anti-Discrimination Bill Signed By Governor Dan Malloy |work=[[The Huffington Post]] |date=July 6, 2011 |accessdate=October 27, 2013}}</ref> The bill protects the rights of transgender residents, including the right to use public facilities of the gender a person identifies with.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.boston.com/news/local/connecticut/articles/2011/06/05/conn_passes_transgender_rights_bill/ | work=The Boston Globe | title=Conn. passes transgender rights bill | date=June 5, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Advocate.com Editors |url=http://www.advocate.com/News/Daily_News/2011/06/07/Conn_Trans_Rights_Bill_a_Sure_Thing/ |title=Conn Trans Rights Bill a Sure Thing |publisher=Advocate.com |date=2011-06-07 |accessdate=2012-08-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://newyork.cbslocal.com/2011/05/20/connecticut-house-passes-transgender-rights-bill/ |title=Connecticut House Passes Transgender Rights Bill; Moves On To Senate \u00ab CBS New York |publisher=Newyork.cbslocal.com |date=2011-05-20 |accessdate=2012-08-17}}</ref>\n\n====Labor laws====\nOn September 21, 2011, Malloy issued Executive Orders 9 and 10, which would allow the [[Service Employees International Union]] to unionize day care workers subsidized through Care 4 Kids and [[personal care assistant|personal care attendants]] under Medicaid waivers by redefining these employees as state employees for [[collective bargaining]] purposes.<ref>{{cite web|author=Office of Governor Malloy |url=http://www.governor.ct.gov/malloy/cwp/view.asp?Q=487166&A=4010 |title=Governor Malloy: Gov. Malloy Advances Workers' Rights for Personal Care Attendants, Family Child Care Providers |publisher=Governor.ct.gov |date=2011-09-21 |accessdate=2012-08-17}}</ref> The executive orders generated intense opposition from child care providers, personal care attendants, their employers with disabilities, the [[National Federation of Independent Business]], and We the People of Connecticut, a constitutionalist organization.<ref>{{cite web|last=Levin Becker|first=Arielle|title=GOP hearing challenges Malloy order on home care attendants|url=http://ctmirror.org/story/14477/pca-executive-orders|publisher=CT Mirror|accessdate=24 November 2011|date=10 November 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111114011206/http://www.ctmirror.org/story/14477/pca-executive-orders|archive-date=14 November 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> Disability advocates objected to being excluded from the decision-making process, to union interference in the intimate relationship between employers and PCAs, and to the likely loss of PCA hours under a capped program; NFIB feared a \"terrible precedent\" in allowing other union organizing drives of small businesses by executive order through [[card check]]; and legislators viewed Malloy's actions as a violation of the state Constitution's [[separation of powers]]. Malloy responded that these workers, whom he described as being among the hardest working and lowest paid, deserved the opportunity to collectively bargain if they wished to do so.\n\n====Criminal justice====\nMalloy, who has long campaigned against [[capital punishment]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.courant.com/2010-10-06/news/hc-gubernatorial-debate-1006-20101005_1_death-penalty-foley-malloy-democrat-dannel-malloy |title=Tom Foley, Dan Malloy Clash On Death Penalty, Jobs, Records In Gubernatorial Debate |author=Christopher Keating |newspaper=[[Hartford Courant]] |date=May 20, 2012 |accessdate=October 27, 2013}}</ref> signed a bill to repeal [[Capital punishment in Connecticut|the state's death penalty]] on April 25, 2012. The bill was not retroactive and did not affect those on death row in Connecticut at the time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/connecticut-abolishes-death-penalty-not-that-it-actually-ever-had-one-2012-4 |title=Connecticut Abolishes The Death Penalty, Not That It Actually Ever Had One |author=Brett Logiurato |website=[[Business Insider]] |date=April 12, 2012 |accessdate=October 27, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2012/04/25/connecticut-governor-signs-bill-to-repeal-death-penalty/|title=Connecticut governor signs bill to repeal death penalty|date=April 25, 2012|work=FOXNews.com|publisher=FOX News Network, LLC.|accessdate=April 25, 2012}}</ref> On August 13, 2015, however, the [[Connecticut Supreme Court]] ruled in 2015 in ''State v. Santiago'' that the legislature's decision to prospectively abolish capital punishment rendered it an offense to \"evolving standards of decency,\" thus commuting the sentences of the 11 men remaining on death row to life in prison without parole.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ctnewsjunkie.com/archives/entry/connecticut_supreme_court_rules_death_penalty_unconstitutional/|title=Connecticut Supreme Court Rules Death Penalty Unconstitutional|publisher=CT News Junkie|date=August 13, 2015|accessdate=August 13, 2015}}</ref> Malloy was in the process of having Connecticut be the first state in the nation to raise the age of being within the juvenile system from 18 to 21 via the Second Chance initiative.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/01/04/opinion/connecticuts-second-chance-society.html?_r=0|title=Connecticut's Second-Chance |date=January 4, 2016|work=nytimes.com|publisher=New York Times|accessdate=May 2, 2016}}</ref>{{needs update|date=August 2019}}\n\n====Education====\nMalloy's \"centerpiece\" education reform bill was unanimously passed by the [[Connecticut House of Representatives]] and signed into law in early May 2012. The bill increases funding for early childhood education and poorer school districts, creates 1,000 more preschool places, creates a kindergarten to third grade literacy pilot program and reformed teacher tenure, tying it to performance.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.courant.com/2012-05-09/news/hc-house-education-reform-0509-20120508_1_school-reform-bill-education-reform-achievement-gap |title=House Unanimously Passes Education Reform Bill |author1=Kathleen Megan |author2=Daniela Altimari |newspaper=[[Hartford Courant]] |date=May 9, 2012 |accessdate=October 27, 2013}}</ref>\n\n====Voting====\nAlso in May 2012, Malloy signed a bill that expanded voting rights in Connecticut, allowing for same-day voter registration. Other provisions to allow early voting and \"no-excuse\" absentee ballots will be subject to a referendum, to be held in 2014.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.courant.com/2013-05-09/news/hc-connecticut-senate-gives-final-approval-to-constitutional-amendment-on-early-voting-20130508_1_absentee-ballots-voting-rights-voting-laws |title=Connecticut Senate Gives Final Approval To Constitutional Amendment On Early Voting |author=Daniela Altimari |newspaper=[[Hartford Courant]] |date=May 9, 2012 |accessdate=October 27, 2013}}</ref> It also allows for online voter registration, beginning in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ctmirror.org/story/2012/05/05/senate-gives-final-approval-election-day-registration |title=Senate gives final approval to Election Day registration |author=Keith M. Phaneuf |publisher=The CT Mirror |date=May 5, 2012 |accessdate=October 27, 2013}}</ref>\n\n====Gun laws====\nIn the wake of the [[Sandy Hook Elementary School shooting]] in [[Newtown, Connecticut|Newtown]] in December 2012, Malloy pushed for strict new [[Gun laws in Connecticut|gun control laws]]. In April 2013, he signed into law a bill that passed the legislature with bipartisan support and required [[universal background checks]], banned [[magazine (firearms)|magazines]] with a capacity of more than 10 rounds, created the country's first registry for dangerous-weapon offenders and added over 100 types of gun to the state's [[assault weapon]]s ban.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/national/connecticut-governor-signs-tough-gun-law-article-1.1307902 |title=Connecticut Governor Dannel Malloy signs bill with gun-control laws among the toughest in nation |newspaper=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]] |date=April 4, 2013 |accessdate=October 27, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2015, Malloy announced he would issue an executive order to prohibit anyone on federal terrorist watchlists (such as the [[No Fly List]]) from obtaining the permits required to acquire firearms in Connecticut.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/12/11/nyregion/connecticut-to-ban-gun-sales-to-those-on-federal-terrorism-lists.html|title=Connecticut to Ban Gun Sales to Those on Federal Terrorism Lists|date=11 December 2015|work=The New York Times|accessdate=21 September 2016}}</ref> The executive order would also revoke existing permits for people on such lists.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-connecticut-guns-idUSKBN0TT2EM20151210|title=Connecticut to ban gun sales to people on watch lists: governor|date=10 December 2015|publisher=|accessdate=21 September 2016|via=Reuters}}</ref>\n\n====Immigration laws====\nOn June 7, 2013, Malloy signed a bill that allows all residents of Connecticut, including illegal immigrants, to apply for a driver's license. He called it a public safety issue that \"needs to be addressed\". The licenses cannot be used to vote or board a plane and the bill took effect in July 2015.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://courantblogs.com/capitol-watch/malloy-signs-undocumented-immigrants-drivers-license-bill-which-takes-effect-in-2015/ |title=Malloy Signs Undocumented Immigrants Driver's License Bill, Which Takes Effect In 2015 |author=Jenny Wilson |newspaper=[[Hartford Courant]] |date=June 7, 2013 |accessdate=October 27, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029184442/http://courantblogs.com/capitol-watch/malloy-signs-undocumented-immigrants-drivers-license-bill-which-takes-effect-in-2015/ |archive-date=October 29, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n====Other issues====\n[[File:Gov. Malloy Meets with Vice President Biden (8394023050).jpg|thumb|Malloy meets with Vice President [[Joe Biden]] in 2013]]\nAt the end of May 2012, Malloy signed a bill that repealed Connecticut's [[Alcohol laws of the United States|ban on the sale of alcohol on Sundays]]. Connecticut, Georgia, Indiana and Minnesota had previously been the only states that still had broad restrictions on the sale of alcohol on Sundays.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/05/21/nyregion/sunday-liquor-sales-end-an-era-in-connecticut.html |title=Buy Alcohol on Sunday? Connecticut Now Allows It |author=Elizabeth Maker |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=May 20, 2012 |accessdate=October 27, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn response to [[Hurricane Sandy]], Malloy partially activated the state's Emergency Operations Center on October 26, 2012<ref name=\"CT.gov\">{{cite web|title=Governor Malloy to Partially Activate the State Emergency Operations Center at 8am Saturday|url=http://www.governor.ct.gov/malloy/cwp/view.asp?A=4010&Q=513076|work=Hurricane Sandy News and Information|publisher=CT.gov|accessdate=2012-10-27}}</ref> and signed a Declaration of Emergency the next day.<ref name=\"governor.ct.gov\">{{cite web|title=Gov. Malloy Signs Declaration of Emergency|url=http://www.governor.ct.gov/malloy/cwp/view.asp?Q=513088&A=4010|work=Hurricane Sandy News and Information|publisher=CT.gov|accessdate=2012-10-27}}</ref> On October 28, President [[Barack Obama]] approved Connecticut's request for an emergency declaration, and hundreds of [[Connecticut National Guard|National Guard]] personnel were deployed.<ref name=\"thehour.com\">{{cite web|title=Obama approves pre-landfall emergency declaration for Connecticut|url=http://www.thehour.com/news/state/obama-approves-pre-landfall-emergency-declaration-for-connecticut/article_a5384ada-2175-11e2-8370-0019bb30f31a.html|work=The Hour|accessdate=2012-10-29|date=2012-10-28}}</ref> On October 29, Malloy ordered road closures for all state highways.<ref>{{cite web|title=All Connecticut highways closed as Sandy approaches|url=http://abclocal.go.com/wabc/story?section=weather&id=8861658|publisher=WABC TV|accessdate=2012-10-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121029075738/http://abclocal.go.com/wabc/story?section=weather&id=8861658|archive-date=2012-10-29|url-status=dead}}</ref> Numerous mandatory and partial evacuations were issued in cities across Connecticut.<ref name=\"ctnowevac\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ctnow.com/weather/hurricane/hc-townbytown-evacuations-20121028,0,1651268.story|title=Town-By-Town Evacuations|date=October 28, 2012|accessdate=2012-10-29|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121030211934/http://www.ctnow.com/weather/hurricane/hc-townbytown-evacuations-20121028,0,1651268.story|archivedate=October 30, 2012}}</ref> Malloy's strong initial response is credited with helping the state to avoid much of the damage that affected neighbouring [[New York City]] and nearby [[New Jersey]]. Five people were killed and over 30,000 houses were destroyed. The [[Federal Emergency Management Agency]] gave the state over $283 million in the 6 months following the hurricane and in August 2013, Malloy announced that the [[United States Department of Housing and Urban Development|Department of Housing and Urban Development]] was giving another $71.8 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/hurricane-sandy-connecticut-210224758.html |title=Connecticut: Sandy's (sometimes) forgotten victim |author=Dylan Stableford |publisher=[[Yahoo! News]] |date=October 25, 2013 |accessdate=October 27, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Later career==\nMalloy was unanimously chosen by the [[University of Maine System]] Board of Trustees to be its Chancellor on May 30, 2019, with his service beginning on July 1.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.centralmaine.com/2019/05/30/former-connecticut-governor-chosen-to-lead-u-maine-system/ |title=Former Connecticut governor chosen to lead University of Maine system|author=Rachel Ohm|publisher=[[Kennebec Journal]] |date=May 30, 2019 |accessdate=May 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Memberships==\n* Chairman of the [[Democratic Governors Association]], 2015\u2013<ref>{{Cite news|title=Malloy Elected New DGA Chair|newspaper=National Journal|date=7 December 2015 |url=http://www.nationaljournal.com/s/125585/malloy-elected-new-dga-chair}}</ref>\n* Trustee and Vice Chair for Education of the Jobs, Education & Workforce Committee, [[United States Conference of Mayors]]\n* Co-Chair of Small Business/Partner America Task Force, [[United States Conference of Mayors]]\n* Former Member, Executive Committee of the [[Democratic National Committee]]\n* Former President, Connecticut Conference of Municipalities\n* Adjunct Professor, the [[University of Connecticut]]\n* Member, Board of Trustees, [[Mitchell College]], [[New London, Connecticut]]\n* Member, [[Mayors Against Illegal Guns Coalition]]\n\n==Personal life==\n\nMalloy and his wife have been married since 1982. Cathy Malloy is the chief executive officer of the Greater Hartford Arts Council.  She formerly served as  executive director of the Center for Sexual Assault Crisis Counseling and Education serving lower [[Fairfield County, Connecticut|Fairfield County]]. The couple has three sons: Dannel, Ben, and Sam.{{Citation needed|date = November 2017}}\n\n== Electoral history ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"5\" |Connecticut Gubernatorial Democratic primary election, 2006\n|-\n|'''Party'''\n|'''Candidate'''\n|'''Votes'''\n|'''%'''\n|'''\u00b1'''\n|-\n|Democratic\n|'''John DeStefano'''\n|135,431\n|50.78\n|\n|-\n|Democratic\n|Dan Malloy\n|131,258\n|49.22\n|\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"5\" |Connecticut Gubernatorial Democratic primary election, 2010\n|-\n|'''Party'''\n|'''Candidate'''\n|'''Votes'''\n|'''%'''\n|'''\u00b1'''\n|-\n|Democratic\n|'''Dan Malloy'''\n|103,154\n|57.01\n|\n|-\n|Democratic\n|Ned Lamont\n|77,772\n|42.99\n|\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"5\" |Connecticut Gubernatorial election, 2010\n|-\n|'''Party'''\n|'''Candidate'''\n|'''Votes'''\n|'''%'''\n|'''\u00b1'''\n|-\n|Democratic*\n|'''Dan Malloy'''\n|567,278\n|49.51\n|\n|-\n|Republican\n|Tom Foley\n|560,874\n|48.95\n|\n|-\n|Independent\n|Thomas Marsh\n|17,629\n|1.54\n|\n|-\n|Write-in\n|Paul Copp\n|13\n|0.00\n|\n|-\n|Write-in\n|Robert Thibodeau\n|5\n|0.00\n|\n|}\n<nowiki>*</nowiki>Malloy was also listed on the Working Families Party line.\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"5\" |Connecticut Gubernatorial election, 2014\n|-\n|'''Party'''\n|'''Candidate'''\n|'''Votes'''\n|'''%'''\n|'''\u00b1'''\n|-\n|Democratic*\n|'''Dan Malloy (inc.)'''\n|554,314\n|50.73\n|\n|-\n|Republican**\n|Tom Foley\n|526,295\n|48.16\n|\n|-\n|Petition\n|Joe Visconti\n|11,456\n|1.05\n|\n|-\n|Write-in\n|Jonathan Pelto\n|568\n|0.05\n|\n|-\n|Write-in\n|Daniel Gaita\n|108\n|0.01\n|\n|-\n|Write-in\n|John Traceski\n|20\n|0.00\n|\n|-\n|Write-in\n|John Renjillian\n|12\n|0.00\n|}\n<nowiki>*</nowiki>Malloy was also listed on the Working Families Party line.\n\n<nowiki>**</nowiki>Foley was also listed on the Independent Party line.\n\n==See also==\n* [[Connecticut gubernatorial election, 2006]]\n* [[Connecticut gubernatorial election, 2010]]\n* [[Connecticut gubernatorial election, 2014]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* [http://www.ct.gov/malloy Governor Dannel P. Malloy] official government website\n* [http://www.danmalloy.com Dan Malloy for Governor]\n* {{Dmoz|Regional/North_America/United_States/Connecticut/Government/Executive_Branch/Governor_Dannel_P._Malloy|Dannel P. Malloy}}\n* {{C-SPAN|dannelmalloy}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=Stanley Esposito}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Mayor of Stamford, Connecticut|Mayor of Stamford]]|years=1995\u20132009}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Michael Pavia]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Jodi Rell]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[List of Governors of Connecticut|Governor of Connecticut]]|years=2011\u20132019}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Ned Lamont]]}}\n|-\n{{s-ppo}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[John DeStefano, Jr.|John DeStefano]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]] nominee for [[List of Governors of Connecticut|Governor of Connecticut]]|years=[[Connecticut gubernatorial election, 2010|2010]], [[Connecticut gubernatorial election, 2014|2014]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Ned Lamont]]}}\n|-\n{{s-bef|before=[[Steve Bullock (American politician)|Steve Bullock]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=Chair of the [[Democratic Governors Association]]|years=2015\u20132017}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Jay Inslee]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{Governors of Connecticut}}\n{{University of Maine system}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Malloy, Dan}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:20th-century American lawyers]]\n[[Category:21st-century American politicians]]\n[[Category:American gun control activists]]\n[[Category:American people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:American prosecutors]]\n[[Category:American Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:Boston College Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:Catholics from Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Connecticut Democrats]]\n[[Category:Democratic Party state governors of the United States]]\n[[Category:Governors of Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Mayors of Stamford, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Ned Lamont]]\n[[Category:New York (state) lawyers]]\n[[Category:New York County Assistant District Attorneys]]\n[[Category:People with dyslexia]]\n[[Category:University of Connecticut faculty]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Daniel Molloy}}\n{{short description|88th Governor of Connecticut}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name         = Dan Malloy\n|image        = Dannel Malloy 2016.jpg\n|office1      = 13th Chancellor of the<br>[[University of Maine System]]<br>\n|term_start1  = July 1, 2019\n|term_end1    =\n|predecessor1  = [[James H. Page]]\n|successor1    =\n|order2        = 88th [[List of governors of Connecticut|Governor of Connecticut]]\n|lieutenant2   = [[Nancy Wyman]]\n|term_start2   = January 5, 2011\n|term_end2     = January 9, 2019\n|predecessor2  = [[Jodi Rell]]\n|successor2    = [[Ned Lamont]]\n|office3      = 29th [[Mayor of Stamford, Connecticut|Mayor of Stamford]]\n|term_start3  = December 1, 1995\n|term_end3    = December 1, 2009\n|predecessor3 = Stanley Esposito\n|successor3   = [[Michael Pavia]]\n|birth_name   = Dannel Patrick Malloy\n|birth_date   = {{birth date and age|1955|7|21}}\n|birth_place  = [[Stamford, Connecticut]], U.S.\n|death_date   = \n|death_place  = \n|party        = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|spouse       = Cathy Malloy\n|education    = [[Boston College]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]], [[Juris Doctor|JD]])\n|signature    = DannelPMalloySignture.jpg\n}}\n'''Dannel Patrick Malloy''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|d|\u00e6|n|\u0259l|_|m|\u0259|\u02c8|l|\u0254\u026a}}; born July 21, 1955) is an American politician, who served as the [[List of Governors of Connecticut|88th governor of Connecticut]] from 2011 to 2019. A member of the [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic Party]], he chaired the [[Democratic Governors Association]] from 2016 to 2017. On July 1, 2019, he began his tenure as the Chancellor of the [[University of Maine System]].\n\nBorn in [[Stamford, Connecticut]], Malloy is a graduate of [[Boston College Law School]]. Malloy began his career as an assistant district attorney in New York in 1980 before moving back to Stamford and entering private practice. He served on the Stamford board of finance from 1984 to 1994 before being elected Mayor of [[Stamford, Connecticut|Stamford]]. He served four terms as mayor from December 1995 to December 2009.\n\nMalloy ran unsuccessfully for Governor of Connecticut in [[Connecticut gubernatorial election, 2006|2006]], losing the Democratic primary to [[John DeStefano, Jr.]], the [[List of mayors of New Haven, Connecticut|Mayor]] of [[New Haven, Connecticut|New Haven]], who was defeated in the general election by incumbent Republican Governor [[Jodi Rell]]. He ran again in [[Connecticut gubernatorial election, 2010|2010]] and comfortably won the primary, defeating [[Ned Lamont]], the [[United States Senate election in Connecticut, 2006|2006 U.S. Senate nominee]], by 57% of the vote to 43%.<ref name=\"courant.com\">{{cite web|url=http://articles.courant.com/2010-05-23/news/hc-malloy-governor-endorsement-0521_1_greenwich-cable-television-entrepreneur-stamford-mayor-dannel-malloy-clean-elections|title=Dannel Malloy Wins Democratic Endorsement For Governor|work=courant.com|accessdate=21 September 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/11/nyregion/11conn.html|title=Lamont Loses Connecticut Primary for Governor|date=11 August 2010|work=The New York Times|accessdate=21 September 2016}}</ref> Rell did not run for reelection and Malloy faced former [[United States Ambassador to Ireland]] [[Thomas C. Foley]] in the general election, defeating him by fewer than 6,500 votes. Malloy was sworn in on January 5, 2011. He was reelected in a rematch with Foley in [[Connecticut gubernatorial election, 2014|2014]], increasing his margin of victory to over 28,000 votes. As of July 2018, he had a 21% job approval rating and a 71% disapproval rating, making him the second least popular and third most disliked governor in the United States, after [[Mary Fallin]] of [[Oklahoma]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://morningconsult.com/2018/07/25/americas-most-and-least-popular-governors-2/|title=America's Most and Least Popular Governors -- July 2018|date=25 July 2018|publisher=}}</ref> On April 13, 2017, Malloy announced he would not seek reelection in [[Connecticut gubernatorial election, 2018|2018]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.courant.com/politics/hc-gov-malloy-will-not-seek-a-third-term-20170413-story.html|title=In Emotional Remarks, Gov. Malloy Says He Will Not Seek Third Term - Hartford Courant|first=Daniela|last=Altimari|website=courant.com}}</ref> He was succeeded in office by Democrat [[Ned Lamont]] on January 9, 2019.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theday.com/article/20181107/NWS12/181109564|title=Stefanowski concedes race to Lamont: 'He won fair and square'|first1=Mark|last1=Pazniokas|first2=Keith M.|last2=Phaneuf|work=The Day|date=November 7, 2018|accessdate=November 8, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Early life, education and early career==\nDannel Patrick Malloy was born and raised in [[Stamford, Connecticut]], the seventh of seven sons and youngest of the eight children of Agnes Veronica (n\u00e9e Egan), a nurse, and William Francis Malloy.<ref>{{cite web|last=Siedzik|first=Jason|url=http://www.registercitizen.com/articles/2010/08/03/news/doc4c57388607a1d754613517.txt|title=Dan Malloy stands behind the striking employees of Laurel Hill Health Care|publisher=The Register Citizen|accessdate=2012-12-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://familytreemaker.genealogy.com/users/m/a/l/William-F-Malloy/FILE/0001text.txt |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-11-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141015065815/http://familytreemaker.genealogy.com/users/m/a/l/William-F-Malloy/FILE/0001text.txt |archivedate=2014-10-15 }}</ref> He is of Irish descent and was raised as a [[Catholic]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stamfordplus.com/stm/information/nws1/publish/politics/Irish-eyes-were-smiling-at-Governor-Elect-Malloy-in-Stamford-reception10764.shtml|title=Irish eyes were smiling at Governor-elect Malloy in Stamford reception|publisher=Stamfordplus.com|accessdate=2012-12-16}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Lisa Miller|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/on-faith/catholic-activists-pushing-politicians-to-turn-tide-against-the-death-penalty/2012/04/19/gIQAU2EpTT_story.html|title=Catholic activists pushing politicians to turn tide against the death penalty|newspaper=The Washington Post|date=2012-04-19|accessdate=2012-12-16}}</ref>\n\nAs a child, Malloy suffered from [[learning disabilities]] and difficulties with [[motor coordination]]. He did not learn to tie his shoes until the fifth grade. Malloy eventually was diagnosed with [[dyslexia]]<ref>{{cite news|title=AP Interview: Malloy overcame dyslexia, physical struggles|date=May 30, 2006|accessdate=November 14, 2010|url = http://www.ctpost.com/default/article/AP-Interview-Malloy-overcame-dyslexia-physical-112920.php|last=Haigh|first=Susan|agency=Associated Press|newspaper=The Connecticut Post}}</ref><ref name=\"Hernandez\">{{cite news|title=Odds Defied? Malloy Knows the Territory|last=Hernandez|first=Raymond|accessdate=November 14, 2010|date=August 11, 2010|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2010/08/12/nyregion/12malloy.html|newspaper=The New York Times}}</ref> and learned the skills necessary to succeed academically. He does not write or type, and rarely reads from notes in public, but developed an extraordinarily useful memory.<ref>{{Cite news|title=Connecticut Governor, Tackling Budget, Criticizes Christie's Approach|date=February 15, 2011|accessdate=February 16, 2011|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/02/16/nyregion/16malloy.html?_r=1&adxnnl=1&adxnnlx=1297839652-SRcFblaLbQenLjEJtrZZbg|last=Halbfinger|first=David M.|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> He graduated ''[[magna cum laude]]'' from [[Boston College]], where he met his wife Cathy, and later earned his [[Juris Doctor|J.D.]] degree from [[Boston College Law School]].<ref>{{cite news|title=AP Interview: Malloy overcame dyslexia, physical struggles|date=May 30, 2006|accessdate=November 14, 2010|url=http://www.ctpost.com/default/article/AP-Interview-Malloy-overcame-dyslexia-physical-112920.php|last=Haigh|first=Susan|agency=Associated Press|newspaper=The Connecticut Post}}</ref><ref name=\"Hernandez\"/>\n\nAfter passing the [[bar exam]], Malloy served as an [[Assistant District Attorney]] in [[Brooklyn, New York]] from 1980-84. During his tenure as a prosecutor, Malloy tried 23 felony cases, four of them homicides, and won 22 convictions. He was subsequently a partner in the Stamford law firm of Abate and Fox from 1984-95. He served on the Stamford Board of Finance from 1983-94.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.governor.ct.gov/malloy/cwp/view.asp?a=4011&q=471134|title=Governor Dannel P. Malloy profile at Connecticut's Official State Website|first=Department of Information|last=Technology|work=ct.gov|accessdate=September 21, 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Mayor of Stamford (1995\u20132009)==\nIn 1995, he ran successfully for Mayor of Stamford, defeating two-term Republican incumbent Stanley Esposito. At the same time, voters approved a measure to extend the Mayor's term of office from two years to four, effective at the next election. He was re-elected in 1997, 2001 and 2005.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stamfordplus.com/stm/information/nws1/publish/magazine/And-they-re-off5194.shtml|title=And they're off!|author=Bill Squier|publisher=Stamford Plus|date=June 1, 2009|accessdate=October 28, 2013}}</ref>\n\nMalloy made crime reduction a priority during his tenure as mayor; Stamford saw a dramatic decrease in homicides under his administration. Stamford is currently ranked as the 9th safest city in the United States and 3rd safest in the Northeast region<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stamfordplus.com/stm/information/nws1/publish/Local_2/Mayor-releases-crime-statistics-for-first-six-months-of-20095884.shtml|title=StamfordPlus.com News - Mayor releases crime statistics for first six months of 2009|work=stamfordplus.com|accessdate=21 September 2016}}</ref> and for the past six years has ranked in the top 11 safest cities with populations of 100,000 or more, according to the [[FBI]].<ref>Lowe, Zach. [http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-31324427_ITM \"Stamford named ninth safest city in U.S.\"] ''The Advocate'' (Stamford), 2007-06-20. Retrieved on 2009-02-19</ref> Malloy wrote a blog known as \"The Blog That Works\", since deleted, until mid-January 2010.\n\nBudgeting and districting of the various fire departments throughout the city has been unstable since 2007, due to an extended legal conflict between the volunteer departments and the Malloy administration, which sought to consolidate the fire departments against the advice and wishes of the volunteer fire departments.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stamfordadvocate.com/default/article/Stamford-fire-service-consolidation-part-of-272317.php|last=Morganteen|first=Jeff|date=December 2, 2009|title=Stamford fire service consolidation part of Malloy's legacy|publisher=stamfordadvocate.com|accessdate=August 29, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Governor of Connecticut (2011\u20132019)==\n\n===Elections===\n\n====2006====\n{{Main|2006 Connecticut gubernatorial election}}\nIn 2004, Malloy was the first candidate to announce his bid for the Democratic Party nomination for Governor of Connecticut. In a major upset in Malloy's favor, he received the convention endorsement of the Democratic Party on May 20, 2006 by one vote. Malloy lost in the primary election however against [[Mayor of New Haven|New Haven Mayor]] [[John DeStefano, Jr.]] on August 8, 2006.\n\n====2010====\n{{Main|2010 Connecticut gubernatorial election}}\nOn February 3, 2009, Malloy officially filed paperwork with Connecticut's State Elections Enforcement Commission to form a gubernatorial exploratory committee,<ref>Pazniokas, Mark. [http://www.courant.com/news/politics/hcu-govmalloy-0203,0,785420.story \"Stamford Mayor Explores Run For Governor\"]{{Dead link|date=November 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} ''[[The Hartford Courant]]'', 2009-02-03. Retrieved on 2009-02-19</ref> and subsequently announced that he did not intend to seek re-election as Mayor of Stamford.<ref name=\"mayorrun\">Wright, Chase. [http://thestamfordtimes.com/story/464494 \"Malloy focuses on governor's seat\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110717033928/http://thestamfordtimes.com/story/464494 |date=2011-07-17 }}, ''The Stamford Times'', 2009-02-04.</ref> On March 9, 2010, Malloy filed the required paperwork to officially [[Connecticut gubernatorial election, 2010|run for governor]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.stamfordadvocate.com/local/article/Malloy-makes-it-official-he-s-running-for-400115.php|title=Malloy makes it official: he's running for governor|publisher=StamfordAdvocate|date=2010-03-10|accessdate=2010-08-29}}</ref>\n\nMalloy received the Democratic Party's endorsement for governor on May 22, 2010, in a 68-32 vote over 2006 Democratic senatorial candidate [[Ned Lamont]].<ref name=\"courant.com\"/> Connecticut's Democratic Party rules allow any candidate who received more than 15% of the vote at its nominating convention to challenge the endorsed candidate for the nomination in a primary, and Lamont announced that he would challenge Malloy in the gubernatorial primary. The primary was held on August 10, 2010. Malloy won with 58% of the vote, according to [[Associated Press|AP]]-reported unofficial results.<ref name=AP>AP, \"Connecticut \u2013 Summary Vote Results\" ''Daily Coruant'', August 11, 2010. Found at [http://hosted.ap.org/dynamic/files/elections/2010/by_state/CT_Page_0810.html?SITE=CTHARELN&SECTION=POLITICS AP website]; retrieved August 11, 2010.</ref><ref name=Dem>DemFromCT, \"CT primary: Malloy beats Lamont, GOP Gov. leans Foley, McMahon wins but under 50%\", [[DailyKos]], August 10, 2010; see [http://www.dailykos.com/story/2010/8/10/891992/-CT-primary:-Malloy-beats-Lamont,-GOP-Gov.-leans-Foley,-McMahon-wins-but-under-50 DailyKos website]; retrieved August 11, 2010.</ref><ref name=Post>Ken Dixon, \"Foley joins Malloy as primary winner,\" August 10, 2010. Found at [http://www.ctpost.com/news/article/Malloy-stretches-lead-Foley-still-on-top-in-610659.php Connecticut Post website]; retrieved August 11, 2010</ref> According to preliminary numbers, he beat Lamont 101,354 to 73,875.<ref name=AP /><ref name=Dem />\n\nAs a Democratic candidate for governor prior to the Democratic state convention and subsequent primary, Malloy chose [[Nancy Wyman]] to be his running mate. Wyman is the only woman elected [[Connecticut Comptroller|State Comptroller]] since the office was created in 1786. Malloy's choice was confirmed by the Democratic nominating convention on May 22, and Wyman became the official 2010 Democratic candidate for lieutenant governor when she defeated primary opponent Mary Glassman on August 10. After the primaries, candidates for governor and lieutenant governor run together as a team on a single ticket. Thus, Malloy and Wyman were both elected on November 2, 2010.\n\nMalloy faced [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] [[Thomas C. Foley]], the former [[United States Ambassador to Ireland]] under President [[George W. Bush]], in the race for governor. Tom Foley had never been elected to public office. In the last [[Quinnipiac University Polling Institute]] poll released on the morning before [[Election Day]], Malloy trailed Foley 48% to 45%.<ref>Q Poll: Blumenthal Up 9 Points; Governor Too Close To Call.[http://www.courant.com/news/politics/hc-qu-poll-story-1101,0,4009370.story \"Q Poll: Blumenthal Up 9 Points; Governor Too Close To Call\"] \"[[The Hartford Courant]]\", 2010-11-01. Retrieved on 2010-11-01.</ref>\n\nAccording to ''[[The New York Times]]'' on November 3, Malloy was elected governor; they later placed Foley in the lead with no declared winner.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://elections.nytimes.com/2010/results/connecticut?ref=nyregion|title=Connecticut - Election Results 2010 - The New York Times|work=nytimes.com|accessdate=21 September 2016}}</ref> The [[Associated Press]] had at one point also placed Foley ahead by 8,424 votes because they hadn't added the votes from [[New Haven]] or [[Bridgeport]] at that time.<ref name=SAdvocate>{{cite news|url=http://www.stamfordadvocate.com/local/article/Malloy-declared-winner-but-Foley-fights-on-797028.php|title=Malloy declared winner, but Foley fights on |author=Ken Dixon and Bill Cummings|newspaper=[[Stamford Advocate]]|date=November 3, 2010|accessdate=November 4, 2010}}</ref> In the days following the election, there was controversy over [[Connecticut gubernatorial election, 2010#Bridgeport ballot shortage|several polling locations in Bridgeport]] remaining open until 10 p.m. on Election Day due to ballot shortages.<ref name=SAdvocate/> Foley's team looked into the events that took place in [[Bridgeport]] and determined there was insufficient evidence of enough fraud to overcome the vote deficit.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcconnecticut.com/news/politics/Foley-to-Make-Announcement-on-Plans-Today-106883273.html|title=Foley Concedes to Malloy|work=nbcconnecticut.com|accessdate=21 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n====2014====\n{{Main|2014 Connecticut gubernatorial election}}\nOn March 28, 2014, Malloy announced his intention to seek a second term.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.courant.com/2014-03-28/news/hc-malloy-seeking-reelection-20140328_1_re-election-plans-press-conference-capitol-complex|title=Gov. Dannel P. Malloy: Gov. Dannel P. Malloy Announces Re-Election Bid|work=courant.com|accessdate=21 September 2016}}</ref> With full support, he was unopposed in the Democratic primary. On August 12, [[Thomas C. Foley|Tom Foley]], Malloy's Republican opponent in 2010, won his party's nomination,<ref name=2014primaryresults>{{cite web |url=http://www.sots.ct.gov/sots/lib/sots/electionservices/ElectionResults/2014_Town_Primary_Returns/August_12_2014_Primary_Unofficial_Results.pdf |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140903064952/http://www.sots.ct.gov/sots/lib/sots/electionservices/ElectionResults/2014_Town_Primary_Returns/August_12_2014_Primary_Unofficial_Results.pdf |url-status=dead |archive-date=September 3, 2014 |title=Unofficial primary results |publisher=Connecticut Secretary of State |date=August 12, 2014 |accessdate=August 28, 2014 }}</ref> making the 2014 election a rematch of the bitter 2010 contest. As expected, the race was very close. On November 4, Malloy won reelection with 51.1 percent of the vote.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.statementofvote-sots.ct.gov/StatementOfVote/WebModules/ReportsLink/OfficeTitle.aspx|title=OfficeTitle|work=ct.gov|accessdate=21 September 2016|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141013005918/http://www.statementofvote-sots.ct.gov/StatementOfVote/WebModules/ReportsLink/OfficeTitle.aspx|archivedate=13 October 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2014-11-05/connecticut-governor-race-deadlocked-in-rematch-of-2010-contest.html | work=Bloomberg | first=Brian | last=Chappatta | title=Connecticut's Malloy Wins Re-Election as Foley Concedes | date=November 5, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/11/06/nyregion/dannel-malloy-thomas-foley-connecticut-governors-race.html?_r=0 | work=The New York Times | first=Benjamin | last=Mueller | title=Dannel Malloy, in Repeat, Wins a Close Election for Connecticut Governor | date=November 5, 2014}}</ref> Foley conceded the election on November 5 without direct communication with Malloy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcconnecticut.com/news/local/governors-race-election-decision-2014-results-malloy-foley-281536171.html|title=Foley Concedes Governor's Race to Malloy|work=nbcconnecticut.com|accessdate=21 September 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Tenure===\n[[File:Inauguration of Governor Dannel P. Malloy (5344187708).jpg|thumb|Dan Malloy taking the oath of office, January 2011]]\nMalloy was sworn in as the 88th Governor of Connecticut on January 5, 2011, succeeding Republican Governor [[Jodi Rell]].\n\nIn the state's legislative elections of November 2012, Republicans tried to tie Democratic legislators to Malloy, who had consistently faced negative job approval ratings.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.npr.org/blogs/itsallpolitics/2013/08/25/214133469/a-guide-to-the-nations-most-vulnerable-governors |title=A Guide To The Nation's Most Vulnerable Governors |author=Alan Greenblatt |publisher=[[NPR]] |date=August 25, 2013 |accessdate=October 27, 2013}}</ref> The strategy did not work and the Democrats recorded no losses in either house. Malloy called the results a \"vindication\" and said that \"Tough times require tough decisions that are not immediately popular... you should not be afraid to make tough decisions, particularly if you are transparent about those decisions, if you explain why those decisions were necessary. In our case, the tough decisions we had to make were in fact caused by Republican governors.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ctmirror.org/story/2012/11/08/malloy-sees-vindication-2012-election-results |title=Malloy sees vindication in 2012 election results |author=Mark Pazniokas |publisher=The CT Mirror |date=November 8, 2012 |accessdate=October 27, 2013}}</ref>\n\nAccording to a July 2016 ''[[The New York Times|New York Times]]'' survey, Malloy was the most unpopular Democratic governor in the country, with a 64% disapproval and 29% approval rating, and the second-most unpopular overall, after [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican]] [[Sam Brownback]] of [[Governor of Kansas|Kansas]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Parlapiano|first=Alicia|title=Pence Ranks Low in Approval, but Not as Low as Trump and Clinton|url=https://www.nytimes.com/interactive/2016/07/14/us/politics/mike-pence-approval-rating-governors.html?_r=0|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=July 15, 2016|accessdate=August 21, 2016}}</ref>\n\n====Economy====\nThe first task facing Malloy upon taking office was addressing a multibillion-dollar deficit as a result of the prior state budget enacted by the Democratic super-majority-controlled legislature which Rell chose to accept without signing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wtnh.com/dpp/news/hartford_cty/Hartford-rell-looks-to-fix-2011%27s-budget-deficit |title=Hartford Rell looks to fix 2011's budget deficit &#124; WTNH.com Connecticut |publisher=Wtnh.com |date= |accessdate=2012-08-17}}</ref> Malloy adopted what he called an agenda of \"shared sacrifice\" which was dependent on increases in various taxes, including the income tax, the gas tax, the sales tax, and the estate tax, as well as $1 billion each year in union concessions.<ref>{{cite web|author=|url=http://articles.courant.com/2011-02-17/news/hc-ed-malloy-budget-sacrifice-0217-20110217_1_spending-cuts-cuts-in-state-programs-state-workers |title=Malloy's Budget Pitch: 'Shared Sacrifice' \u2013 Hartford Courant |publisher=Articles.courant.com |date=2011-02-17 |accessdate=2012-08-17}}</ref> Malloy chose not to reduce aid to municipalities as part of his budget agenda,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://articles.courant.com/2011-02-16/news/hc-malloy-cities-towns-0217-20110216_1_town-aid-road-municipal-aid-mayors-and-first-selectmen |title=City And Town Aid Escape Malloy's Budget-Cutting \u2013 Hartford Courant |publisher=Articles.courant.com |date=2011-02-16 |accessdate=2012-08-17}}</ref> although such aid would have been jeopardized if labor concessions were not reached.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thehour.com/story/502842 |title=Malloy may cut municipal aid if unions don't concede \u2013 The Hour Publishing Company: Norwalk |publisher=Thehour.com |date=2011-04-13 |accessdate=2012-08-17}}</ref> After two months of negotiations, in May 2011, Malloy won $1.6 billion in union [[givebacks]]. The budget deal meant that, in contrast to many other states, there were no layoffs.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2011/05/14/nyregion/connecticut-reaches-deal-with-unions-to-close-budget-shortfall.html |title=Connecticut Unions Agree to $1.6 Billion in Givebacks |author=Peter Applebome |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=May 13, 2011 |accessdate=October 27, 2013}}</ref> Many of Malloy's proposed tax increases were unpopular,<ref>{{cite web|author=LeAnne Gendreau |url=http://www.nbcconnecticut.com/news/politics/Most-Disapprove-of-Malloy-Poll--117639723.html |title=Most Disapprove of Malloy: Poll |publisher=NBC Connecticut |date=2011-03-09 |accessdate=2012-08-17}}</ref> despite a statewide \"listening tour\" to promote the budget.<ref>{{cite web|author=Colin McEnroe|url=http://www.courant.com/news/opinion/hc-op-mcenroe-budget-malloy-republica20110424,0,3090603.column?track=rss |title=Looking For Sequel To Malloy's Budget Show \u2013 Hartford Courant |publisher=Courant.com |date=2011-04-24 |accessdate=2012-08-17}}</ref>\n\n====Marijuana====\nIn June 2011, Malloy signed a bill that [[Places that have decriminalized non-medical cannabis in the United States|decriminalized possession of small amounts of marijuana]]. Offenders pay a $150 fine for a first offense and a fine ranging from $200 to $500 for subsequent offenses. Those younger than 21 face a 60-day driver's license suspension. Paraphernalia has also been decriminalized as long as the person possesses under 1/2 an ounce of marijuana. Offenders may still be arrested for under 1/2 an ounce or a pipe if they are in a school zone and there is a [[Mandatory sentencing|mandatory minimum sentence]] (MMS) of 3 years. There is also an MMS of 3 years for sale to a minor.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nbcconnecticut.com/news/politics/Marijuana-Decriminalization-Bill-Passes-123381848.html |title=Marijuana Decriminalization Bill Passes |publisher=NBC Connecticut |date= |accessdate=2013-07-06}}</ref>\n\nConnecticut became the 17th state to [[Medical cannabis in the United States|legalize medical marijuana]] on June 1, 2012 after Malloy signed a bill into law. Some portions of the law were effective immediately while the remaining portions became effective on October 1, 2012.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2012/06/01/us-usa-marijuana-connecticut-idUSBRE85018X20120601?feedType=RSS&feedName=domesticNews | work=Reuters | title=Medical marijuana legalized in Connecticut | date=2012-06-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.cga.ct.gov/2012/BA/2012HB-05389-R010597-BA.htm | work=State of Connecticut | title=OLR Bill Analysis \u2013 AN ACT CONCERNING THE PALLIATIVE USE OF MARIJUANA. | date=2012-10-20}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2016, Malloy publicly stated that he opposed the legalization of recreational marijuana in [[Connecticut]] and that he would not support legislative efforts at legalization.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.courant.com/politics/capitol-watch/hc-malloy-blasts-legalizing-recreational-marijuana-20161215-story.html |title=Malloy Blasts Legalizing Recreational Marijuana |newspaper=Hartford Courant |accessdate=2016-12-15}}</ref>\n\n====LGBT equality====\nMalloy supports progressive social measures, including protections for transgender identity. Malloy praised the Transgender Rights Bill HB 6599<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cga.ct.gov/asp/cgabillstatus/cgabillstatus.asp?selBillType=Bill&bill_num=HB-6599 |title=Bill Status |publisher=Cga.ct.gov |date= |accessdate=2012-08-17}}</ref> and promised he would sign it into law. It passed the legislature and he signed it on July 5, 2011.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2011/07/06/connecticut-gender-identity-discrimination-dan-malloy_n_891739.html |title=Connecticut Gender Identity Anti-Discrimination Bill Signed By Governor Dan Malloy |work=[[The Huffington Post]] |date=July 6, 2011 |accessdate=October 27, 2013}}</ref> The bill protects the rights of transgender residents, including the right to use public facilities of the gender a person identifies with.<ref>{{cite news| url=http://www.boston.com/news/local/connecticut/articles/2011/06/05/conn_passes_transgender_rights_bill/ | work=The Boston Globe | title=Conn. passes transgender rights bill | date=June 5, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Advocate.com Editors |url=http://www.advocate.com/News/Daily_News/2011/06/07/Conn_Trans_Rights_Bill_a_Sure_Thing/ |title=Conn Trans Rights Bill a Sure Thing |publisher=Advocate.com |date=2011-06-07 |accessdate=2012-08-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://newyork.cbslocal.com/2011/05/20/connecticut-house-passes-transgender-rights-bill/ |title=Connecticut House Passes Transgender Rights Bill; Moves On To Senate \u00ab CBS New York |publisher=Newyork.cbslocal.com |date=2011-05-20 |accessdate=2012-08-17}}</ref>\n\n====Labor laws====\nOn September 21, 2011, Malloy issued Executive Orders 9 and 10, which would allow the [[Service Employees International Union]] to unionize day care workers subsidized through Care 4 Kids and [[personal care assistant|personal care attendants]] under Medicaid waivers by redefining these employees as state employees for [[collective bargaining]] purposes.<ref>{{cite web|author=Office of Governor Malloy |url=http://www.governor.ct.gov/malloy/cwp/view.asp?Q=487166&A=4010 |title=Governor Malloy: Gov. Malloy Advances Workers' Rights for Personal Care Attendants, Family Child Care Providers |publisher=Governor.ct.gov |date=2011-09-21 |accessdate=2012-08-17}}</ref> The executive orders generated intense opposition from child care providers, personal care attendants, their employers with disabilities, the [[National Federation of Independent Business]], and We the People of Connecticut, a constitutionalist organization.<ref>{{cite web|last=Levin Becker|first=Arielle|title=GOP hearing challenges Malloy order on home care attendants|url=http://ctmirror.org/story/14477/pca-executive-orders|publisher=CT Mirror|accessdate=24 November 2011|date=10 November 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111114011206/http://www.ctmirror.org/story/14477/pca-executive-orders|archive-date=14 November 2011|url-status=dead}}</ref> Disability advocates objected to being excluded from the decision-making process, to union interference in the intimate relationship between employers and PCAs, and to the likely loss of PCA hours under a capped program; NFIB feared a \"terrible precedent\" in allowing other union organizing drives of small businesses by executive order through [[card check]]; and legislators viewed Malloy's actions as a violation of the state Constitution's [[separation of powers]]. Malloy responded that these workers, whom he described as being among the hardest working and lowest paid, deserved the opportunity to collectively bargain if they wished to do so.\n\n====Criminal justice====\nMalloy, who has long campaigned against [[capital punishment]],<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.courant.com/2010-10-06/news/hc-gubernatorial-debate-1006-20101005_1_death-penalty-foley-malloy-democrat-dannel-malloy |title=Tom Foley, Dan Malloy Clash On Death Penalty, Jobs, Records In Gubernatorial Debate |author=Christopher Keating |newspaper=[[Hartford Courant]] |date=May 20, 2012 |accessdate=October 27, 2013}}</ref> signed a bill to repeal [[Capital punishment in Connecticut|the state's death penalty]] on April 25, 2012. The bill was not retroactive and did not affect those on death row in Connecticut at the time.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.businessinsider.com/connecticut-abolishes-death-penalty-not-that-it-actually-ever-had-one-2012-4 |title=Connecticut Abolishes The Death Penalty, Not That It Actually Ever Had One |author=Brett Logiurato |website=[[Business Insider]] |date=April 12, 2012 |accessdate=October 27, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2012/04/25/connecticut-governor-signs-bill-to-repeal-death-penalty/|title=Connecticut governor signs bill to repeal death penalty|date=April 25, 2012|work=FOXNews.com|publisher=FOX News Network, LLC.|accessdate=April 25, 2012}}</ref> On August 13, 2015, however, the [[Connecticut Supreme Court]] ruled in 2015 in ''State v. Santiago'' that the legislature's decision to prospectively abolish capital punishment rendered it an offense to \"evolving standards of decency,\" thus commuting the sentences of the 11 men remaining on death row to life in prison without parole.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.ctnewsjunkie.com/archives/entry/connecticut_supreme_court_rules_death_penalty_unconstitutional/|title=Connecticut Supreme Court Rules Death Penalty Unconstitutional|publisher=CT News Junkie|date=August 13, 2015|accessdate=August 13, 2015}}</ref> Malloy was in the process of having Connecticut be the first state in the nation to raise the age of being within the juvenile system from 18 to 21 via the Second Chance initiative.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/01/04/opinion/connecticuts-second-chance-society.html?_r=0|title=Connecticut's Second-Chance |date=January 4, 2016|work=nytimes.com|publisher=New York Times|accessdate=May 2, 2016}}</ref>{{needs update|date=August 2019}}\n\n====Education====\nMalloy's \"centerpiece\" education reform bill was unanimously passed by the [[Connecticut House of Representatives]] and signed into law in early May 2012. The bill increases funding for early childhood education and poorer school districts, creates 1,000 more preschool places, creates a kindergarten to third grade literacy pilot program and reformed teacher tenure, tying it to performance.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.courant.com/2012-05-09/news/hc-house-education-reform-0509-20120508_1_school-reform-bill-education-reform-achievement-gap |title=House Unanimously Passes Education Reform Bill |author1=Kathleen Megan |author2=Daniela Altimari |newspaper=[[Hartford Courant]] |date=May 9, 2012 |accessdate=October 27, 2013}}</ref>\n\n====Voting====\nAlso in May 2012, Malloy signed a bill that expanded voting rights in Connecticut, allowing for same-day voter registration. Other provisions to allow early voting and \"no-excuse\" absentee ballots will be subject to a referendum, to be held in 2014.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.courant.com/2013-05-09/news/hc-connecticut-senate-gives-final-approval-to-constitutional-amendment-on-early-voting-20130508_1_absentee-ballots-voting-rights-voting-laws |title=Connecticut Senate Gives Final Approval To Constitutional Amendment On Early Voting |author=Daniela Altimari |newspaper=[[Hartford Courant]] |date=May 9, 2012 |accessdate=October 27, 2013}}</ref> It also allows for online voter registration, beginning in 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ctmirror.org/story/2012/05/05/senate-gives-final-approval-election-day-registration |title=Senate gives final approval to Election Day registration |author=Keith M. Phaneuf |publisher=The CT Mirror |date=May 5, 2012 |accessdate=October 27, 2013}}</ref>\n\n====Gun laws====\nIn the wake of the [[Sandy Hook Elementary School shooting]] in [[Newtown, Connecticut|Newtown]] in December 2012, Malloy pushed for strict new [[Gun laws in Connecticut|gun control laws]]. In April 2013, he signed into law a bill that passed the legislature with bipartisan support and required [[universal background checks]], banned [[magazine (firearms)|magazines]] with a capacity of more than 10 rounds, created the country's first registry for dangerous-weapon offenders and added over 100 types of gun to the state's [[assault weapon]]s ban.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nydailynews.com/news/national/connecticut-governor-signs-tough-gun-law-article-1.1307902 |title=Connecticut Governor Dannel Malloy signs bill with gun-control laws among the toughest in nation |newspaper=[[Daily News (New York)|Daily News]] |date=April 4, 2013 |accessdate=October 27, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2015, Malloy announced he would issue an executive order to prohibit anyone on federal terrorist watchlists (such as the [[No Fly List]]) from obtaining the permits required to acquire firearms in Connecticut.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/12/11/nyregion/connecticut-to-ban-gun-sales-to-those-on-federal-terrorism-lists.html|title=Connecticut to Ban Gun Sales to Those on Federal Terrorism Lists|date=11 December 2015|work=The New York Times|accessdate=21 September 2016}}</ref> The executive order would also revoke existing permits for people on such lists.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-connecticut-guns-idUSKBN0TT2EM20151210|title=Connecticut to ban gun sales to people on watch lists: governor|date=10 December 2015|publisher=|accessdate=21 September 2016|via=Reuters}}</ref>\n\n====Immigration laws====\nOn June 7, 2013, Malloy signed a bill that allows all residents of Connecticut, including illegal immigrants, to apply for a driver's license. He called it a public safety issue that \"needs to be addressed\". The licenses cannot be used to vote or board a plane and the bill took effect in July 2015.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://courantblogs.com/capitol-watch/malloy-signs-undocumented-immigrants-drivers-license-bill-which-takes-effect-in-2015/ |title=Malloy Signs Undocumented Immigrants Driver's License Bill, Which Takes Effect In 2015 |author=Jenny Wilson |newspaper=[[Hartford Courant]] |date=June 7, 2013 |accessdate=October 27, 2013 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131029184442/http://courantblogs.com/capitol-watch/malloy-signs-undocumented-immigrants-drivers-license-bill-which-takes-effect-in-2015/ |archive-date=October 29, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n====Other issues====\n[[File:Gov. Malloy Meets with Vice President Biden (8394023050).jpg|thumb|Malloy meets with Vice President [[Joe Biden]] in 2013]]\nAt the end of May 2012, Malloy signed a bill that repealed Connecticut's [[Alcohol laws of the United States|ban on the sale of alcohol on Sundays]]. Connecticut, Georgia, Indiana and Minnesota had previously been the only states that still had broad restrictions on the sale of alcohol on Sundays.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2012/05/21/nyregion/sunday-liquor-sales-end-an-era-in-connecticut.html |title=Buy Alcohol on Sunday? Connecticut Now Allows It |author=Elizabeth Maker |newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=May 20, 2012 |accessdate=October 27, 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn response to [[Hurricane Sandy]], Malloy partially activated the state's Emergency Operations Center on October 26, 2012<ref name=\"CT.gov\">{{cite web|title=Governor Malloy to Partially Activate the State Emergency Operations Center at 8am Saturday|url=http://www.governor.ct.gov/malloy/cwp/view.asp?A=4010&Q=513076|work=Hurricane Sandy News and Information|publisher=CT.gov|accessdate=2012-10-27}}</ref> and signed a Declaration of Emergency the next day.<ref name=\"governor.ct.gov\">{{cite web|title=Gov. Malloy Signs Declaration of Emergency|url=http://www.governor.ct.gov/malloy/cwp/view.asp?Q=513088&A=4010|work=Hurricane Sandy News and Information|publisher=CT.gov|accessdate=2012-10-27}}</ref> On October 28, President [[Barack Obama]] approved Connecticut's request for an emergency declaration, and hundreds of [[Connecticut National Guard|National Guard]] personnel were deployed.<ref name=\"thehour.com\">{{cite web|title=Obama approves pre-landfall emergency declaration for Connecticut|url=http://www.thehour.com/news/state/obama-approves-pre-landfall-emergency-declaration-for-connecticut/article_a5384ada-2175-11e2-8370-0019bb30f31a.html|work=The Hour|accessdate=2012-10-29|date=2012-10-28}}</ref> On October 29, Malloy ordered road closures for all state highways.<ref>{{cite web|title=All Connecticut highways closed as Sandy approaches|url=http://abclocal.go.com/wabc/story?section=weather&id=8861658|publisher=WABC TV|accessdate=2012-10-29|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121029075738/http://abclocal.go.com/wabc/story?section=weather&id=8861658|archive-date=2012-10-29|url-status=dead}}</ref> Numerous mandatory and partial evacuations were issued in cities across Connecticut.<ref name=\"ctnowevac\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ctnow.com/weather/hurricane/hc-townbytown-evacuations-20121028,0,1651268.story|title=Town-By-Town Evacuations|date=October 28, 2012|accessdate=2012-10-29|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121030211934/http://www.ctnow.com/weather/hurricane/hc-townbytown-evacuations-20121028,0,1651268.story|archivedate=October 30, 2012}}</ref> Malloy's strong initial response is credited with helping the state to avoid much of the damage that affected neighbouring [[New York City]] and nearby [[New Jersey]]. Five people were killed and over 30,000 houses were destroyed. The [[Federal Emergency Management Agency]] gave the state over $283 million in the 6 months following the hurricane and in August 2013, Malloy announced that the [[United States Department of Housing and Urban Development|Department of Housing and Urban Development]] was giving another $71.8 million.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.yahoo.com/hurricane-sandy-connecticut-210224758.html |title=Connecticut: Sandy's (sometimes) forgotten victim |author=Dylan Stableford |publisher=[[Yahoo! News]] |date=October 25, 2013 |accessdate=October 27, 2013}}</ref>\n\n==Later career==\nMalloy was unanimously chosen by the [[University of Maine System]] Board of Trustees to be its Chancellor on May 30, 2019, with his service beginning on July 1.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.centralmaine.com/2019/05/30/former-connecticut-governor-chosen-to-lead-u-maine-system/ |title=Former Connecticut governor chosen to lead University of Maine system|author=Rachel Ohm|publisher=[[Kennebec Journal]] |date=May 30, 2019 |accessdate=May 30, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Memberships==\n* Chairman of the [[Democratic Governors Association]], 2015\u2013<ref>{{Cite news|title=Malloy Elected New DGA Chair|newspaper=National Journal|date=7 December 2015 |url=http://www.nationaljournal.com/s/125585/malloy-elected-new-dga-chair}}</ref>\n* Trustee and Vice Chair for Education of the Jobs, Education & Workforce Committee, [[United States Conference of Mayors]]\n* Co-Chair of Small Business/Partner America Task Force, [[United States Conference of Mayors]]\n* Former Member, Executive Committee of the [[Democratic National Committee]]\n* Former President, Connecticut Conference of Municipalities\n* Adjunct Professor, the [[University of Connecticut]]\n* Member, Board of Trustees, [[Mitchell College]], [[New London, Connecticut]]\n* Member, [[Mayors Against Illegal Guns Coalition]]\n\n==Personal life==\n\nMalloy and his wife have been married since 1982. Cathy Malloy is the chief executive officer of the Greater Hartford Arts Council.  She formerly served as  executive director of the Center for Sexual Assault Crisis Counseling and Education serving lower [[Fairfield County, Connecticut|Fairfield County]]. The couple has three sons: Dannel, Ben, and Sam.{{Citation needed|date = November 2017}}\n\n== Electoral history ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"5\" |Connecticut Gubernatorial Democratic primary election, 2006\n|-\n|'''Party'''\n|'''Candidate'''\n|'''Votes'''\n|'''%'''\n|'''\u00b1'''\n|-\n|Democratic\n|'''John DeStefano'''\n|135,431\n|50.78\n|\n|-\n|Democratic\n|Dan Malloy\n|131,258\n|49.22\n|\n|}\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! colspan=\"5\" |Connecticut Gubernatorial Democratic primary election, 2010\n|-\n|'''Party'''\n|'''