or\n| leader_name1                    = Yasim Sadiq\n| leader_title2                   = Vice Mayor\n| unit_pref                       = <!--Enter: Imperial, if Imperial (metric) is desired-->\n| area_footnotes                  = <!-- ([[List of China administrative regions by area|ranked 29th]]) -->\n| area_total_km2                  = 14577\n| area_urban_km2                  = 583<!--ALL\n fields dealing with a measurements are subject to automatic unit conversion-->\n| area_land_km2                   = <!--See table @ Template:Infobox Settlement for details on automatic unit conversion-->\n| population_est                  = 3,550,000\n| pop_est_as_of                   = 2015\n| pop_est_footnotes               = <ref name=\"2015 Pop Estimate\">{{cite web|title=Bulletin for the economical and social development in 2015 |url=http://tjj.urumqi.gov.cn/tjsj/283763.htm |accessdate=March 16, 2016}}</ref>\n| population_urban                = 3,575,000\n| population_urban_footnotes      = (2017)<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://www.demographia.com/db-worldua.pdf|title=Demographia World Urban Areas. 14th Annual Edition|last=Cox|first=W|publisher=Demographia|year=2018|isbn=|location=St. Louis|pages=22}}</ref>\n| population_as_of                = 2017 census\n| population_total                = 3519600\n| population_density_km2          = auto\n| timezone                        = ''[[De jure]]'': [[China Standard Time|China Standard]] ([[UTC+08:00]])<br/>''[[De facto]]'': both [[China Standard Time|China Standard]] ([[UTC+08:00]]) and [[Xinjiang Time|\u00dcr\u00fcmqi Time]] ([[UTC+06:00]])\n| coordinates                     = {{coord|43|49|30|N|87|36|00|E|type:adm2nd_region:CN-65|display=it}}\n| elevation_footnotes             = <!--for references: use <ref> </ref> tags-->\n| postal_code_type                = [[Postal code of China|Postal code]]\n| postal_code                     = 830000\n| area_code_type                  = [[Telephone numbers in China|Area code]]\n| area_code                       = 991\n| blank_name                      = [[License Plate (China)|License plate prefixes]]\n| blank_info                      = {{lang|zh-cn|\u65b0A}}\n| iso_code                        = [[ISO 3166-2:CN|CN-XJ-01]]\n| blank2_name                     = [[Gross domestic product|GDP]] (2017)\n| blank2_info                     = [[Renminbi|CNY]]\uffe5 274.4 billion <br/> US $40.65billion\n| blank3_name                     = GDP per capita\n| blank3_info                     = [[Renminbi|CNY]] \uffe577958 <br/> US $11549\n| website                         = [http://www.urumqi.gov.cn/ www.urumqi.gov.cn] {{in lang|zh}}\n}}\n{{Infobox Chinese\n|pic=Urumqi (Chinese and Uighur).svg\n|piccap= \"\u00dcr\u00fcmqi\" in [[Simplified Chinese characters|Simplified Chinese]] (top), [[Traditional Chinese characters|Traditional Chinese]] (middle) and [[Uyghur Arabic alphabet|Uyghur Arabic]] (bottom) scripts\n|picupright=0.8\n|t = {{linktext|\u70cf\u9b6f\u6728\u9f4a}}\n|s = {{linktext|\u4e4c\u9c81\u6728\u9f50}}\n|p = W\u016bl\u01d4m\u00f9q\u00ed\n|w = Wu<sup>1</sup>-lu<sup>3</sup>-mu<sup>4</sup>-ch{{asper}}i<sup>2</sup>\n|j = Wu1lou5muk6cai4\n|l = \"Beautiful pasture\" (in [[Mongol language|Mongol]])<!-- the Mandarin name is merely a transliteration and is thus meaningless. -->\n|mi = {{IPAc-cmn|wu|1|.|l|u|3|.|m|u|4|.|q|i|2}}\n|gr = Uluumuhchyi\n|bpmf = \u3128&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\u310c\u3128\u02c7&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\u3107\u3128\u02cb&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\u3111\u3127\u02ca\n|order = st\n|uig = {{script/Arabic|\u0626\u06c8\u0631\u06c8\u0645\u0686\u0649}}\n|uly = \u00dcr\u00fcmchi\n|uyy = \u00dcr\u00fcmqi\n|sgs = \u00dcr\u00fcmqi\n|usy = \u04ae\u0440\u04af\u043c\u0447\u0438\n|uipa = {{IPA-ug|\u028fr\u028fm\u02c8t\u0283i|}}\n|mon = \u04e8\u0440\u04e9\u043c\u0447\n|mong = \u1825\u1837\u1825\u182e\u1834\u1822\n|psp = Urumtsi\n|altname = Dihua\n|psp2=Tihwa\n|c2 = {{linktext|\u8fea\u5316}}\n|p2 = D\u00edhu\u00e0\n|w2 = Ti<sup>2</sup>-hua<sup>4</sup>\n|bpmf2 = \u3109\u3127\u02ca&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;\u310f\u3128\u311a\u02cb\n|gr2 = Dyihuah\n|mi2 = {{IPAc-cmn|d|i|2|.|h|ua|4}}\n|showflag = p\n|l2 = \"To enlighten (the uncivilized people)\"\n}}\n{{Contains Uyghur text}}\n\n'''\u00dcr\u00fcmqi''' or '''Urumchi''' ({{IPAc-en|UK|\u028a|\u02c8|r|\u028a|m|t\u0283|i}},<ref>{{cite web|title=Urumqi|url=https://en.oxforddictionaries.com/definition/urumqi|website=Oxford Living Dictionaries - English|accessdate=29 December 2017}}</ref> {{IPAc-en|US|\u02cc|\u028ar|\u028a|m|\u02c8|t\u0283|i\u02d0}};<ref>{{cite web|title=Urumqi|url=https://en.oxforddictionaries.com/definition/us/urumqi|website=Oxford Living Dictionaries - US English|accessdate=29 December 2017}}</ref> {{IPA-ug|\u028fr\u028fm\u02c8t\u0283i}}; {{lang-ug|\u0626\u06c8\u0631\u06c8\u0645\u0686\u0649}}, [[Common Turkic Alphabet|CTA]]: \u00dcr\u00fcm\u00e7i; {{lang-zh|s=\u4e4c\u9c81\u6728\u9f50|p=W\u016bl\u01d4m\u00f9q\u00ed}}), abbreviated '''Wushi''' ({{lang-zh|s=\u4e4c\u5e02|p=W\u016bsh\u00ec}}), formerly known as '''Tihwa''' ({{lang-zh|s=\u8fea\u5316|p=D\u00edhu\u00e0}}), is the capital of the [[Xinjiang|Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region]] in the far [[Northwest China|northwest]] of the [[China|People's Republic of China]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Illuminating China's Provinces, Municipalities and Autonomous Regions|url=http://www.china.org.cn/english/features/43608.htm|publisher=PRC Central Government Official Website|accessdate=17 May 2014}}</ref> \u00dcr\u00fcmqi was a major hub on the [[Silk Road]] during China's [[Tang dynasty]] and developed its reputation as a leading [[cultural]] and commercial center during the [[Qing dynasty]] in the 19th century.\n\nWith an estimated population of 3.5 million in 2015, \u00dcr\u00fcmqi is the second-largest city in China's northwestern interior as well as the largest in [[Central Asia]] in terms of population.<ref name=\"2015 Pop Estimate\">{{cite web|title=Bulletin for the economical and social development in 2015 |url=http://tjj.urumqi.gov.cn/tjsj/283763.htm |accessdate=March 16, 2016}}</ref> According to the Guinness Book of Records, \u00dcr\u00fcmqi is the most remote city from any sea in the world.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=keCMNVyeroYC&pg=PA29&lpg=PA29&dq=Guinness+Book+of+Records+most+remote+city+from+sea#v=onepage&q=Guinness%20Book%20of%20Records%20most%20remote%20city%20from%20sea&f=false|title=Guinness World Records 2008|last=Glenday|first=Craig|date=2008-04-29|publisher=Bantam Books|isbn=9780553589955|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.guinnessworldrecords.com/world-records/land-farthest-from-sea|title=Land farthest from sea|work=Guinness World Records|access-date=2017-09-07|language=en-GB}}</ref> \u00dcr\u00fcmqi has seen significant economical development since the 1990s and currently serves as a [[List of transport topics#Nodes|regional transport node]] and a cultural, political and commercial center.\n\n== History ==\n\nAlthough \u00dcr\u00fcmqi is situated near the northern route of the [[Silk Road]], the present city is a relatively young city. The earliest known settlement in the area can be dated to the 7th century CE, but there was no permanent settlement for a long period and it was not known as \u00dcr\u00fcmqi until the [[Dzungar Khanate]] in the 17th century, and the current city dates from the rebuilding started in the 18th century.\n\n=== Early period ===\nDuring prehistory, the [[Gushi culture|Jushi]] or Gushi, a nomadic people who lived on the northern slopes of the Tianshan Mountains, inhabited the area.\n\nThe oldest known settlement in the area, a village called '''Urabo''' (or Wulabo), was located about {{convert|10|km|0|abbr=off}} from the southern suburbs of present-day \u00dcr\u00fcmqi.  Under the name '''Luntai''', the  city was established near Urabo by the [[Tang dynasty|Tang]] government during the 22nd year of [[Emperor Taizong of Tang|Emperor Taizong]]'s reign (648 AD), as part of the [[Protectorate General to Pacify the West]] that controlled Xinjiang.<ref name=chinatoday>{{cite web|url=http://www.chinatoday.com.cn/English/chinatours/urumqi.htm |title=Urumqi |publisher=Chinatoday.com.cn |date=1 February 1954 |access-date=19 February 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20021021001913/http://www.chinatoday.com.cn/English/chinatours/urumqi.htm |archive-date=21 October 2002 |url-status=dead }}</ref> It was a seat of local government, and collected taxes from the [[caravan (travellers)|caravans]] along the northern route of the Silk Road.<ref name=chinatoday />\n\nAfter the Tang retreated from the [[Western Regions]], the region came under the control of the [[Uyghurs]] of the [[Uyghur Khaganate|Khaganate]] and [[Gaochang]]/[[Qocho]]. After the Tang until the Qing Dynasty, there was little information about the \u00dcr\u00fcmqi area, and there appeared to be no permanent settlement here for most of this period. The Mongols referred to the wider area as [[Beshbalik|Bishbalik]] meaning five cities, referring to the five towns that surrounded the present-day \u00dcr\u00fcmqi area.<ref name=\"piper\"/>\n\n===Dzungar period===\nThe [[Oirats]] [[Dzungar people|Dzungar]] tribes that formed the [[Dzungar Khanate]] were the last major power to control \u00dcr\u00fcmqi before the Manchus gained control of Xinjiang, and their language gave \u00dcr\u00fcmqi its modern-day name. In the Ming dynasty, there was a record of a place at Jiujiawan {{convert|5|km|0|abbr=off}} to the west of present \u00dcr\u00fcmqi, which may have been the Dzungar town that was later destroyed during the Qing conquest. The Mongolians also used the area as herding ground in this period.<ref name=\"piper\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=drGGEsi1fFEC&pg=PA71&lpg=PA71#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Beyond the Great Wall: Urban Form and Transformation on the Chinese Frontiers |author=Piper Rae Gaubatz |publisher=Stanford University Press |date=31 March 1996 |isbn= 978-0804723992 |pages=70\u201372 }}</ref> Steppe peoples had used the location, the pass between the [[Bogda Shan]] to the east and the [[Tian Shan]] to the west, connecting the [[Dzungaria|Dzungar Basin]] to the north and the [[Turpan Depression]] to the south.\n\n\u00dcr\u00fcmqi remained a small town of lesser importance than the oasis and Silk Road trade center [[Turpan]] {{convert|200|km|abbr=on}} to the southeast. Fighting for the control of Dzungaria led to the [[Khoshut|Khoshuuts]] (now classified as Mongols) leaving \u00dcr\u00fcmqi for [[Qinghai]] and [[Tibet]] in the 1620s and 1630s.<ref>{{cite book|author=James A. Millward|title=Eurasian Crossroads: A History of Xinjiang|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8FVsWq31MtMC&pg=PA89#v=onepage&q&f=false|year=2007|publisher=Columbia University Press|isbn=978-0-231-13924-3|page=89}}</ref> The Uyghurs were introduced into the \u00dcr\u00fcmqi area in the 18th century by the Dzungars who moved them from the west [[Tarim Basin|Tarim region]] to be ''taranchis'' or farmers in \u00dcr\u00fcmqi.<ref name=\"Millward2007\">{{cite book|author=James A. Millward|title=Eurasian Crossroads: A History of Xinjiang|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8FVsWq31MtMC&pg=PA93|year=2007|publisher=Columbia University Press|isbn=978-0-231-13924-3|pages=92\u201393}}</ref>\n\n===Qing rule===\nIn the 18th century, the Qing went to war against the [[Dzungar Khanate]]. \u00dcr\u00fcmqi was taken by the Qing in 1755, and the Dzungars of the region were eliminated in the [[Dzungar genocide]]. One writer, [[Wei Yuan]], described the resulting desolation in what became northern Xinjiang as \"an empty plain for a thousand ''[[Li (unit)|li]]'', with no trace of man\". A fort was built (either in 1755 or 1758 depending on sources), and the Qing then established garrisons of Manchu and Mongol [[Eight Banners|bannermen]] and Han Chinese troops at \u00dcr\u00fcmqi.<ref>{{cite book|author=James A. Millward|title=Eurasian Crossroads: A History of Xinjiang|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8FVsWq31MtMC&pg=PA99#v=onepage&q&f=false|year=2007|publisher=Columbia University Press|isbn=978-0-231-13924-3|page=99}}</ref> After 1759, the Qing government established state farms in the under-populated areas around \u00dcr\u00fcmqi, where there was fertile, well-watered land.<ref>Millward (2007), pp. 95, 104</ref> The Manchu soldiers also constructed a temple with red walls dedicated to [[Guan Yu|Guandi]] on Pingding mountain overlooking \u00dcr\u00fcmqi, which gave \u00dcr\u00fcmqi its nickname, Red Temple.<ref name=\"piper\"/>\n\nThe Manchus began to construct a walled city in 1763 to the south of the first fort, and it was completed in 1767.<ref name=\"piper\"/> The [[Qianlong Emperor]] had named the new settlement \"Dihua\" ({{zh|c=\u8fea\u5316|p=D\u00edhu\u00e0|links=no}}; [[Manchu language|Manchu]]: ''Wen de dahabure fu''), meaning \"to enlighten (the uncivilized people)\".<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=hGlsCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA23#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=China's Forgotten People: Xinjiang, Terror and the Chinese State |first= Nick |last=Holdstock |publisher=I.B.Tauris |date=30 May 2015 |isbn=978-1784531409 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |jstor = 20062627 | doi = 10.1177/0097700405282349 |title=Reinventing China Imperial Qing Ideology and the Rise of Modern Chinese National Identity in the Early Twentieth Century|journal= Modern China |last1= Zhao |first1=Gang |volume= 32 |pages= 3\u201330 |number=1 |date= January 2006}}</ref> In 1771, another city named Gongning Cheng ({{lang|zh-hant|\u978f\u5be7\u57ce}}) was built nearby to the northwest to house Manchu bannermen, and this would become the seat of government.<ref name=\"piper\"/> The bannermen settlement to the west was commonly referred to as Mancheng ({{zh|labels=no|t=\u6eff\u57ce |l=Manchu City}}), while Dihua to the east became a Han Chinese town commonly called Hancheng (Han City).<ref name=\"jeong\">{{cite book |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UgOwDAAAQBAJ&pg=PT1857#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=The Silk Road Encyclopedia |author= Jeong Su-il |chapter=Urumqi |isbn=9781624120763 |date=2016-07-18 }}</ref> The \u00dcr\u00fcmqi of the early period was therefore a [[Twin cities|twin-city]], with Gongning Cheng the administrative center while Dihua grew into Xinjiang's commercial and financial center.<ref name=\"Millward 1998\">{{cite book|title=Beyond the Pass: Economy, Ethnicity, and Empire in Qing Xinjiang, 1758\u20131864|first=James A.|last=Millward|publisher=Stanford University Press|year=1998|pages=131\u2013134}}</ref>\n\n[[Han Chinese]] from all over China moved into Dihua, as did Chinese [[Hui people|Hui Muslims]] from [[Gansu]] and [[Shaanxi]].<ref name=\"Millward1998\">{{cite book|author=James Millward|title=Beyond the Pass: Economy, Ethnicity, and Empire in Qing Central Asia, 1759\u20131864|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=7ir2CAAAQBAJ&pg=PA133#v=onepage&q&f=false|date=1 June 1998|publisher=Stanford University Press|isbn=978-0-8047-9792-4|pages=133\u2013}}</ref> The origin of Hui in \u00dcr\u00fcmqi is often indicated by the names of their Mosques.<ref>{{cite book|title=Beyond the Pass: Economy, Ethnicity, and Empire in Qing Central Asia, 1759\u20131864|first=James A.|last=Millward|volume=|edition=illustrated|year=1998|publisher=Stanford University Press|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MC6sAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA169#v=onepage&q&f=false|page=169|isbn=978-0804729338|accessdate=24 April 2014| ref=harv }}</ref> By 1762, more than 500 shops had already been opened by Chinese migrants to the area of modern-day \u00dcr\u00fcmqi. Those Qing literati who visited Dihua were impressed by its cultural sophistication and similarity to eastern China. The writer [[Ji Xiaolan]] compared Dihua to Beijing, in that both had numerous wine shops which offered daily performances of Chinese music and dance.<ref>{{cite journal|title=Whose Xinjiang? The Transition in Chinese Intellectuals' Imagination of the \"New Dominion\" During the Qing Dynasty|series=Harvard-Yenching Institute Working Paper Series|first=Jianfei|last=Jia|year=2011 |url=https://harvard-yenching.org/features/hyi-working-paper-series-jia-jianfei }}</ref>\n\nIn 1870, the [[Battle of \u00dcr\u00fcmqi (1870)|Battle of \u00dcr\u00fcmqi]] took place between the Turkic Muslim forces of [[Yaqub Beg]] against the [[Hui people|Dungan Muslim]] forces of Tuo Ming (Daud Khalifa). With the help of Xu Xuegong's [[Han Chinese]] militia, Yaqub Beg's forces defeated the Dungans.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8FVsWq31MtMC&pg=PA119|title=Eurasian Crossroads: a history of Xinjiang|author=James A. Millward|year=2007|publisher=Columbia University Press|location=New York, NY|isbn=978-0-231-13924-3|pages=119\u2013120|accessdate=28 June 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AtduqAtBzegC&pg=PA96#v=onepage&q&f=false|title=Holy War in China: the Muslim rebellion and state in Chinese Central Asia, 1864\u20131877|author= Ho-dong Kim|year=2004|publisher=Stanford University Press|location=Stanford, Calif.|page=96|isbn=978-0-8047-4884-1|accessdate=28 June 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pEfWaxPhdnIC&pg=PA224|title=Late Ch'ing, 1800\u20131911|author1=John King Fairbank|authorlink1=John K. Fairbank|authorlink2=Kwang-Ching Liu|author2=Kwang-ching Liu |author3=Denis Crispin Twitchett |year=1980|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge, UK|isbn=978-0-521-22029-3|pages=223\u2013224|accessdate=28 June 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/modernizationofi00blac |url-access=registration |title=The Modernization of Inner Asia|author1=Cyril E. Black |author2=Louis Dupree |author3=Elizabeth Endicott-West |author4=Eden Naby |year=1991|publisher=M. E. Sharpe|location=|isbn=978-0-87332-779-4|page=[https://archive.org/details/modernizationofi00blac/page/45 45]|accessdate=28 November 2010}}</ref> Gongning Cheng was captured, its Qing administrator killed, and the city burnt to the ground and abandoned.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=drGGEsi1fFEC&pg=PA72&lpg=PA72#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Beyond the Great Wall: Urban Form and Transformation on the Chinese Frontiers |author=Piper Rae Gaubatz |publisher=Stanford University Press |date=31 March 1996 |isbn= 978-0804723992 |page=72 }}</ref> The Qing later regained control of \u00dcr\u00fcmqi. In 1884, the [[Guangxu Emperor]] established [[Xinjiang]] as a province, with Dihua as its capital.<ref>{{cite web  |url=http://www.britannica.com/EBchecked/topic/620188/Urumqi/278262/History |title=Online Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica |publisher=Britannica.com  |date=31 January 2007  |accessdate=19 February 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Republican era===\nAfter the collapse of the Qing dynasty, Xinjiang was ruled from \u00dcr\u00fcmqi by a succession of warlords: [[Yang Zengxin]] (1911\u20131928), [[Jin Shuren]] (1928\u20131933), [[Sheng Shicai]] (1933\u20131942), and [[Zhang Zhizhong]] as governor of Xinjiang in 1942\u20131949. Of these, Yang and Sheng were considered capable rulers.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XuvqBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA166 |title=Xinjiang: China's Muslim Borderland |first=  Calla |last= Wiener |editor=S. Frederick Starr |pages=166\u2013167 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=9781317451372 |date=2015-03-04 }}</ref>\n \nDuring the [[Kumul Rebellion]], the [[Battle of \u00dcr\u00fcmqi (1933)]] and the [[Battle of \u00dcr\u00fcmqi (1933\u201334)]] took place between the forces of [[Ma Zhongying]]'s [[36th Division (National Revolutionary Army)]] and [[Jin Shuren]] and [[Sheng Shicai]]'s provincial forces. At the second battle, Ma was assisted by the [[Han Chinese]] General [[Zhang Peiyuan]].\n\n===People's Republic era===\nFollowing the founding of the People's Republic of China, on 1 February 1954, the city's name was officially changed back to its Dzungar Oirat name '''\u00dcr\u00fcmqi''', meaning \"beautiful pasture\" in the [[Oirat language]] of the Dzungar people.<ref>\"The Historical and Geographical Role of Urumchi, Capital of Chinese Central Asia.\" Herold J. Wiens. ''Annals of the Association of American Geographers'', Vol. 53, No. 4 (Dec. 1963), p. 447.</ref>\n\nIn the late 1970s, [[Deng Xiaoping]] relaxed China's tight control over Xinjiang, and \u00dcr\u00fcmqi benefited from the development of the oil and gas industry in Xinjiang.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XuvqBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA4&lpg=PA4#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Xinjiang: China's Muslim Borderland |first= S. Frederick |last=Starr |page=4 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=9781317451372 |date=2015-03-04 }}</ref>\n\nNew mosques were built in \u00dcr\u00fcmqi with financial assistance from the Chinese government.<ref>{{cite book|author=Joanne N. Smith Finley|title=The Art of Symbolic Resistance: Uyghur Identities and Uyghur-Han Relations in Contemporary Xinjiang|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LQBBAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA238#v=onepage&q&f=false|date=9 September 2013|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-90-04-25678-1|pages=238\u2013}}</ref> While the Chinese government implemented strict rules on religion in southern Xinjiang, the treatment of the Uyghurs and their religion in \u00dcr\u00fcmqi were more lax and permissive.<ref>{{cite book|author=Joanne N. Smith Finley|title=The Art of Symbolic Resistance: Uyghur Identities and Uyghur-Han Relations in Contemporary Xinjiang|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LQBBAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA240#v=onepage&q&f=false|date=9 September 2013|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-90-04-25678-1|pages=240\u2013}}</ref>\n\nIn May 1989, [[1989 \u00dcr\u00fcmqi unrest|unrest in \u00dcr\u00fcmqi]] resulted in 150 injuries. In February 1997, bombings in \u00dcr\u00fcmqi following the [[Ghulja incident]] resulted in 20 deaths and scores of injuries.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XuvqBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA380 |title=Xinjiang: China's Muslim Borderland |first= Dru C. |last=Gladney |editor= S. Frederick Starr |pages=379\u2013380 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=9781317451372 |date=2015-03-04 }}</ref>\n\n====July 2009 riots and subsequent unrest====\n{{See also|July 2009 \u00dcr\u00fcmqi riots|September 2009 Xinjiang unrest}}\n\nIn the largest eruption of ethnic violence in China in decades, there were riots in July 2009 between ethnic Han Chinese and Uyghurs. The ''New York Times'' reporter covering the riot described the violence as \"clashes with riot police and Uyghurs rampaging through the city and killing Han civilians. Then, for at least three days, bands of Han vigilantes roamed Urumqi, attacking and killing Uyghurs.\"<ref name=\"nyt\">{{cite news|title=Rumbles on the Rim of China's Empire|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/07/12/weekinreview/12wong.html?pagewanted=2&_r=0|work=New York Times|date=11 July 2009}}</ref> Before the riot broke out, young Uyghurs had marched through the city \"to protest a case of judicial discrimination\".<ref name=\"nyt\"/> According to official figures, most of the 197 killed in the riot were Han, a statement which [[Edward Wong]], writing for the ''New York Times'' says is disputed by Uyghurs.<ref name=\"nyt\"/><ref name=\"deathtooll\">{{cite news|title=China's Great Game: New frontier, old foes|url=https://www.ft.com/content/60f33cf8-6dae-11e5-8171-ba1968cf791a|publisher=Financial Times|date=14 October 2015}}</ref>\n\n== Geography ==\nThe largest city in [[western China]], \u00dcr\u00fcmqi has earned a place in the ''[[Guinness Book of Records]]'' as the most remote city from any sea in the world. It is about {{convert|2500|km}} from the nearest coastline as \u00dcr\u00fcmqi is the closest major city to the Eurasian [[pole of inaccessibility]], although [[Karamay]] and [[Altay City|Altay]], both in Xinjiang, are closer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.google.com/maps/search/46.28333,+86.66667/@46.286224,86.682129,6z?source=s_q&hl=en&dg=dbrw&newdg=1|title=Google Maps}}</ref> The city has an administrative area of {{convert|10,989|km2}} and has an average elevation of {{convert|800|m}}.\n\nThe location {{coord|43|40|52|N|87|19|52|E}} in the southwestern suburbs of \u00dcr\u00fcmqi ([[\u00dcr\u00fcmqi County]]) was designated by local geography experts as the \"center point of Asia\" in 1992, and a [[Geographical Center of Asian Continent|monument to this effect]] was erected there in the 1990s. The site is a local tourist attraction.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.confluence.org/confluence.php?visitid=12710|title=DCP: Geographic Center of Asia (visit #1)}}</ref>\n\n===Water supply===\nAlthough surrounded by deserts (the [[Gurbant\u00fcngg\u00fct Desert|Gurbant\u00fcngg\u00fct]] in the north and the [[Taklamakan Desert|Taklamakan]] in the south), the \u00dcr\u00fcmqi area is naturally watered by a number of small rivers flowing from the snow-capped [[Tian Shan]] mountains: the main range of the Tian Shan in south of the city ([[\u00dcr\u00fcmqi County]]), and the [[Bogda Shan]] east of the city ([[Dabancheng District]]). A network consisting of thousands of miles of canals, reservoirs, and tunnels called ''karez,'' redistribute the water throughout the extensively irrigated area along the foothills of the mountain range. It compromises an ancient irrigation system built 2,000 years ago.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.npr.org/sections/parallels/2017/10/21/554271726/impossible-to-save-scientists-are-watching-chinas-glaciers-disappear|title='Impossible To Save': Scientists Are Watching China's Glaciers Disappear|work=NPR.org|access-date=2017-10-21|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThere are 20,000 glaciers in Xinjiang \u2013 nearly half of all the glaciers in China. Since the 1950s, Xinjiang's glaciers have retreated by between 21 percent to 27 percent due to [[global warming]]. [[Tianshan Glacier No. 1]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u4e00\u53f7\u51b0\u5ddd}}), origin of \u00dcr\u00fcmqi River, is the largest glacier near a major city in China, but has already split into two smaller glaciers.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nAs the \u00dcr\u00fcmqi region's population and economy are growing, the water demand exceeds the natural supply. To alleviate water shortages, the [[Irtysh\u2013Karamay\u2013\u00dcr\u00fcmqi Canal|Irtysh\u2013\u00dcr\u00fcmqi Canal]] was constructed in the first decade of the 21st century. The canal's main trunk terminates in the so-called  \"Reservoir 500\" (\"500\"\u6c34\u5e93; {{coord|44|12|00|N|87|49|00|E|display=inline|region:CN-65_type:landmark}}) in the far north-eastern suburbs of the city (on the border of \u00dcr\u00fcmqi's suburban [[Midong District]] and [[Fukang]] City). A new industrial area, called Ganquanbao Industrial Park ({{lang|zh-hans|\u7518\u6cc9\u5821\u5de5\u4e1a\u56ed}}), or Industrial New City 500 ({{lang|zh-hans|500\u5de5\u4e1a\u65b0\u57ce}}) was being developed in 2009, west of the reservoir, relying on it for water supply.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.xjass.com/jj/content/2009-01/13/content_53392_11.htm |script-title=zh:\u89e3\u51b3\u7c73\u4e1c\u65b0\u533a\u5efa\u8bbe\u9879\u76ee\u4f9b\u6c34\u7d27\u7f3a\u95ee\u9898\u7684\u65b9\u5411 |trans-title=Approaches to solving water supply problems for the development projects in the Midong New Area |language=zh-hans |access-date=13 January 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131022010738/http://www.xjass.com/jj/content/2009-01/13/content_53392_11.htm |archive-date=22 October 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.wxsq.gov.cn/structure/zjxq/tzhjnr_1360_1.htm |script-title=zh:\u9ad8\u65b0\u533a\uff08\u65b0\u5e02\u533a\uff09\u7518\u6cc9\u5821\u5de5\u4e1a\u56ed\u57fa\u672c\u6982\u51b5--\u4e4c\u9c81\u6728\u9f50\u9ad8\u65b0\u6280\u672f\u4ea7\u4e1a\u5f00\u53d1\u533a(\u65b0\u5e02\u533a)] |trans-title=High-tech zone Ganquanbao Industrial Park Facts \u2013 Urumqi High-tech Industrial Development Zone (new city) |language=zh-hans |access-date=21 May 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131021233710/http://www.wxsq.gov.cn/structure/zjxq/tzhjnr_1360_1.htm |archive-date=21 October 2013 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> From the reservoir area water is further distributed over a network of canals throughout the lower Midong District.\n\n=== Climate ===\nIn \u00dcr\u00fcmqi, a [[continent]]al [[cold semi-arid climate]] ([[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]] ''[[Semi-arid climate#Cold Semi-arid climates|BSk]]'') prevails, with very large differences between summer and winter. It has warm summers, with a July daily average of {{convert|23.7|\u00b0C|1}}, and very cold winters, with a January daily average of {{convert|\u221212.6|\u00b0C|1}}. The annual average temperature is {{convert|6.90|\u00b0C|1}}. The city is semi-arid, with its summers slightly wetter than its winters, yet sunny weather is much more likely in the warmer months, and relative humidity is the lowest during summer. With monthly percent possible sunshine ranging from 30&nbsp;percent in December to 70&nbsp;percent in August and September, the city receives 2,523 hours of bright sunshine annually. Its annual precipitation is about {{convert|290|mm|in|1}}. Extremes since 1951 have ranged from {{convert|\u221241.5|\u00b0C|0}} on 27 February 1951 to {{convert|42.1|\u00b0C|0}} on 1 August 1973.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://cdc.cma.gov.cn/dataSetLogger.do?changeFlag=dataLogger |title=Archived copy |access-date=15 January 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140710164442/http://cdc.cma.gov.cn/dataSetLogger.do?changeFlag=dataLogger |archive-date=10 July 2014 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.mherrera.org/temp.htm\n| title = Extreme Temperatures Around the World\n| accessdate = 1 December 2010\n}}</ref>\n\n<!-- can't fit perfectly for now...\n{{climate chart\n| \u00dcr\u00fcmqi\n| \u221216.6 | \u22127.4 | 10\n| \u221213.7 | \u22124.7 | 10\n| \u2212 5.4 |  2.7 | 19\n|   4.8 | 16.1 | 32\n|  11.2 | 23.1 | 39\n|  16.1 | 27.6 | 36\n|  18.2 | 30.1 | 30\n|  16.7 | 29.0 | 23\n|  11.2 | 23.1 | 26\n|   3.1 | 13.2 | 26\n| \u2013 5.9 |  2.0 | 19\n| \u221212.9 | 