ipitation days = 9.2\n|Feb precipitation days = 7.2\n|Mar precipitation days = 7.2\n|Apr precipitation days = 6.8\n|May precipitation days = 6.8\n|Jun precipitation days = 8.0\n|Jul precipitation days = 8.4\n|Aug precipitation days = 6.3\n|Sep precipitation days = 5.0\n|Oct precipitation days = 5.5\n|Nov precipitation days = 6.9\n|Dec precipitation days = 9.6\n\n|Jan sun = 101.6 |Jan percentsun = 35\n|Feb sun = 128.8 |Feb percentsun = 44\n|Mar sun = 180.5 |Mar percentsun = 49\n|Apr sun = 248.0 |Apr percentsun = 62\n|May sun = 283.3 |May percentsun = 63\n|Jun sun = 282.7 |Jun percentsun = 61\n|Jul sun = 298.7 |Jul percentsun = 64\n|Aug sun = 301.0 |Aug percentsun = 70\n|Sep sun = 262.6 |Sep percentsun = 70\n|Oct sun = 224.4 |Oct percentsun = 66\n|Nov sun = 127.4 |Nov percentsun = 44\n|Dec sun =  84.3 |Dec percentsun = 30\n                 |year percentsun= 57<!--automatically calculated value of 54.8 yields a maximum of 12.61 hr/day, which is physically impossible-->\n|source 1 = [http://cdc.cma.gov.cn/dataSetLogger.do?changeFlag=dataLogger China Meteorological Administration]\n|date=August 2010\n}}\n\n===Air quality and pollution===\n{{update|section|date=November 2015}}\nAccording to the National Environmental Analysis released by [[Tsinghua University]] and the [[Asian Development Bank]] in January 2013, \u00dcr\u00fcmqi is among the top ten cities in the world with the most air pollution. According to this report, seven of these cities are in China, including [[Taiyuan]], [[Beijing]], [[Lanzhou]], [[Chongqing]], [[Jinan]], and [[Shijiazhuang]] (besides \u00dcr\u00fcmqi).<ref>{{cite news|title=WEATHER & EXTREME EVENTS 7 of 10 Most Air-Polluted Cities Are in China|url=http://news.discovery.com/earth/weather-extreme-events/7-of-10-most-air-polluted-cities-china-130116.htm|accessdate=1 September 2014|work=JAN 16, 2013|agency=http://news.discovery.com|publisher=Imaginechina/Corbis}}</ref>\n\n[[Blacksmith Institute]] mentioned \u00dcr\u00fcmqi in ''2007 World's Worst Polluted Places'' caused by air pollution along with [[Linfen]] and [[Lanzhou]], all in China.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.blacksmithinstitute.org/wwpp2007/finalReport2007.pdf|title=THE WORLD'S WORST POLLUTED PLACESThe Top Ten(of The Dirty Thirty)|date=|website=|access-date=18 February 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071011181528/http://www.blacksmithinstitute.org/wwpp2007/finalReport2007.pdf|archive-date=11 October 2007|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref> In 2008, ''[[Toronto Star]]''  listed \u00dcr\u00fcmqi as one of the Top Ten worst places to live in the world due to sulphurous pollution.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.thestar.com/article/559958 |title=Winter in Urumqi, one of the world's most polluted cities Alison Bate |date= 31 December 2008|work= The Star|accessdate=18 February 2012 |location=Toronto}}</ref> Heavy haze is extremely common in winter, which frequently affects air traffic. Officials believed that severe winter air pollution in \u00dcr\u00fcmqi is mainly caused by energy-heavy industries and the outdated coal-firing winter heating system.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://english.peopledaily.com.cn/90882/7730374.html|title=Urumqi to invest heavily to cut air pollution \u2013 People's Daily Online|date= |website= |accessdate=18 February 2012}}</ref> According to a report by Department of Environmental Science and Engineering of [[Fudan University]], the average PM<sub>2.5</sub> and TSP concentrations in the winter of 2007 were 12 times higher than USA standard for PM<sub>2.5</sub> and 3 times the National Ambient Air Quality Standard of China for TSP.<ref name=fudan>{{cite journal|last=Li|first=Juan Li|authorlink=|author2=Guoshun Zhuanga|author3=Kan Huanga|author4=Yanfen Lina|author5=Chang Xua|author6=Shulong Yub|title=Characteristics and sources of air-borne particulate in Urumqi, China, the upstream area of Asia dust|journal=Atmospheric Environment|volume=42|issue=4|pages=776\u2013787|year=2008|url=http://environment.fudan.edu.cn/CACS/papers/characteristics%20and%20sources%20of%20air-borne%20particulate%20in%20urumqi,%20china,%20the%20upstream%20area%20of%20asia%20dust.pdf|doi=10.1016/j.atmosenv.2007.09.062|id=| accessdate= 18 February 2012|pmid=|bibcode=2008AtmEn..42..776L}}</ref> The [[sulfur dioxide]] from industrial emissions mixed with the local anthropogenic aerosol with the transported soil dust from outside the city were the main sources of the high concentration of sulfate, one of the main factors causing the heavy air pollution over \u00dcr\u00fcmqi.<ref name=fudan/>\n\n===Timing of sunrise===\nBecause of the use of a [[Time in China|single time zone]] for all of China, in \u00dcr\u00fcmqi which is at a far western location in China, the sun is 2 hours and 10 minutes behind [[China Standard Time]] (CST = [[UTC]]+8). During early January the sun does not rise until 09:45 and it sets between 18:45 and 19:10 local time. In September and March the sun rises around 08:00, and sets around 19:45. However, in June the sun rises at about 06:25 and does not set until 21:45.\n\n== Administrative divisions ==\n[[File:Txu-oclc-6654394-nk-45-3rd-ed.jpg|left|thumb|Map including \u00dcr\u00fcmqi (labeled as WU-LU-MU-CH'I) and nearby areas from the [[International Map of the World]] (1975)]]\n\u00dcr\u00fcmqi currently comprises 8 [[Administrative divisions of the People's Republic of China#County level|county-level]] subdivisions: 7 [[District (PRC)|districts]] and 1 [[County (People's Republic of China)|county]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:90%; margin:auto;\"\n!colspan=\"8\"| Map\n|-\n|colspan=\"8\"| <div style=\"position: relative\" class=\"center\">\n{{Image label begin|image=Administrative division Urumqi.png|width=450|link=}} \n{{Image label|x=900|y=1840|scale=450/2320|text=[[Tianshan District|'''1''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=620|y=1860|scale=450/2320|text=[[Saybag District|'''Saybag''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=790|y=1530|scale=450/2320|text=[[Xinshi District, \u00dcr\u00fcmqi|'''2''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=900|y=1710|scale=450/2320|text=[[Shuimogou District|'''Shuimogou''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=630|y=1550|scale=450/2320|text=[[Toutunhe District|'''3''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=1560|y=2110|scale=450/2320|text=[[Dabancheng District|'''Dabancheng<br/>\u203b''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=1010|y=1500|scale=450/2320|text=[[Midong District|'''Midong''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=550|y=2290|scale=450/2320|text=[[\u00dcr\u00fcmqi County|'''\u00dcr\u00fcmqi<br/>County''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=240|y=650|scale=450/2320|text=[[Tianshan District|'''1. Tianshan''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=240|y=750|scale=450/2320|text=[[Xinshi District, \u00dcr\u00fcmqi|'''2. Xinshi''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=240|y=850|scale=450/2320|text=[[Toutunhe District|'''3. Toutunhe''']]}}\n{{Image label|x=630|y=2880|scale=450/2320|text=[[Dabancheng District|'''\u203b''']]}}\n</div>\n|-\n! Name\n! Simplified Chinese\n! Hanyu Pinyin\n! [[Uyghur language|Uyghur]] ([[Uyghur Arabic script|UEY]])\n! Uyghur Latin ([[Uyghur Latin script|ULY]])\n! Population ([[Sixth National Population Census of the People's Republic of China|2010]])<ref>{{cite web|title=CHINA: \u00dcr\u00fcmqi / \u4e4c\u9c81\u6728\u9f50\u5e02 |url=http://www.citypopulation.de/php/china-township-urumqi.php|work=City Population}}</ref>\n! Area (km<sup>2</sup>)\n! Density (/km<sup>2</sup>)\n|-\n|colspan=\"9\" align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#D3D3D3\"|'''City proper'''\n|-\n| [[Tianshan District]]\n| {{lang|zh-hans|\u5929\u5c71\u533a}}\n| {{transl|zh|Ti\u0101nsh\u0101n Q\u016b}}\n| {{script/Arabic|\u062a\u06d5\u06ad\u0631\u0649\u062a\u0627\u063a \u0631\u0627\u064a\u0648\u0646\u0649}}\n| {{transl|ug|Tengritagh Rayoni}}\n| 696,277\n| 171\n| 4071.79\n|-\n| [[Saybag District]]\n| {{lang|zh-hans|\u6c99\u4f9d\u5df4\u514b\u533a}}\n| {{transl|zh|Sh\u0101y\u012bb\u0101k\u00e8 Q\u016b}}\n| {{script/Arabic|\u0633\u0627\u064a\u0628\u0627\u063a \u0631\u0627\u064a\u0648\u0646\u0649}}\n| {{transl|ug|Saybagh Rayoni}}\n| 664,716\n| 422\n| 1575.15\n|-\n| [[Xinshi District, \u00dcr\u00fcmqi|Xinshi District]]\n| {{lang|zh-hans|\u65b0\u5e02\u533a}}\n| {{transl|zh|X\u012bnsh\u00ec Q\u016b}}\n| {{script/Arabic|\u064a\u06d0\u06ad\u0649\u0634\u06d5\u06be\u06d5\u0631 \u0631\u0627\u064a\u0648\u0646\u0649}}\n| {{transl|ug|Y\u00ebngisheher Rayoni}}\n| 730,307\n| 143\n| 5107.04\n|-\n| [[Shuimogou District]]\n| {{lang|zh-hans|\u6c34\u78e8\u6c9f\u533a}}\n| {{transl|zh|Shu\u01d0m\u00f2g\u014du Q\u016b}}\n| {{script/Arabic|\u0634\u06c7\u064a\u0645\u0648\u06af\u06c7 \u0631\u0627\u064a\u0648\u0646\u0649}}\n| {{transl|ug|Shuymogu Rayoni}}\n| 390,943\n| 92\n| 4249.38\n|-\n|colspan=\"9\" align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#D3D3D3\"|'''Suburban'''\n|-\n| [[Toutunhe District]]\n| {{lang|zh-hans|\u5934\u5c6f\u6cb3\u533a}}\n| {{transl|zh|T\u00f3ut\u00fanh\u00e9 Q\u016b}}\n| {{script/Arabic|\u062a\u06c7\u062f\u06c7\u06ad\u062e\u0627\u0628\u0627 \u0631\u0627\u064a\u0648\u0646\u0649}}\n| {{transl|ug|Tudungxaba Rayoni}}\n| 172,796\n| 276\n| 626.07\n|-\n| [[Dabancheng District]]\n| {{lang|zh-hans|\u8fbe\u5742\u57ce\u533a}}\n| {{transl|zh|D\u00e1b\u01cench\u00e9ng Q\u016b}}\n| {{script/Arabic|\u062f\u0627\u06cb\u0627\u0646\u0686\u0649\u06ad \u0631\u0627\u064a\u0648\u0646\u0649}}\n| {{transl|ug|Dawanching Rayoni}}\n| 40,657\n| 5,188\n| 7.83\n|-\n| [[Midong District]]\n| {{lang|zh-hans|\u7c73\u4e1c\u533a}}\n| {{transl|zh|M\u01d0d\u014dng Q\u016b}}\n| {{script/Arabic|\u0645\u0649\u062f\u0648\u06ad \u0631\u0627\u064a\u0648\u0646\u0649}}\n| {{transl|ug|Midong Rayoni}}\n| 333,676\n| 3,594\n| 92.84\n|-\n|colspan=\"9\" align=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#D3D3D3\"|'''Rural'''\n|-\n| [[\u00dcr\u00fcmqi County]]\n| {{lang|zh-hans|\u4e4c\u9c81\u6728\u9f50\u53bf}}\n| {{transl|zh|W\u016bl\u01d4m\u00f9q\u00ed Xi\u00e0n}}\n| {{script/Arabic|\u0626\u06c8\u0631\u06c8\u0645\u0686\u0649 \u0646\u0627\u06be\u0649\u064a\u0649\u0633\u0649}}\n| {{transl|ug|\u00dcr\u00fcmchi Nahiyisi}}\n| 83,187\n| 4,332\n| 19.20\n|}\n\n== Demographics ==\n[[File:\u5927\u5df4\u624e China Xinjiang Urumqi Welcome you to tour the, \u041a\u0438\u0442\u0430\u0439 \u0421\u0438\u043d\u044c\u0446\u0437 - panoramio - jun jin luo (1).jpg|thumb|Mosque in \u00dcr\u00fcmqi]]\n\u00dcr\u00fcmqi has been a multi-ethnic city from the time of the Qing conquest; in the early years, the Manchus lived in Gongning Cheng, Han Chinese in Dihua and various other ethnic groups such as the Hui, Uyghurs and others in the suburban districts.<ref name=\"piper2\">{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=drGGEsi1fFEC&pg=PA73&lpg=PA73#v=onepage&q&f=false |title=Beyond the Great Wall: Urban Form and Transformation on the Chinese Frontiers |author=Piper Rae Gaubatz |publisher=Stanford University Press |date=31 March 1996 |isbn= 978-0804723992 |pages=73\u201375 }}</ref> The Muslims settled to the south of the walled-city of Dihua, and although the walls have since been demolished, the Muslims are still concentrated there.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XuvqBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA244 |title=Xinjiang: China's Muslim Borderland |first= Stanley W. |last= Toops |editor=S. Frederick Starr |page=244 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=9781317451372 |date=2015-03-04 }}</ref> A census in 1787 showed that there were 114,348 Hui and Han in the prefectures of Zhenxi (which included Bark\u00f6l and Hami) and \u00dcr\u00fcmqi.<ref>{{cite book|author=James A. Millward|title=Eurasian Crossroads: A History of Xinjiang|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8FVsWq31MtMC&pg=PA306#v=onepage&q&f=false|year=2007|publisher=Columbia University Press|isbn=978-0-231-13924-3|pages=306\u2013307}}</ref> In \u00dcr\u00fcmqi city itself, there were 39,000 people in the 1880s and by the early 20th century, 50,000 people.<ref name=\"piper2\"/> \u00dcr\u00fcmqi in 1908 was said to have been inhabited by Uyghurs (then called Turkis), Chinese, Manchus and a few Mongols, with the Uyghurs estimated to comprise a quarter of the population.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/?id=puZHAQAAMAAJ&dq=urumtsi+sungaria&q=wulumuhts%27i |title=L. Richard's Comprehensive Geography of the Chinese Empire and Dependencies |authors=Louis Richard, M. Kennelly |date=1908 |page=532 }}</ref>\n\nIn the People's Republic era, an active program to resettle Han population in Xinjiang was initiated.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=XuvqBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA169 |title=Xinjiang: China's Muslim Borderland |first=  Calla |last= Wiener |editor=S. Frederick Starr |pages=168\u2013169 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=9781317451372 |date=2015-03-04 }}</ref> In 1960, there were 76,496 Uyghurs and 477,321 Han Chinese in \u00dcr\u00fcmqi.<ref name=\"Millward2007 2\">{{cite book|author=James A. Millward|title=Eurasian Crossroads: A History of Xinjiang|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=8FVsWq31MtMC&pg=PA260#v=onepage&q&f=false|year=2007|publisher=Columbia University Press|isbn=978-0-231-13924-3|page=260}}</ref>\n\nAccording to the 2000 census, \u00dcr\u00fcmqi had 2,081,834 inhabitants, with a population density of 174.53 inhabitants/km<sup>2</sup> (452.3 inhabitants/sq. mi.).<ref name=\"2000 census\">{{cite book |script-title=zh:2000\u5e74\u4eba\u53e3\u666e\u67e5\u4e2d\u56fd\u6c11\u65cf\u4eba\u53e3\u8d44\u6599 |publisher={{lang|zh|\u6c11\u65cf\u51fa\u7248\u793e}} |year=2003 |isbn=978-7-105-05425-1}}</ref>\n\nIn the 2010 census, the population was recorded as 3,112,559. Part of the increase was due to boundary changes, for example, Miquan was merged into [[Midong District]] and became part of \u00dcr\u00fcmqi in 2007.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.citypopulation.de/php/china-xinjiang-admin.php?adm1id=6501 |title=W\u016aL\u016cM\u00d9Q\u00cd SH\u00cc (Prefecture-level City) |work=City Population }}</ref>\n\n;Population by ethnicity\n{| class = \"wikitable\"\n|- style=\"background:#eee;\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" | [[List of ethnic groups in China|Ethnicity]]\n! colspan=\"2\" | 2000<ref name=\"2000 census\"/>\n! colspan=\"2\" | 2010<ref>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OkAVAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA65|pages=65\u201366 |title=Eurasian Corridors of Interconnection: From the South China to the Caspian Sea|editors= Susan M. Walcott, Corey Johnson|date=August 2012 |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-1135078751|author=Stanley W. Toops}}</ref><ref>{{cite book |author=Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region People's Government Census Leaders' Office |script-title=zh:\u300a\u65b0\u7586\u7ef4\u543e\u5c14\u81ea\u6cbb\u533a2010\u5e74\u4eba\u53e3\u666e\u67e5\u8d44\u6599\u300b|date=August 2012 |publisher=China Statistics Print |language=zh-hans |isbn=978-7-5037-6516-2}}</ref>\n|- style=\"background:#eee;\"\n! Population\n! style=\"width:4em;\"|%\n! Population\n! style=\"width:4em;\"|%\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Han Chinese]]\n| 1,567,562\n| 75.30\n| 2,331,654\n| 74.91\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Uyghurs|Uyghur]]\n| 266,342\n| 12.79\n| 387,878\n| 12.46\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Hui people|Hui]]\n| 167,148\n| 8.03\n| 280,186\n| 9.00\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Kazakhs]]\n| 48,772\n| 2.34\n| 68,076\n| 2.19\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Manchu people|Manchu]]\n| 7,682\n| 0.37\n| 8,541\n| 0.27\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Mongols|Mongol]]\n| 7,252\n| 0.35\n| 10,454\n| 0.34\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Xibe people|Xibe]]\n| 3,674\n| 0.18\n| 4,820\n| 0.15\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Russians|Russian]]\n| 2,603\n| 0.13\n| 3,010\n| 0.10\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Monguor people|Tu]]\n| 1,613\n| 0.08\n| 2,869\t\n| 0.09\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Kyrgyz people|Kyrgyz]]\n| 1,436\n| 0.07\n| 2,207\n| 0.07\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Uzbeks|Uzbek]]\n| 1,406\n| 0.07\n| 1,581\n| 0.05\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Zhuang people|Zhuang]]\n| 878\n| 0.04\n|\n|\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Tatars|Tatar]]\n| 767\n| 0.04\n|\n|\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Tibetan people|Tibetan]]\n| 665\n| 0.03\n|\n|\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Dongxiangs|Dongxiang]]\n| 621\n| 0.03\n| 2,333\n| 0.07\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Miao people|Miao]]\n| 620\n| 0.03\n|\n|\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |[[Koreans|Korean]]\n| 588\n| 0.03\n|\n|\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" |Other\n| 2,205\n| 0.09\n| 8,950\n| 0.29\n|- style=\"background:#EEF\"\n|Total \n|2,081,834\n|\n|3,112,559\n|\n|}\n\n== Economy ==\n[[File:Outer Ring Road of Urumqi.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Outer Ring Road viaducts in \u00dcr\u00fcmqi at night]]\n\u00dcr\u00fcmqi is a major industrial center within Xinjiang. \u00dcr\u00fcmqi, together with [[Karamay]] and [[Korla]], account for 64.5&nbsp;percent of the total industrial output of Xinjiang. \u00dcr\u00fcmqi is also the largest consumer center in the region, recording [[Renminbi|\u00a5]]41.9 billion retail sales of consumer goods in 2008, an increase of 26&nbsp;percent from 2007. The [[Gross domestic product|GDP]] per capita reached US$6,222 in 2008.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tdctrade.com/mktprof/china/xinjiang.htm |title=hktdc.com \u2013 Profiles of China Provinces, Cities and Industrial Parks |publisher=Tdctrade.com |date= |accessdate=19 February 2010}}</ref> According to statistics, \u00dcr\u00fcmqi ranked 7th in 2008 by the disposable income for urban residents among cities in [[Western China]].<ref>{{cite web |script-title=zh:\u4e4c\u9c81\u6728\u9f50\u4eba\u5747\u53ef\u652f\u914d\u6536\u5165\u589e\u957f\u5c45\u897f\u90e8\u5341\u7701\u7b2c8\u4f4d|date= |url=http://www.nxein.com/zhjj/mzqyjj/200711/5573.html |accessdate= }}</ref> \u00dcr\u00fcmqi has been a central developmental target for the [[China Western Development]] project that the Central Government is pursuing.\n\nThe [[\u00dcr\u00fcmqi Foreign Economic Relations and Trade Fair]] ({{zh|c=\u4e4c\u6d3d\u4f1a}}) has been held annually since 1991 and has been upgraded into the first [[China-Eurasia Expo]] in 2011. Its purpose is to promote domestic and foreign markets. The 17th Fair has attracted participants from the [[Ministry of Commerce of the People's Republic of China|Ministry of Commerce]] and the [[China Council for the Promotion of International Trade|China Council for Promotion of International Trade]].<ref>{{cite web |title=17th Urumqi Trade Fair opens&nbsp;\u2013 CCTV International |publisher= CCTV.com |date= |url=http://www.cctv.com/program/bizchina/20080902/102963.shtml |accessdate= }}</ref>\n[[File:Urumqi partial panorama at dusk.JPG|thumb|left|250px|Buildings in \u00dcr\u00fcmqi CBDs near [[People's Square (\u00dcr\u00fcmqi)|People's Square]] ]]\nXinjiang Guanghui Group ({{lang|zh-hans|\u65b0\u7586\u5e7f\u6c47\u96c6\u56e2}}) is the largest [[real estate]] enterprise and most powerful [[privately held company|privately owned company]] in Xinjiang and is currently engaged in energy and automobiles. [[Zhong Tian Plaza|China CITIC Bank Mansion]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u4e2d\u4fe1\u94f6\u884c\u5927\u53a6}}), headquarters of Guanghui, located in one of the CBDs in North Xinhua Road, is the tallest building in \u00dcr\u00fcmqi and [[Xinjiang]]; with a height of {{convert|229|m|abbr=off}}, it is also the tallest in [[Northwestern China]] and [[Central Asia]]. Zhongshan Road (Sun Yat-sen Road, Chinese: {{lang|zh|\u4e2d\u5c71\u8def}}) has been one of the ten most famous commercial streets in China since 2005. Zhongshan Road has always been the hub of [[consumer electronics]] in the city, with the largest computer, [[mobile phone]] and [[consumer electronics]] market in Xinjiang, including Baihuacun, Cyber Digital Plaza and Fountain Plaza.\n\nAs the economic center in Xinjiang, \u00dcr\u00fcmqi has expanded its urban area since the 1990s. The [[Central Business District|CBDs]] in the city increased rapidly all around the major districts. Despite the old city areas being primarily in the south, the development in the north part began since the late 1980s. The completion of the new office tower for \u00dcr\u00fcmqi Municipal Government in 2003 at [[Nanhu Square]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u5357\u6e56\u5e7f\u573a}}) in Nanhu Road marked a shift of the city center to the north. Lacking a subway, the city commenced the construction of [[viaduct]]s for Outer Ring Road ({{lang|zh-hans|\u5916\u73af\u8def}}) since 2003, which considerably facilitates transport. Youhao Road ({{lang|zh-hans|\u53cb\u597d\u8def}}) and surrounding neighborhood, is the commercial center for business, shopping and amusement. Youhao Group ({{lang|zh-hans|\u53cb\u597d\u96c6\u56e2}}), the namesake local enterprise, owns a major market share of retails. Maison Mode Urumqi ({{lang|zh-hans|\u4e4c\u9c81\u6728\u9f50\u7f8e\u7f8e\u767e\u8d27}}), open since 2008, became one of the few notable department stores for [[luxury good|luxury merchandise]] in the city.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.maisonmode.com/mm_wlmq.html|script-title=zh:MAISON MODE \u00b7 \u7f8e\u7f8e}}</ref> The \u00dcr\u00fcmqi Economic and Technological Development Zone (UETD) located in the northern [[Toutunhe District]], has been a leading base for steel, machinery manufacturing, biochemistry and other industrial innovations.\n{{Clear}}\n\n== Tourism ==\n[[File:People's Square of Urumqi 1.jpg|thumb|[[People's Square (\u00dcr\u00fcmqi)|People's Square]]]]\n[[File:Urumqi s bazzar.jpg|thumb|[[Grand Bazaar (\u00dcr\u00fcmqi)|International Grand Bazaar Xinjiang]]]]\n* [[Grand Bazaar (\u00dcr\u00fcmqi)|Grand Bazaar]], a [[bazaar]] on South Jiefang Road ({{lang|zh|\u89e3\u653e\u5357\u8def}}).\n* [[Hong Shan]] (Red Mountain) is the symbol of \u00dcr\u00fcmqi, located in Hongshan Park.\n* [[People's Park (\u00dcr\u00fcmqi)|People's Park]], south of Hongshan Park.\n* [[People's Square (\u00dcr\u00fcmqi)|People's Square]]\n* Nanhu Square ({{lang|zh-hans|\u5357\u6e56\u5e7f\u573a}})\n* Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous Region Museum ({{lang|zh-hans|\u65b0\u7586\u7ef4\u543e\u5c14\u81ea\u6cbb\u533a\u535a\u7269\u9986}}), which was completely rebuilt in the early 2000s.<ref>[http://www.chinaheritagequarterly.org/features.php?searchterm=003_twomuseums.inc&issue=003 A TALE OF TWO CITIES: NEW MUSEUMS FOR YINING AND URUMQI]. ''CHINA HERITAGE NEWSLETTER'', No. 3, September 2005</ref>\n* [[Heaven Lake of Tian Shan|Heavenly Lake Scenic Area]], a popular park with some of China's most famous alpine scenery, over two hours outside \u00dcr\u00fcmqi.\n* Shuimogou Hot Springs ({{lang|zh-hans|\u6c34\u78e8\u6c9f\u6e29\u6cc9}}) is located {{convert|5|km|abbr=on}} northeast of \u00dcr\u00fcmqi.\n* Xinjiang Silk Road Museum ({{lang|zh-hans|\u65b0\u7586\u4e1d\u7ef8\u4e4b\u8def\u535a\u7269\u9986}}) is located next to the Grand Bazaar at No. 160 Shengli Road. It is located on the fourth and fifth floors of a large European-style building which houses a shopping complex as well. Most of the exhibits have English names as well and some of the guides speak some English.\n* \u00dcr\u00fcmqi City Museum ({{lang|zh-hans|\u4e4c\u9c81\u6728\u9f50\u535a\u7269\u9986}}) is located at South Nanhu Road 123 ({{lang|zh-hans|\u5357\u6e56\u5357\u8def123\u53f7}}).\n* \u00dcr\u00fcmqi Tatar [[Mosque]] ({{lang|zh-hans|\u4e4c\u9c81\u6728\u9f50\u5854\u5854\u5c14\u5bfa\u6e05\u771f\u5bfa}}) is a luxuriously furnished mosque located on Jiefang Road. Permission must have been obtained prior to visiting the mosque.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.muslim2china.com/china-mosques/Urumqi-Tartar-Mosque-43.html#?|title=Urumqi Tartar Mosque - Mosques in China - muslim2china.com}}</ref>\n* The monument at the [[Geographical Center of Asian Continent]], in Yongfeng Township, [[\u00dcr\u00fcmqi County]]\n*Xinjiang International Grand Bazaar in \u00dcr\u00fcmqi City Tianshan District, which is currently the country's largest bazaar. The architectural style of the Grand Bazaar has an Islamic style. Inside, dazzling, exquisite commodities of ethnic minorities are sold.\n* \u00dcr\u00fcmqi Silk Road Ski Resort ({{lang|zh-hans|\u4e1d\u7ef8\u4e4b\u8def\u6ed1\u96ea\u573a}}) is located in \u00dcr\u00fcmqi County.\n*...\n\n== Education and science ==\n[[File:Xife.jpg|thumb|Xinjiang University of Finance and Economics.]]\n[[File:Front-Gate of Urumqi No.1 High School.JPG|thumb|\u00dcr\u00fcmqi No.1 High School.]]\n\u00dcr\u00fcmqi has many educational campuses including [[Xinjiang University]], [[Xinjiang Normal University]], [[Xinjiang Agricultural University]], [[Xinjiang Medical University]] and many others.\n\n=== Universities ===\n* [[Xinjiang University]] (\u65b0\u7586\u5927\u5b66)\n* [[Xinjiang Normal University]] (\u65b0\u7586\u5e08\u8303\u5927\u5b66)<ref>[http://www.xjnu.edu.cn/ Xinjiang Normal University official website]</ref>\n* [[Xinjiang Agricultural University]] (\u65b0\u7586\u519c\u4e1a\u5927\u5b66)\n* [[Xinjiang Arts Institute]] (\u65b0\u7586\u827a\u672f\u5b66\u9662)\n* [[Xinjiang University of Finance and Economics]] (\u65b0\u7586\u8d22\u7ecf\u5927\u5b66)\n* [[\u00dcr\u00fcmqi Vocational University]] (\u4e4c\u9c81\u6728\u9f50\u804c\u4e1a\u5927\u5b66)\n* [[Xinjiang Vocational and Technical Institute]] (\u65b0\u7586\u4ea4\u901a\u804c\u4e1a\u6280\u672f\u5b66\u9662)\n* [[Xinjiang Medical University]] (\u65b0\u7586\u533b\u79d1\u5927\u5b66)\n\n=== High schools ===\n* [[No.1 Senior High School of \u00dcr\u00fcmqi|\u00dcr\u00fcmqi No.1 High School]]\n* [[Bingtuan No.2 Middle School]]\n* [[Bayi Senior High School of \u00dcr\u00fcmqi]]\n* [[No.70 Senior High School of \u00dcr\u00fcmqi]]\n* [[No.8 Senior High School of \u00dcr\u00fcmqi]]\n* [[No.6 Senior High School of \u00dcr\u00fcmqi]]\n\n===Research institutes===\n* [[Xinjiang Astronomical Observatory]]\n* [[The Xingjiang Technical Institute of Physics & Chemistry.CAS]]\n* [[Xingjiang Institute of Ecology and Geography]]\n\n== Transportation ==\n[[File:China Xinjiang Airlines Boeing 757-200 Newton-1.jpg|thumb|right|\u00dcr\u00fcmqi Diwopu International Airport.]]\n[[File:Urumqi South Railway Station, 2006-04-25.jpg|thumb|right|\u00dcr\u00fcmqi South Railway Station.]]\n\n=== Air ===\n\u00dcr\u00fcmqi is served by the [[\u00dcr\u00fcmqi Diwopu International Airport]]. It is a hub for China Southern Airlines. \u00dcr\u00fcmqi Diwopu International Airport is the largest airport in Xinjiang, and the only airport in China to serve flights from [[Afghanistan]], [[Kyrgyzstan]] and [[Tajikistan]].\n\n=== Rail ===\n\u00dcr\u00fcmqi is Xinjiang's main rail hub with two primary railway stations, the older [[\u00dcr\u00fcmqi South Railway Station]] (formerly the Urumqi Railway Station) and [[\u00dcr\u00fcmqi Railway Station]] opened in July 2016. The [[Lanxin High-Speed Railway|Lanzhou-Xinjiang High Speed Railway]] stops at both stations, running from \u00dcr\u00fcmqi to [[Lanzhou]] which has been in operation since the end of 2014.\n\nThe city is served by several conventional rail lines. \u00dcr\u00fcmqi is the western terminus of the [[Lanzhou\u2013Xinjiang railway|Lanzhou\u2013Xinjiang (Lanxin)]] and [[\u00dcr\u00fcmqi\u2013Dzungaria railway|\u00dcr\u00fcmqi\u2013Dzungaria (Wuzhun)]] Railway, and the eastern terminus of the [[Northern Xinjiang railway|Northern Xinjiang (Beijiang)]] and the [[Second \u00dcr\u00fcmqi\u2013Jinghe railway]]. The Beijiang and the Lanxin Lines form part of the [[Eurasian Land Bridge|Trans-Eurasian Continental Railway]], which runs from [[Rotterdam]] through the [[Dzungarian Gate|Alataw Pass]] on the Kazakhstan border to \u00dcr\u00fcmqi and on to Lanzhou and [[Lianyungang]].\n\n=== Road ===\n\n* [[China National Highway 216]]\n* [[China National Highway 312]]\n* [[China National Highway 314]]\n\nMany roads to the north and west typically shut down by early October, remaining closed until the end of winter.\n\n=== Metro ===\nThe [[\u00dcr\u00fcmqi Metro]] opened in 25 October 2018, when the northern section of Line 1 was opened to the public. The southern section of Line 1 opened on 28 June 2019.<ref name=Line1a>{{cite web|url=https://mp.weixin.qq.com/s/msdsH_DrMgRNMDE5l0GiJw|title=\u901a\u5357\u5f7b\u5317\u5c55\u901a\u9014 \u4e4c\u9c81\u6728\u9f50\u5730\u94c1\u4e0e\u60a8\u9010\u68a6\u540c\u884c|date=2019-06-27|url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190627120117/https://mp.weixin.qq.com/s/msdsH_DrMgRNMDE5l0GiJw |archive-date=2019-06-27}}</ref> Line 1 runs between [[\u00dcr\u00fcmqi Diwopu International Airport]] and Santunbei in downtown \u00dcr\u00fcmqi, with a total length of {{convert|27.615|km|1|abbr=on}} and 21 stations.<ref name=Line1a /><ref name=Line1Length>{{cite web|title=\u4e4c\u9c81\u6728\u9f50\u5730\u94c11\u53f7\u7ebf\u5317\u6bb5\u7a7a\u8f7d\u8bd5\u8fd0\u884c|url=https://www.kanzhun.com/news/122618.html|date=2018-04-18|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190609051438/https://www.kanzhun.com/news/122618.html|archive-date=2019-06-09}}</ref> It is fully underground.<ref name=U1length>{{cite web|url=http://www.bjgdjs.com/html/2019-09/797.html|title=28\u65e5\uff0c\u4eac\u7586\u5408\u4f5c\u7684\u4e4c\u9c81\u6728\u9f50\u8f68\u9053\u4ea4\u901a1\u53f7\u7ebf\u5168\u7ebf\u5f00\u901a\u8bd5\u8fd0\u8425|date=2019-09-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191106163139/http://www.bjgdjs.com/html/2019-09/797.html|archive-date=2019-11-06|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nThe planned system consists of 7 lines totaling {{convert|211|km|0|abbr=on}} in length. The first two lines, Line 1 and Line 2 will be constructed with an estimated cost of 31.24 billion yuan.<ref>{{cite web|script-title=zh:\u65b0\u7586\u4e4c\u9c81\u6728\u9f50\u5e02\u6295\u8d44312.4\u4ebf\u5143\u5efa\u8bbe\u4e24\u6761\u8f68\u9053\u4ea4\u901a  |url=http://www.tianshannet.com.cn/news/content/2012-04/20/content_6764912.htm|publisher=[[Tianshannet]] |accessdate=24 October 2012|date=20 April 2012|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190406013651/http://news.ts.cn/content/2012-04/20/content_6764912.htm|archive-date=2019-04-06}}</ref>\n\n=== Bus rapid transit ===\nThe [[\u00dcr\u00fcmqi BRT]] bus service was launched in August 2011 after an investment of 930 million yuan in an effort to improve urban traffic.<ref>{{cite web\n  |url=http://english.cntv.cn/20110829/108853.shtml\n  |title=NW China's Xinjiang launches BRT bus service CCTV News \u2013 CNTV English\n  |publisher=CNTV\n  |date=\n  |accessdate=17 February 2012\n}}</ref> There are currently 9 routes operated, BRT1, BRT2, BRT3, BRT4, BRT5, BRT 6, its branch BRT 61, BRT 7, and its branch BRT 71.<ref>{{cite web\n |url          = http://www.chinabrt.org/en/cities/urumqi.aspx\n |title        = Urumqi BRT\n |publisher    = chinabrt.org\n |date         = \n |access-date   = 17 February 2012\n |archive-url  = https://web.archive.org/web/20120318190156/http://www.chinabrt.org/en/cities/urumqi.aspx\n |archive-date = 18 March 2012\n |url-status     = dead\n |df           = dmy-all\n}}</ref>\n\n== Media ==\nThe [[Xinjiang Networking Transmission Limited]] operates the [[Urumqi People's Broadcasting Station|\u00dcr\u00fcmqi People's Broadcasting Station]] and the [[Xinjiang People Broadcasting Station]], broadcasting in the [[Standard Chinese|Mandarin]], [[Uyghur language|Uyghur]], [[Kazakh language|Kazakh]], [[Mongolian language|Mongolian]], Russian and the [[Kyrgyz language|Kyrgyz]] languages.\n\nThe [[Xinjiang Television Station]] (XJTV), located in \u00dcr\u00fcmqi, is the major TV broadcasting station in the [[Xinjiang Uyghur Autonomous Region]]. The local television station for \u00dcr\u00fcmqi city is [[\u00dcr\u00fcmqi Television Station]] (UTV)(\u4e4c\u9c81\u6728\u9f50\u7535\u89c6\u53f0).\n\n== Sport ==\n* [[Xinjiang Flying Tigers]] is a basketball team that is part of the [[Chinese Basketball Association]], based in \u00dcr\u00fcmqi, Xinjiang. Its corporate sponsor is Xinjiang Guanghui Group.\n* [[Xinjiang Tianshan Leopard F.C.]] is a local football team in the [[China League One]].\n\nChina started a [[bandy]] development programme by organising educational days in \u00dcr\u00fcmqi in June 2009.<ref>[https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:Gf8LNSHMc8IJ:www.internationalbandy.com/download.do?ug%3DAdministrator%26f%3DChina%2520on%2520the%2520way%2520into%2520the%2520Bandy%2520family.doc+altry+xiang+bandy&hl=en&gl=uk&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEESibsk1eA0Ea6KGTzWE_FNhq1Najd02L5kKOnBmUgS_J7SF2Koqn_tgL15k1lAfLmPe5DFZJWkONS49X21fGMQOA6qgkEUkPd0h07WMeAvkzyYFUnvu-jTaCD54bB87rEU5ncAJd&sig=AHIEtbTkBxDi70IsFNCXSFFYoMJDzRz1mA&pli=1 China on the way into the bandy family]</ref>\n\nIn 2015 an indoor [[speed skating]] arena was opened.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.speedskatingnews.info/en/data/rink/CHUQ/|title=Xinjiang Ice Sports Center (CHUQ) \u2013 Rink \u2013 SpeedSkatingNews}}</ref>\n\n== Twin towns and sister cities ==\n{{See also|List of twin towns and sister cities in China}}\n{{More citations needed section|date=May 2015}}\n\u00dcr\u00fcmqi is [[Twin towns and sister cities|twinned]] with:\n{| class=\"wikitable\" border=\"1\" style=\"font-size:100%; background:#FFFFEF; float:left;\"\n|-\n! City\n! Region\n! Country\n|-\n| [[Malaybalay]]\n| [[File:Flag of Bukidnon.png|24px]] [[Bukidnon]]\n| {{flagu|Philippines}}\n|-\n| [[Salt Lake City]]\n| {{flag|Utah}}\n| {{flagu|United States}}\n|-\n| [[Osan]]\n| [[Gyeonggi]]\n| {{flagu|South Korea}}\n|-\n| [[Peshawar]]\n| [[File:Flag of Khyber Pakhtunkhwa.svg|24px]] [[Khyber Pakhtunkhwa]]\n| {{flagu|Pakistan}}\n|-\n| [[Dushanbe]]\n| [[Districts of Republican Subordination]]\n| {{flagu|Tajikistan}}\n|-\n| [[Klang (city)|Klang]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.hongshannet.cn/wlmqG/Intr/Twin/201408/t20140828_246899.html|title=Twin Towns and Sister Cities (Abroad)|author=Yi Yanjun|publisher=Hong Shan|date=2 September 2014|access-date=21 December 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151221034748/http://en.hongshannet.cn/wlmqG/Intr/Twin/201408/t20140828_246899.html|archive-date=21 December 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n| {{flag|Selangor}}\n| {{flagu|Malaysia}}\n|-\n| [[Bishkek]]\n| [[File:Flag of Chuy Province.svg|24px]] [[Chuy Province]]\n| {{flagu|Kyrgyzstan}}\n|-\n| [[Almaty]]\n| [[File:Flag of Almaty.svg|24px]] [[Almaty]]{{ref|1|1}}\n| {{flagu|Kazakhstan}}\n|-\n| [[Chelyabinsk]]\n| {{flag|Chelyabinsk Oblast}}\n| {{flagu|Russia}}\n|-\n| [[Mashhad]]\n|[[Razavi Khorasan Province]]\n| {{flagu|Iran}}\n|}\n{{Clear}}\n<small>{{note|1|1}}[[Almaty]] is a state-level city of [[Kazakhstan]]</small>\n\n== References ==\n\n=== Citations ===\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n=== Sources ===\n; Journal article\n* [[Owen Lattimore]]. (1973) \"Return to China's Northern Frontier.\" ''The Geographical Journal'', Vol. 139, No. 2 (Jun. 1973), pp.&nbsp;233\u2013242.\n\n== Further reading ==\n* Zang, Xiaowei. \"[http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/01419870.2011.644313#.Usgvo_sSPOs Ethnic variation in network composition in \u00dcr\u00fcmchi: do state policies matter?].\" ''[[Ethnic and Racial Studies]]''. 2013. Volume 36, Issue 1. DOI: 10.1080/01419870.2011.644313. p.&nbsp;179\u2013198.\n\n== External links ==\n{{sisterlinks|d=Q16959|b=Pinyin/Urumqi|n=Category:\u00dcr\u00fcmqi|voy=Urumqi|c=Urumqi|s=no|q=no|m=no|mw=no|species=no|v=no}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.urumqi.gov.cn/|\u00dcr\u00fcmqi Government official website}}\n\n{{Xinjiang}}\n{{Metropolitan cities of the People's Republic of China}}\n{{Provincial capitals of China}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Urumqi}}\n[[Category:\u00dcr\u00fcmqi| ]]<!--please leave the empty space as standard-->\n[[Category:Populated places along the Silk Road]]\n[[Category:Cities in Central Asia]]\n[[Category:Populated places in Xinjiang]]\n[[Category:Provincial capitals in China]]\n", "name_user": "Bender235", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eQing rule", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/%C3%9Cr%C3%BCmqi"}
